The following data are obtained for a metal subjected to a magnetic field: 
\begin{tabular}{cc} \hline $\boldsymbol{H}($ amperes $/ \mathbf{m})$ & $\boldsymbol{B}\left(\right.$ weber $\left./ \mathbf{m}^{\mathbf{2}}\right)$ \\ \hline 0 & 0 \\ $4 \times 10^5$ & 0.50263 \\ \hline \end{tabular} 
Calculate the relative permeability for this metal.

solution:
We are given the conductivity and mobility of electrons in copper as:
\[
\sigma = 5.97 \times 10^5\ \mathrm{S/cm}, \quad \mu = 32\ \mathrm{cm^2/V \cdot s}
\]

Using the relation:
\[
\sigma = n e \mu \quad \Rightarrow \quad n = \frac{\sigma}{e \mu}
\]

Substituting values (and converting mobility to SI units, \(\mu = 32 \times 10^{-4}\ \mathrm{m^2/V \cdot s}\)):
\[
n = \frac{5.97 \times 10^7\ \mathrm{S/m}}{(1.602 \times 10^{-19}\ \mathrm{C})(32 \times 10^{-4}\ \mathrm{m^2/V \cdot s})}
\approx 1.165 \times 10^{29}\ \mathrm{electrons/m^3}
\]

Now calculate the number of copper atoms per unit volume. Using:
\[
\rho = 8.96\ \mathrm{g/cm^3} = 8960\ \mathrm{kg/m^3}, \quad M = 63.546\ \mathrm{g/mol} = 63.546 \times 10^{-3}\ \mathrm{kg/mol}
\]
\[
N_{\mathrm{A}} = 6.022 \times 10^{23}\ \mathrm{atoms/mol}
\]

Then the number density of Cu atoms is:
\[
n_{\mathrm{Cu}} = \frac{\rho N_{\mathrm{A}}}{M}
= \frac{8960 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23}}{63.546 \times 10^{-3}}
\approx 8.49 \times 10^{28}\ \mathrm{atoms/m^3}
\]

Finally, the number of conduction electrons per Cu atom is:
\[
\frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{Cu}}}
= \frac{1.165 \times 10^{29}}{8.49 \times 10^{28}}
\approx 1.38
\]

The relationship between the band gap energy ($E_{\mathrm{g}}$ in eV) and the wavelength of light ($\lambda$ in micrometers) emitted from an LED can be derived from the equation $E_{\mathrm{g}}=\frac{h c}{\lambda}$, where $h$ is Planck's constant and $c$ is the speed of light. Simplifying this for practical applications, we obtain:

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text{ in } \mathrm{eV}) & =\frac{h c}{\lambda} \\
\lambda(\text{ in } \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{h c}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text{ in } \mathrm{eV})} \\
\therefore \lambda(\text{ in } \mu \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{12.41172 \times 10^{-7}}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text{ in } \mathrm{eV})} \mathrm{m} \times 10^{-6} \mu \mathrm{m} / \mathrm{m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the wavelength of light emitted from an LED is given by:

$$
\lambda(\text{ in } \mu \mathrm{m})=\frac{1.24}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text{ in } \mathrm{eV})} \mu \mathrm{m}
$$

This simplified relationship is widely used in optoelectronic applications to correlate the wavelength of light emitted from LEDs with their band gap energy.

Using Equation ($\lambda(\mathrm{in} \mu \mathrm{m})=\frac{1.24}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\mathrm{in} \mathrm{eV})} \mu \mathrm{m}$), the wavelength of light emitted from the LED can be calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda(\text { in } \mu \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{1.24}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text { in } \mathrm{eV})} \mu \mathrm{m} \\
\therefore \lambda(\text { in } \mu \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{1.24}{3.47} \mu \mathrm{~m}=0.357 \mu \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Converting this value to nanometers gives $0.357 \times 1000=357 \mathrm{~nm}$, which corresponds to the wavelength of UV light.

The conductivity ($\sigma$) is calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma= & \left(1.6 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(10^{13}\right)(8000) \\
& \therefore \sigma=1.28 \times 10^{-3} \Omega^{-1} \cdot \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

The resistivity ($\rho$) is the inverse of conductivity, thus:

$$
\rho = \frac{1}{\sigma} = 781 \Omega \cdot \mathrm{~cm}
$$

This value is much lower than $3.51 \times 10^{8} \Omega \cdot \mathrm{~cm}$, which is the value of resistivity for intrinsic GaAs.

1:
  description: For Si, $E_{\mathrm{g}}$ at 0 K is $1.170 \mathrm{eV}, \alpha=4.73 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}$, and $\beta=636 \mathrm{~K}$. Therefore, the band gap at 300 K is calculated as:
  calculation: $$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{g}} & =E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text { at } T=0 \mathrm{~K})-\frac{\alpha T^{2}}{T+\beta} \\
& =1.170-\frac{\left(4.73 \times 10^{-4}\right)(300)^{2}}{(300+636)} \\
& =1.124 \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$
2:
  description: For GaAs, the $E_{\mathrm{g}}$ at 0 K is $1.519 \mathrm{eV}, \alpha=5.41 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}$, and $\beta=204 \mathrm{~K}$. Therefore, the band gap at 300 K is calculated as:
  calculation: $$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\mathrm{g}} & =1.519-\frac{\left(5.41 \times 10^{-4}\right)(300)^{2}}{(300+204)} \\
& =1.422 \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$
conclusion: Thus, the band gaps of Si and GaAs at 300 K are 1.124 and 1.422 eV, respectively.

Using the Varshni parameters for GaN (see Table), we can show that the band gap of GaN at 300 K is 3.4 eV. For this band gap, the wavelength based on a GaN LED will be

$$
\begin{aligned}
\lambda(\text { in } \mu \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{1.24}{E_{\mathrm{g}}(\text { in } \mathrm{eV})} \mu \mathrm{m} \\
\therefore \lambda(\text { in } \mu \mathrm{m}) & =\frac{1.24}{3.40} \mu \mathrm{~m}=0.365 \mu \mathrm{~m}=365 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

From Equations ($x_{\mathrm{n}}=\left[\left(\frac{2 \varepsilon V_0}{q}\right)\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{a}}}{N_{\mathrm{d}}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{N_{\mathrm{a}}+N_{\mathrm{d}}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}$) and ($x_{\mathrm{p}}=\left[\left(\frac{2 \varepsilon V_0}{q}\right)\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{d}}}{N_{\mathrm{a}}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{N_{\mathrm{a}}+N_{\mathrm{d}}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}$),

\[
\begin{aligned}
X_{\mathrm{n}} &= \left[\left(\frac{2 \times 11.8 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-14}~\mathrm{F/cm} \times 0.757~\mathrm{V}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19}~\mathrm{C}}\right) \left(\frac{10^{17}~\mathrm{atoms/cm^3}}{10^{16}~\mathrm{atoms/cm^3}}\right) \left(\frac{1}{10^{17} + 10^{16}}\right)\right]^{1/2} \\
X_{\mathrm{n}} &= 2.98 \times 10^{-5}~\mathrm{cm} \quad \text{or} \quad 298~\mathrm{nm}
\end{aligned}
\]

The space charge width on the p-side \((X_{\mathrm{p}})\) is given by

\[
X_{\mathrm{p}} = \left[\left(\frac{2 \times 11.8 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-14}~\mathrm{F/cm} \times 0.755~\mathrm{V}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19}~\mathrm{C}}\right) \left(\frac{10^{16}~\mathrm{atoms/cm^3}}{10^{17}~\mathrm{atoms/cm^3}}\right) \left(\frac{1}{10^{17} + 10^{16}}\right)\right]^{1/2}
\]

\[
X_{\mathrm{p}} = 2.98 \times 10^{-6}~\mathrm{cm} \quad \text{or} \quad 29.8~\mathrm{nm}
\]

Because of the higher dopant concentration, the penetration depth on the p-side \((X_{\mathrm{p}})\) is smaller.

3. The total width of the depletion layer \((w)\) will be \(w = 298 + 29.8 = 327.8~\mathrm{nm}\).

From Equation ($T \approx \exp \left(-\frac{4 \sqrt{2 m_{\mathrm{e}}^*} E_{\mathrm{g}}^{3 / 2}}{21 q \hbar E}\right)$), the probability of tunneling is given by

\[
T = \exp \left( 
\frac{
-4 \sqrt{2 \left(0.02 \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31}~\mathrm{kg} \right)} 
\left( 0.4~\mathrm{eV} \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19}~\mathrm{J/eV} \right)^{3/2}
}{
3 \left(1.6 \times 10^{-19}~\mathrm{C} \right) \left(1.05 \times 10^{-34}~\mathrm{J \cdot s} \right) 
\left( 3 \times 10^{4}~\mathrm{V/cm} \times 10^{2}~\mathrm{cm/m} \right)
}
\right)
\]

Note the use of SI units, including the conversion of the electric field from \(\mathrm{V/cm}\) to \(\mathrm{V/m}\).

\[
T = 2.82 \times 10^{-4}
\]

which is greater than \(10^{-6}\). Therefore, Zener tunneling is important for this value of the electric field in InAs.

From Figure, the ionic polarizability of $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ ions is $2.01 \AA^{3}$. The ionic polarizabilities of lithium ($\mathrm{Li}^{+}$) and silicon ($\mathrm{Si}^{4+}$) ions are $1.20 \AA^{3}$ and $0.87 \AA^{3}$, respectively. Thus, the dielectric polarizability ($\alpha_{D}^{\top}$) of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{SiO}_{3}$ is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha_{\mathrm{O}}^{\top} \text{ Lithium silicate } & =2 \alpha_{\mathrm{i}(+1)}+\alpha_{\mathrm{s}(+4)}+3 \alpha_{\mathrm{c}(-2)} \\
& =2(1.2)+0.87+3(2.01)=9.3 \AA^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

The molar volume of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{SiO}_{3}$ is $V_{\mathrm{m}}=59.01 \AA^{3}$. Therefore, using Equation, the calculated dielectric constant ($\varepsilon_{\mathrm{r}, \mathrm{cal}}$) of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{SiO}_{3}$ is

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \varepsilon_{\mathrm{r}, \mathrm{cal}}=\frac{3 V_{\mathrm{m}}+8 \pi \alpha_{\mathrm{O}}^{\top}}{3 V_{\mathrm{m}}-4 \pi \alpha_{\mathrm{O}}^{\top}} \\
& \varepsilon_{\mathrm{r}, \mathrm{cal}}=\frac{(3 \times 59.01)+8 \pi(9.3)}{(3 \times 59.01)-4 \pi(9.3)}=6.82
\end{aligned}
$$

The average atomic weight of silicon $\left(\bar{A}{\mathrm{Si}}\right)$ is computed by adding fraction-of-\frac{occurrence}{atomic} weight products for the three isotopes-i.e., using Equation ($\bar{A}_{\mathrm{M}}=\sum_i f_{i_{\mathrm{M}}} \mathrm{A}_{i_{\mathrm{M}}}$). (Remember: fraction of occurrence is equal to the percent of occurrence divided by 100.) Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
\bar{A}{\mathrm{Si}}=f{28 \mathrm{Si}} A{28 \mathrm{Si}}+f{29 \mathrm{Si}} A{29 \mathrm{Si}}+f{30 \mathrm{Si}} A{30 \mathrm{Si}} \\
=(0.9223)(27.9769 \mathrm{amu})+(0.0468)(28.9765 \mathrm{amu})+(0.0309)(29.9738 \mathrm{amu})=28.0854 \mathrm{amu}
\end{gathered}
$$

The average atomic weight of zinc $\bar{A}{\mathrm{Zn}}$ is computed by adding fraction-of-occurrence-atomic weight products for the five isotopes-i.e., using Equation ($\bar{A}_{\mathrm{M}}=\sum_i f_{i_{\mathrm{M}}} \mathrm{A}_{i_{\mathrm{M}}}$). (Remember: fraction of occurrence is equal to the percent of occurrence divided by 100.) Thus

$$
\bar{A}{\mathrm{Zn}}=f{\mathrm{sd} \mathrm{Zn}} A{\mathrm{sd} \mathrm{Zn}}+f{\mathrm{sg}{\mathrm{Zn}}} A{\mathrm{sg}{\mathrm{Zn}}}+f{\mathrm{s} 1{\mathrm{Zn}}} A{\mathrm{s} 2{\mathrm{Zn}}}+f{\mathrm{sg}{\mathrm{Zn}}} A{\mathrm{sg}{\mathrm{Zn}}}+f{1{\mathrm{Zn}{\mathrm{Zn}}}} A{\mathrm{sg}{\mathrm{Zn}}}
$$

Including data provided in the problem statement we solve for $\bar{A}{\mathrm{Zn}}$ as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\bar{A}{\mathrm{Zn}}=(0.4863)(63.929 \mathrm{amu})+(0.2790)(65.926 \mathrm{amu}) \\
+(0.0410)(66.927 \mathrm{amu})+(0.1875)(67.925 \mathrm{amu})+(0.0062)(69.925 \mathrm{amu}) \\
=65.400 \mathrm{amu}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) In order to determine the number of grams in one amu of material, appropriate manipulation of the \frac{amu}{atom}, $\mathrm{g} / \mathrm{mol}$, and atom $/ \mathrm{mol}$ relationships is all that is necessary, as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\# \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{amu}=\left(\frac{1 \mathrm{~mol}}{6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms }}\right)\left(\frac{1 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{1 \mathrm{amu} / \text { atom }}\right) \\
=1.66 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{amu}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Since there are $453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}$,

$$
\begin{gathered}
1 \mathrm{lb}-\mathrm{mol}=\left(453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{g}-\mathrm{mol}\right) \\
=2.73 \times 10^{26} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{lb}-\mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) The force of attraction $F{A}$ is calculated using Equation ($\begin{aligned} F_A & =\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N} \cdot \mathrm{~m}^2\right)\left(\left|Z_1\right|\right)\left(\left|Z_2\right|\right)}{r^2}\end{aligned}$) taking the interionic separation $r$ to be $r{0}$ the equilibrium separation distance. This value of $r{0}$ is the sum of the atomic radii of the $\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{F}^{-}$ions (per Equation $r_0=r_{\mathrm{K}^{+}}+r_{\mathrm{Br}^{-}}$)-that is

$$
\begin{gathered}
r{0}=r{\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}}+r{\mathrm{F}^{-}} \\
=0.072 \mathrm{~nm}+0.133 \mathrm{~nm}=0.205 \mathrm{~nm}=0.205 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}
\end{gathered}
$$

We may now compute $F{A}$ using Equation ($\begin{aligned} F_A &=\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N} \cdot \mathrm{~m}^2\right)\left(\left|Z_1\right|\right)\left(\left|Z_2\right|\right)}{r^2}\end{aligned}$). If was assume that ion 1 is $\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$ and ion 2 is $\mathrm{F}^{-}$then the respective charges on these ions are $Z{1}=Z{\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}}=+2$, whereas $Z{2}=Z{\mathrm{F}^{-}}=-1$. Therefore, we determine $F{A}$ as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
F{A}=\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N}-\mathrm{m}^{2}\right)\left(\left|Z{1}\right|\right)\left(\left|Z{2}\right|\right)}{r{0}^{2}} \\
=\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N}-\mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(|+2|)(|-1|)}{\left(0.205 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}} \\
=1.10 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~N}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) At the equilibrium separation distance the sum of attractive and repulsive forces is zero according to Equation ($F_A+F_R=0$). Therefore

$$
\begin{gathered}
F{R}=-F{A} \\
=-\left(1.10 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~N}\right)=-1.10 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~N}
\end{gathered}
$$

To begin, let us rewrite Equation ($r_0=r_{\mathrm{K}^{+}}+r_{\mathrm{Br}^{-}}$) to read as follows:

$$
r{0}=r{\mathrm{C}}+r{\mathrm{A}}
$$

in which $r{\mathrm{C}}$ and $r{\mathrm{A}}$ represent, respectively, the radii of the cation and anion. Thus, this problem calls for us to determine the value of $r{\mathrm{A}}$. However, before this is possible, it is necessary to compute the value of $r{0}$ using Equation ($\begin{aligned} F_A & =\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N} \cdot \mathrm{~m}^2\right)\left(\left|Z_1\right|\right)\left(\left|Z_2\right|\right)}{r^2}\end{aligned}$), and replacing the parameter $r$ with $r{0}$. Solving this expression for $r{0}$ leads to the following:

$$
r{0}=\sqrt{\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N}-\mathrm{m}^{2}\right)\left(\left[Z{\mathrm{C}}\right]\right)\left(\left[Z{\mathrm{A}}\right]\right)}{F{A}}}
$$

Here $Z{\mathrm{C}}$ and $Z{\mathrm{A}}$ represent charges on the cation and anion, respectively. Furthermore, inasmuch as both ion are divalent means that $Z{\mathrm{C}}=+2$ and $Z{\mathrm{A}}=-2$. The value of $r{0}$ is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
r{0}= & \sqrt{\frac{\left(2.31 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~N}-\mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(|+2|)(|-2|)}{1.67 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~N}}} \\
& =0.235 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}=0.235 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the version of Equation ($r_0=r_{\mathrm{K}^{+}}+r_{\mathrm{Br}^{-}}$) given above, and incorporating this value of $r{0}$ and also the value of $r{\mathrm{C}}$ given in the problem statement $(0.080 \mathrm{~nm})$ it is possible to solve for $r{\mathrm{A}}$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
r{\mathrm{A}}=r{0}-r{\mathrm{C}} \\
=0.235 \mathrm{~nm}-0.080 \mathrm{~nm}=0.155 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

Lead has an FCC crystal structure and, as given in the problem statement, an atomic radius of 0.1750 nm . The FCC unit cell volume may be computed from Equation ($V_C=16 R^3 \sqrt{2}$) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=16 R^{3} \sqrt{2}=(16)\left(0.175 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3} \sqrt{2} \\
=1.213 \times 10^{-28} \mathrm{~m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for a computation of the density of molybdenum. According to Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$)

$$
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Mo}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

For $\mathrm{BCC}, n=2$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell. Furthermore, because $V{C}=a^{3}$, and $a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}$, then

$$
V{C}=\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{3}
$$

Thus, realizing that $A{\mathrm{Mo}}=95.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$, using the above version of Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), we compute the theoretical density for Mo as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Mo}}}{\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{(2 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(95.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left[(4)\left(0.1363 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} / \sqrt{3}\right]^{3} /(\text { unit cell })\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=10.22 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

According to Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$)

$$
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Sr}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

For FCC, $n=4$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell. Furthermore, because $V{C}=a^{3}$, and $a=2 R \sqrt{2}$, then

$$
V{C}=(2 R \sqrt{2})^{3}
$$

Thus, realizing that $A{\mathrm{Sr}}=87.62 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$, using the above version of Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), we compute the theoretical density of Sr as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Sr}}}{(2 R \sqrt{2})^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
& =\frac{\text { (4 \frac{atoms}{unit} cell) }(87.62 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left[(2)\left(0.215 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}(\sqrt{2})\right] /(\text { unit cell) }\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
& =2.59 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

We are asked to determine the radius of a palladium atom, given that Pd has an FCC crystal structure. For FCC, $n=4$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell, and $V{C}=16 R^{3} \sqrt{2}$. Now, the density of Pd may be expressed using a form of Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Pd}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Pd}}}{\left(16 R^{3} \sqrt{2}\right) N{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Solving for $R$ from the above expression yields

$$
R=\left(\frac{n A{\mathrm{Pd}}}{16 \rho N{\mathrm{A}} \sqrt{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}
$$

Incorporation into this expression values for $A{\mathrm{Pd}}, n$, and $\rho$ leads to the following value of $R$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
=\left[\frac{\left(4 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }\right)(106.4 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{(16)\left(12.0 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)(\sqrt{2})}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
=1.38 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}=0.138 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is possible to compute the radius of a Ta atom using a rearranged form of Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$). For BCC, $n=2$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell. Furthermore, because $V{C}=a^{3}$ and $a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}$ an expression for the BCC unit cell volume is as follows:

$$
V{C}=\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{3}=\frac{64 R^{3}}{3 \sqrt{3}}
$$

For Ta, Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) takes the form

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Ta}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Ta}}}{\left(\frac{64 R^{3}}{3 \sqrt{3}}\right) N{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Solving for $R$ in this equation yields

$$
R=\left(\frac{3 n A{\mathrm{Ta}} \sqrt{3}}{64 \rho N{\mathrm{A}}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}
$$

Upon incorporation of values of $n, A{\mathrm{Ta}}$, and $\rho$ into this equation leads to the atomic radius of Ta as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\left[\frac{(3)(2 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(180.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})(\sqrt{3})}{(64)\left(16.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
=1.43 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}=0.143 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

