c=1.624 a=(1.624)(0.321 \mathrm{~nm})=0.521 \mathrm{~nm}
$$

In order to determine whether Nb has an FCC or a BCC crystal structure, we need to compute its density for each of the crystal structures. For FCC, $n=4$, and $a=2 R \sqrt{2}$. Also, from  figure 2.8 , its atomic weight is $92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Thus, for FCC

$$
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{a^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{(2 R \sqrt{2})^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

$$
=\frac{(4 \text { atoms } / \text { unit cell })(92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left\{[(2)\left(1.43 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)(\sqrt{2})]^{3} /(\text { unit cell })\right\}(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol})}
$$

$$
=9.33 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
$$

For $\mathrm{BCC}, n=2$, and $a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}$, thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{a^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{(2 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left\{\left[\frac{(4)\left(1.43 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)}{\sqrt{3}}\right]^{3} /(\text { unit cell })\right\}(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol})} \\
=8.57 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

which is the value provided in the problem statement. Therefore, Nb has the BCC crystal structure.

In order to determine the APF for U , we need to compute both the unit cell volume $\left(V{C}\right)$ which is just the product of the three unit cell parameters, as well as the total sphere volume $\left(V{S}\right)$ which is just the product of the volume of a single sphere and the number of spheres in the unit cell $(n)$. The value of $n$ may be calculated from a rearranged form of Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=\frac{\rho V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}{A{\mathrm{U}}} \\
=\frac{\left(19.05 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)(2.86)(5.87)(4.95)\left(\times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}{238.03 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=4.01 \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{unit} \mathrm{cell}
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, we determine the atomic packing factor using Equation ($\mathrm{APF}=\frac{\text { volume of atoms in a unit cell }}{\text { total unit cell volume }}$) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{APF}=\frac{V{S}}{V{C}}=\frac{(4)\left(\frac{4}{3} \pi R^{3}\right)}{(a)(b)(c)} \\
=\frac{(4)\left[\frac{4}{3}(\pi)\left(1.385 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}\right]}{(2.86)(5.87)(4.95)\left(\times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)}\\
=0.536
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) For indium, and from the definition of the APF ($\mathrm{APF}=\frac{\text { volume of atoms in a unit cell }}{\text { total unit cell volume }}$) is

$$
\mathrm{APF}=\frac{V{X}}{V{C}}=\frac{n\left(\frac{4}{3} \pi R^{3}\right)}{a^{2} c}
$$

we may solve for the number of atoms per unit cell, $n$, as

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=\frac{(\mathrm{APF}) a^{2} c}{\frac{4}{3} \pi R^{3}} \\
=\frac{(0.693)(4.59)^{2}(4.95)\left(10^{-24} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)}{\frac{4}{3} \pi\left(1.625 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}} \\
=4.0 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) In order to compute the density, we just employ Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{In}}}{a^{2} c N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{(4 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(114.82 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left[\left(4.59 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{2}\left(4.95 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right) / \text { unit cell }\right]\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=7.31 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) We are asked to calculate the unit cell volume for Be. The volume of an HCP unit cell is provided by Equation as follows:

$$
V{C}=6 R^{2} c \sqrt{3}
$$

But, $c=1.568 a$, and $a=2 R$, or $c=(1.568)(2 R)=3.136 R$. Substitution of this expression for $c$ into the above equation leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=(6)(3.14) R^{3} \sqrt{3} \\
=(6)(3.14)(\sqrt{3})\left[0.1143 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~cm}\right]^{3}=4.87 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The theoretical density of Be is determined, using Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), as follows:

$$
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Be}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

For HCP, $n=6$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell, and for $\mathrm{Be}, A{\mathrm{Be}}=9.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ (as noted inside the front cover)—and the value of $V{C}$ was determined in part (a). Thus, the theoretical density of Be is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{(6 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(9.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left(4.87 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=1.84 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for us to compute the atomic radius for Mg. In order to do this we must use Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), as well as the expression that relates the atomic radius to the unit cell volume for HCP-Equation ($\begin{aligned} V_C & =6 R^2 c \sqrt{3}\end{aligned}$)-that is

$$
V{C}=6 R^{2} c \sqrt{3}
$$

In this case $c=1.624 a$, but, for HCP, $a=2 R$, which means that

$$
V{C}=6 R^{2}(1.624)(2 R) \sqrt{3}=(1.624)(12 \sqrt{3}) R^{3}
$$

And from Equation ($\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), the density is equal to

$$
\rho=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Mg}}}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n A{\mathrm{Mg}}}{(1.624)(12 \sqrt{3}) R^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

And, solving for $R$ from the above equation leads to the following:

$$
R=\left[\frac{n A{\mathrm{Mg}}}{(1.624)(12 \sqrt{3}) \rho N{\mathrm{A}}}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}}
$$

For the HCP crystal structure, $n=6$ and from the inside cover, the atomic weight of Mg is $24.31 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Upon incorporation of these values as well as the density of Mg provided in the problem statement, we compute magnesium's atomic radius as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\left[\frac{(6 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(24.31 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{(1.624)(12 \sqrt{3})\left(1.74 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
=1.60 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}=0.160 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we calculate the unit cell volume for Co , which has an HCP crystal structure. In order to do this, it is necessary to use Equation-an expression for the volume of an HCP unit cell in terms of the atomic radius $R$ and the lattice parameter - that is

$$
V{C}=6 R^{2} c \sqrt{3}
$$

The problem states that $c=1.623 a$; also, it is the case for HCP that $a=2 R$. Making these substitutions into the previous equation yields

$$
V{C}=(1.623)(12 \sqrt{3}) R^{3}
$$

And incorporation of the value of $R$ provided in the problem statement leads to the following value for the unit cell volume:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& V{C}=(1.623)(12 \sqrt{3})\left(1.253 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} \\
& =6.64 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}=6.64 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~nm}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

question:
Calculate the theoretical density of NiO, given that it has the rock salt crystal structure. The ionic radii of $\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ are 0.069 nm and 0.140 nm.

Reference:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum A{\mathrm{Ni}}=A{\mathrm{Ni}}=58.69 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& \sum A{\mathrm{O}}=A{\mathrm{O}}=16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

solution:
This density of NiO may be computed using Equation ($\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), which for this problem, is of the form

$$
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A{\mathrm{Ni}}+\sum A{\mathrm{O}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

But because the formula unit is "NiO" then, using the atomic weights of Ni and O

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum A{\mathrm{Ni}}=A{\mathrm{Ni}}=58.69 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& \sum A{\mathrm{O}}=A{\mathrm{O}}=16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

This means that, for this problem, Equation ($\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) becomes the following:

$$
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(A{\mathrm{Ni}}+A{\mathrm{O}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

Since the crystal structure is rock salt, $n^{\prime}=4$ formula units per unit cell (because the rock salt crystal structure consists of two interpenetrating FCC structures - in this case, one for $\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}$ ions; the other for the and $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ ions). At this point it becomes necessary to determine the value of the unit cell volume $V{C}$. Because the unit cell has cubic symmetry, $V{C}$ and the unit cell edge length $a$ are related as

$$
$V{C}=a^{3}$
$$

For the rock salt crystal structure, that $a$, the unit cell edge length is related (in this case) to the ionic radii of Ni and O ions ( $r{\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}}$ and $r{\mathrm{O}^{2-}}$, respectively) as follows:

$$
a=2 r{\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}}+2 r{\mathrm{O}^{2-}}
$$

Which means that

$$
V{C}=a^{3}=\left(2 r{\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}}+2 r{\mathrm{O}^{2-}}\right)^{3}
$$

The ionic radii of $\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ are 0.069 nm and 0.140 nm , respectively. Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=\left(2 r{\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}}+2 r{\mathrm{O}^{2-}}\right)^{3}=[2(0.069 \mathrm{~nm})+2(0.140 \mathrm{~nm})]^{3} \\
=0.0730 \frac{\mathrm{~nm}^{3}}{\text { unit cell }}=\left(0.0730 \frac{\mathrm{~nm}^{3}}{\text { unit cell }}\right)\left(\frac{1 \mathrm{~cm}}{10^{7} \mathrm{~nm}}\right)^{3} \\
=7.30 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

Finally, it is possible for us to compute the density of NiO incorporating Avogadro's number and values of the other parameters in Equation ($\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(A_{\mathrm{Ni}}+A_{\mathrm{O}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{(4 \text { formula \frac{units}{unit} cell })(58.69 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left(7.30 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { formula units } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=6.80 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

question:
Iron oxide (FeO) has the rock salt crystal structure and a density of $5.70 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, determine the unit cell edge length.

Reference:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum A{\mathrm{Fe}}=A{\mathrm{Fe}}=55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& \sum A{\mathrm{O}}=A{\mathrm{O}}=16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

solution:
We are asked to compute the density of CsCl . To solve this problem it is necessary to use Equation-namely

$$
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum \mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cs}}+\sum \mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cl}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

But because the formula unit is "CsCl" then

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum \mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cs}}=\mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cs}}=132.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& \sum \mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cl}}=\mathcal{A}{\mathrm{Cl}}=35.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, in order to compute the unit cell volume, $V{C}$, we make use of the result of Problem 3.3. This problem asks for us to confirm, for the BCC crystal structure, the equation that relates the unit cell edge length (a) and the atomic radius $(R)$-that is

$$
a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}
$$

For this demonstration in Problem 3.3, the " $4 R$ " in this equation is the length of a cube diagonal. For the CsCl crystal structure, this cube diagonal length is equal to $2 r{\mathrm{Cs}}+2 r{\mathrm{Cl}}$ where

$$
\begin{aligned}
& r{\mathrm{Cs}^{\prime}}=\text { the radius of a Cs ion }=0.170 \mathrm{~nm}(\text {  table 3.4 ) } \\
& r{\mathrm{Cl}^{\prime}}=\text { the radius of a Cl ion }=0.181 \mathrm{~nm}(\text {  table 3.4 ) }
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the modified form of Equation ($a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}$) (above) is

$$
a=\frac{2 r{\mathrm{Cs}^{\prime}}+2 r{\mathrm{Cl}}}{\sqrt{3}}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{2(0.170 \mathrm{~nm})+2(0.181 \mathrm{~nm})}{\sqrt{3}} \\
& =0.405 \mathrm{~nm}=4.05 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the unit cell volume, $V{C}=a^{3}$, and for the CsCl crystal structure, $n^{\prime}=1$ formula \frac{unit}{unit} cell, we solve for the density of CsCl using Equation ($\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{Cs}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{Cl}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}$) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(A{\mathrm{Cs}}+A{\mathrm{Cl}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(A{\mathrm{Cs}}+A{\mathrm{Cl}}\right)}{a^{3} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
\rho=\frac{(1 \text { formula \frac{unit}{unit} cell })(132.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+35.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left(4.05 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} / \text { unit cell }\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { formula units } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=4.21 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we compute the density of $\mathrm{CaF}{2}$. In order to solve this problem it is necessary to use equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), which for our problem takes the form:

$$
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A{\mathrm{Ca}}+\sum A{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

But because the formula unit is " $\mathrm{CaF}{2}$ " then

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sum A{\mathrm{Ca}}=A{\mathrm{Ca}}=40.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
\sum A{\mathrm{F}}=2 A{\mathrm{F}}=(2)(19.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=38.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now necessary to determine the unit cell volume, $V{C}$. A unit cell of the fluorite structure is shown in  figure 3.9 . It may be seen that there are four $\mathrm{CaF}{2}$ units per unit cell (i.e., $n^{\prime}=4$ formula \frac{units}{unit} cell). For each of the eight small cubes (or sub-cells) in the unit cell (as demonstrated in the solution to Problem 3.34), the sub-cell edge length $a$ is equal to

$$
a=\frac{2 r{\mathrm{Ca}}^{3+}+2 r{\mathrm{F}^{-}}}{\sqrt{3}}
$$

and, from  table 3.4 

$$
\begin{aligned}
& r{\mathrm{Ca}}^{3+}=0.100 \mathrm{~nm} \\
& r{\mathrm{F}^{-}}=0.133 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore,

$$
a=\frac{2(0.100 \mathrm{~nm})+2(0.133 \mathrm{~nm})}{\sqrt{3}}=0.269 \mathrm{~nm}=2.69 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
$$

And the volume of the unit cell is just

$$
V{C}=(2 a)^{3}=\left[(2)\left(2.69 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~cm}\right)\right]^{3}=1.56 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
$$

Also, from  figure 3.9 , it may be noted that the unit cell is composed of 4 formula units $\left(\mathrm{CaF}{2} \mathrm{~s}\right)$, which means that $n^{\prime}$ in equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{Ca}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) is 4 . Now it is possible to solve for the density of calcium fluoride using equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{Ca}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) as follows:

$$
\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(A{\mathrm{Ca}}+2 A{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

$$
=\frac{(4 \text { formula \frac{units}{unit} cell })[40.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+(2)(19.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})]}{\left(1.56 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { formula units } / \mathrm{mol}\right)}
$$

$$
=3.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
$$

This problem asks us to compute the atomic packing factor for $\mathrm{Fe}{3} \mathrm{O}{4}$ given its density and unit cell edge length. The APF is determined using equation (\mathrm{APF}=\frac{\text { volume of atoms in a unit cell }}{\text { total unit cell volume }}). Computation of the sphere volume is possible by solving for $n^{\prime}$ in equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), from which the number of $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}, \mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$, and $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ ions may be determined; using these values and the atomic radii of these three ion types, $V{S}$ is computed. The unit cell volume is calculated from the unit cell edge length, and realizing that the unit cell is a cube.

Solving for $n^{\prime}$ from equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) leads to

$$
n^{\prime}=\frac{\rho V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}{\sum A{\mathrm{Fe}}+\sum A{\mathrm{O}}}
$$

A formula unit of $\mathrm{Fe}{3} \mathrm{O}{4}$ consists of 3 iron ions and 4 oxygen ions; inasmuch as the atomic weights of iron and oxygen $\left(A{\mathrm{Fe}}\right.$ and $\left.A{\mathrm{O}}\right)$ are $55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ and $16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$, respectively therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \sum A{\mathrm{Fe}}=(3)(55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=167.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& \sum A{\mathrm{O}}=(4)(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=64.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the density value is $5.24 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ (as provided in the problem statement), we calculate $n^{\prime}$ using the above equation as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n^{\prime}=\frac{\rho V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}}{\sum A{\mathrm{Fe}}+\sum A{\mathrm{O}}} \\
=\frac{\left(5.24 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left[\left(8.39 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} / \text { unit cell }\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { formula units } / \mathrm{mol}\right)\right.}{(167.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(64.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})} \\
=8.0 \text { formula \frac{units}{unit} cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, in each $\mathrm{FeO}-\mathrm{Fe}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}$ unit cell there are $8 \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}, 16 \mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$, and $32 \mathrm{O}^{2-}$ ions. From  table 3.4 , $r{\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}}=0.077 \mathrm{~nm}$, $r{\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}}=0.069 \mathrm{~nm}$, and $r{\mathrm{O}^{2-}}=0.140 \mathrm{~nm}$. Thus, the total sphere volume in equation (\mathrm{APF}=\frac{\text { volume of atoms in a unit cell }}{\text { total unit cell volume }}) (which we denote as $V{S}$ ), is the sum of the sphere volume of the $8 \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}, 16 \mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$, and $32 \mathrm{O}^{2-}$ ions as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{S}=(8)\left(\frac{4}{3} \pi\right)\left(7.7 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}+(16)\left(\frac{4}{3} \pi\right)\left(6.9 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} \\
+(32)\left(\frac{4}{3} \pi\right)\left(1.40 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3} \\
=4.05 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

The unit cell volume, $V{C}$, is equal to $a^{3}$ where $a$ is the unit cell edge length ( 0.839 nm as given in the problem statement). Therefore,

$$
V{C}=a^{3}=\left(8.39 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}=5.90 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
$$

Finally, the atomic packing factor (APF) from equation (\mathrm{APF}=\frac{\text { volume of atoms in a unit cell }}{\text { total unit cell volume }}) is just

$$
\mathrm{APF}=\frac{V{S}}{V{C}}=\frac{4.05 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}}{5.90 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}}=0.686
$$

The unit cell shown in the problem statement belongs to the tetragonal crystal system since $a=b=0.35$ $\mathrm{nm}, c=0.45 \mathrm{~nm}$, and $\alpha=\beta=\gamma=90^{\circ}$.
The crystal structure would be called body-centered tetragonal.
As with BCC, $n=2$ \frac{atoms}{unit} cell. Also, for this unit cell

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=\left(3.5 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{2}\left(4.5 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right) \\
=5.51 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, using equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), the density is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A}{V{C} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{(2 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell })(141 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left(5.51 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)}
\end{gathered}
$$

$=8.49 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$

(a) In the figure below is shown a [100] direction within an FCC unit cell.


For this [100] direction there is one atom at each of the two unit cell corners, and, thus, there is the equivalent of 1 atom that is centered on the direction vector. The length of this direction vector is just the unit cell edge length, $2 R \sqrt{2}$ (equation (a=2 R \sqrt{2})). Therefore, using equation (\mathrm{LD}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on direction vector }}{\text { length of direction vector }}), the expression for the linear density of this plane is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{LD}{100}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on }[100] \text { direction vector }}{\text { length of }[100] \text { direction vector }} \\
=\frac{1 \text { atom }}{2 R \sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{2 R \sqrt{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

An FCC unit cell within which is drawn a [111] direction is shown below.


For this [111] direction, the vector shown passes through only the centers of the single atom at each of its ends, and, thus, there is the equivalence of 1 atom that is centered on the direction vector. The length of this direction vector is denoted by $z$ in this figure, which is equal to

$$
z=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}
$$

where $x$ is the length of the bottom face diagonal, which is equal to $4 R$. Furthermore, $y$ is the unit cell edge length, which is equal to $2 R \sqrt{2}$ (equation (a=2 R \sqrt{2})). Thus, using the above equation, the length $z$ may be calculated as follows:

$$
z=\sqrt{(4 R)^{2}+(2 R \sqrt{2})^{2}}=\sqrt{24 R^{2}}=2 R \sqrt{6}
$$

Therefore, using equation (\mathrm{LD}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on direction vector }}{\text { length of direction vector }}), the expression for the linear density of this direction is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{LD}{111}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on }[111] \text { direction vector }}{\text { length of }[111] \text { direction vector }} \\
=\frac{1 \text { atom }}{2 R \sqrt{6}}=\frac{1}{2 R \sqrt{6}}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The atomic radius for copper is 0.128 nm . Therefore, the linear density for the [100] direction is

$$
\mathrm{LD}{100}(\mathrm{Cu})=\frac{1}{2 R \sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{(2)(0.128 \mathrm{~nm}) \sqrt{2}}=2.76 \mathrm{~nm}^{-1}=2.76 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}
$$

While for the [111] direction

$$
\mathrm{LD}{111}(\mathrm{Cu})=\frac{1}{2 R \sqrt{6}}=\frac{1}{(2)(0.128 \mathrm{~nm}) \sqrt{6}}=1.59 \mathrm{~nm}^{-1}=1.59 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}
$$

(a) In the figure below is shown a [110] direction within a BCC unit cell.


For this [110] direction there is one atom at each of the two unit cell corners, and, thus, there is the equivalence of 1 atom that is centered on the direction vector. The length of this direction vector is denoted by $x$ in this figure, which is equal to

$$
x=\sqrt{z^{2}-y^{2}}
$$

where $y$ is the unit cell edge length, which, from equation (a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}) is equal to $\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}$. Furthermore, $z$ is the length of the unit cell diagonal, which is equal to $4 R$. Thus, using the above equation, the length $x$ may be calculated as follows:

$$
x=\sqrt{(4 R)^{2}-\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{2}}=\sqrt{\frac{32 R^{2}}{3}}=4 R \sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}
$$

Therefore, using equation (\mathrm{LD}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on direction vector }}{\text { length of direction vector }}), the expression for the linear density of this direction is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{LD}{110}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on [110] direction vector }}{\text { length of [110] direction vector }} \\
=\frac{1 \text { atom }}{4 R \sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4 R \sqrt{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

A BCC unit cell within which is drawn a [111] direction is shown below.


For although the [111] direction vector shown passes through the centers of three atoms, there is an equivalence of only two atoms associated with this unit cell-one-half of each of the two atoms at the end of the vector, in addition to the center atom belongs entirely to the unit cell. Furthermore, the length of the vector shown is equal to $4 R$, since all of the atoms whose centers the vector passes through touch one another. Therefore, according to equation (\mathrm{LD}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on direction vector }}{\text { length of direction vector }}), the linear density is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{LD}{111}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on [111] direction vector }}{\text { length of [111] direction vector }} \\
=\frac{2 \text { atoms }}{4 R}=\frac{1}{2 R}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The atomic radius for iron is 0.124 nm . Therefore, the linear density for the [110] direction is

$$
\mathrm{LD}{110}(\mathrm{Fe})=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4 R \sqrt{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{(4)(0.124 \mathrm{~nm}) \sqrt{2}}=2.47 \mathrm{~nm}^{-1}=2.47 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}
$$

While for the [111] direction

$$
\mathrm{LD}{111}(\mathrm{Fe})=\frac{1}{2 R}=\frac{1}{(2)(0.124 \mathrm{~nm})}=4.03 \mathrm{~nm}^{-1}=4.03 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}
$$

(a) A (0001) plane for an HCP unit cell is show below.


Each of the 6 perimeter atoms in this plane is shared with three other unit cells, whereas the center atom is shared with no other unit cells; this gives rise to three equivalent atoms belonging to this plane.

In terms of the atomic radius $R$, the area of each of the 6 equilateral triangles that have been drawn is $R^{2} \sqrt{3}$, or the total area of the plane shown is $6 R^{2} \sqrt{3}$. And the planar density for this (0001) plane (equation (\mathrm{PD}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on a plane }}{\text { area of plane }})) is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{PD}{0001}=\frac{\text { number of atoms centered on (0001) plane }}{\text { area of (0001) plane }} \\
=\frac{3 \text { atoms }}{6 R^{2} \sqrt{3}}=\frac{1}{2 R^{2} \sqrt{3}}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The atomic radius for titanium is 0.145 nm . Therefore, the planar density for the (0001) plane is

$$
\mathrm{PD}{0001}(\mathrm{Ti})=\frac{1}{2 R^{2} \sqrt{3}}=\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{3}(0.145 \mathrm{~nm})^{2}}=13.73 \mathrm{~nm}^{-2}=1.373 \times 10^{19} \mathrm{~m}^{-2}
$$

(a) For the crystals having cubic symmetry, $a=b=c$. Making this substitution into the above equation leads to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{d{h k l}^{2}} & =\frac{h^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{k^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{l^{2}}{a^{2}} \\
& =\frac{h^{2}+k^{2}+l^{2}}{a^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

(b) For crystals having tetragonal symmetry, $a=b \neq c$. Replacing $b$ with $a$ in the equation found in the problem statement leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{1}{d{h k l}^{2}}=\frac{h^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{k^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{l^{2}}{c^{2}} \\
=\frac{h^{2}+k^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{l^{2}}{c^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

The volume of a BCC unit cell is calculated using equation (a=\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}) as follows

$$
V_{C}=a^{3}=\left(\frac{4 R}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^{3}=\frac{64 R^{3}}{3 \sqrt{3}}
$$

Now, using equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), we may determine the density as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho=\frac{n A}{V_{C} N_{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{n A}{\left(\frac{64 R^{3}}{3 \sqrt{3}}\right) N_{\mathrm{A}}}=\frac{(3 \sqrt{3}) n A}{64 R^{3} N_{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, from this expression, solving for $R$, leads to

$$
R=\left[\frac{(3 \sqrt{3}) n A}{64 \rho N_{\mathrm{A}}}\right]^{1 / 3}
$$

Since there are two atoms per unit cell $(n=2)$ and incorporating values for the density $(\rho)$ and atomic weight $(A)$ provided in the problem statement, we calculate the value of $R$ as follows:

$$
R=\left[\frac{(3 \sqrt{3})(2 \text { atoms/unit cell })(48.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{(64)\left(7.24 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}\right]^{1 / 3}
$$


$$
=1.22 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}=0.122 \mathrm{~nm}
$$

The density of a ceramic may be calculated using equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), that is,
\begin{equation}
\rho = \frac{n^{\prime} \left( \sum A_{\mathrm{C}} + \sum A_{\mathrm{A}} \right)}{V_{\mathrm{C}} N_{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{equation}

For the rock salt crystal structure, 4 formula units are associated with each unit cell (i.e., $n^{\prime} = 4$). In addition, for this crystal structure, the anions and cations touch each other along the edge of the unit cell; thus, the unit cell edge length $a$ is equal to twice the sum of the cation and anion radii, that is,
\begin{equation}
a = 2 \left( r_{\mathrm{C}} + r_{\mathrm{A}} \right)
\end{equation}

Since the unit cell has cubic symmetry,
\begin{equation}
V_{\mathrm{C}} = a^{3} = \left[ 2 \left( r_{\mathrm{C}} + r_{\mathrm{A}} \right) \right]^3 = 8 \left( r_{\mathrm{C}} + r_{\mathrm{A}} \right)^3
\end{equation}

Making this substitution into equation (\rho=\frac{n^{\prime}\left(\sum A_{\mathrm{C}}+\sum A_{\mathrm{A}}\right)}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) gives:
\begin{equation}
\rho = \frac{n^{\prime} \left( A_{\mathrm{C}} + A_{\mathrm{A}} \right)}{8 \left( r_{\mathrm{C}} + r_{\mathrm{A}} \right)^3 N_{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{equation}

In one formula unit (i.e., one CA unit), there is one C ion and one A ion, which means:
\begin{align}
A_{\mathrm{C}} &= 22.7~\mathrm{g/mol} \\
A_{\mathrm{A}} &= 91.4~\mathrm{g/mol}
\end{align}

Substituting atomic weight values and ionic radii for C and A into the equation leads to:
\begin{equation}
\rho = \frac{4 \times (22.7~\mathrm{g/mol} + 91.4~\mathrm{g/mol})}
{8 \left(1.37 \times 10^{-8}~\mathrm{cm} + 2.41 \times 10^{-8}~\mathrm{cm} \right)^3 \times \left(6.022 \times 10^{23}~\mathrm{formula~units/mol} \right)} = 0.219 g/cm^3
\end{equation}

(a) For polytetrafluoroethylene, each repeat unit consists of two carbon atoms and four fluorine atoms ( table 4.3 ). If $A{\mathrm{C}}$ and $A{\mathrm{F}}$ represent the atomic weights of carbon and fluorine, respectively, then

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=2\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+4\left(A{\mathrm{F}}\right) \\
=(2)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(4)(19.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=100.02 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) For poly(methyl methacrylate), from  table 4.3 , each repeat unit has five carbon atoms, eight hydrogen atoms, and two oxygen atoms. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=5\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+8\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=(5)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(8)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(2)(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=100.11 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(c) For nylon 6,6, from  table 4.3 , each repeat unit has twelve carbon atoms, twenty-two hydrogen atoms, two nitrogen atoms, and two oxygen atoms. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=12\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+22\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{N}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=(12)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(22)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(2)(14.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(2)(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}) \\
=226.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(d) For poly(ethylene terephthalate), from  table 4.3 , each repeat unit has ten carbon atoms, eight hydrogen atoms, and four oxygen atoms. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=10\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+8\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+4\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=(10)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(8)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(4)(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=192.16 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) The repeat unit molecular weight of polypropylene is called for in this portion of the problem. For polypropylene, from  table 4.3 , each repeat unit has three carbon atoms and six hydrogen atoms. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=3\left(A{C}\right)+6\left(A{\Pi}\right) \\
=(3)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(6)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=42.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Because the degree of polymerization is 15,000 , the number-average molecular weight may be computed using a rearranged form of equation (D P=\frac{\bar{M}_n}{m}), as follows:

$$
\bar{M}{n}=(D P) m=(15,000)(42.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=631,200 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
$$

For chlorinated polyethylene, we are asked to determine the weight percent of chlorine added for $8 \% \mathrm{Cl}$ substitution of all original hydrogen atoms. Consider 50 carbon atoms; for polyethylene there are 100 possible sidebonding sites. Ninety-two are occupied by hydrogen and eight are occupied by Cl . Thus, the mass of these 50 carbon atoms, $m{\mathrm{C}}$, is just

$$
m{\mathrm{C}}=50\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)=(50)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=600.5 \mathrm{~g}
$$

Likewise, for hydrogen and chlorine,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m{\mathrm{H}}=92\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)=(92)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=92.74 \mathrm{~g} \\
& m{\mathrm{Cl}}=8\left(A{\mathrm{Cl}}\right)=(8)(35.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=283.60 \mathrm{~g}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the concentration of chlorine, $C{\mathrm{Cl}}$, is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{Cl}}=\frac{m{\mathrm{Cl}}}{m{\mathrm{C}}+m{\mathrm{H}}+m{\mathrm{Cl}}} \times 100 \\
=\frac{283.60 \mathrm{~g}}{600.5 \mathrm{~g}+92.74 \mathrm{~g}+283.60 \mathrm{~g}} \times 100=29.0 \mathrm{wt} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) This portion of the problem asks for us to calculate the number-average molecular weight for a linear polytetrafluoroethylene for which $L$ in equation (L=N d \sin \left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)) is 2000 nm . It is first necessary to compute the value of $N$ using this equation, where, for the $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$ chain bond, $d=0.154 \mathrm{~nm}$, and $\theta=109^{\circ}$ (Section 4.4). Thus, solving equation (L=N d \sin \left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)) for $N$ yields:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N=\frac{L}{d \sin \left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right)} \\
=\frac{2000 \mathrm{~nm}}{(0.154 \mathrm{~nm}) \sin \left(\frac{109^{\circ}}{2}\right)}=15,900
\end{gathered}
$$

Since there are two $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$ bonds per PTFE repeat unit, there is an average of $\frac{N}{2}$ or $15,\frac{900}{2}=7950$ repeat units per chain, which is also the degree of polymerization, $D P$. In order to compute the value of $\bar{M}{n}$ using equation (D P=\frac{\bar{M}_n}{m}), we must first determine $m$ for PTFE. Each PTFE repeat unit consists of two carbon atoms and four fluorine atoms, thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
m=2\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+4\left(A{\mathrm{F}}\right) \\
=(2)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(4)(19.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=100.02 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, using equation (D P=\frac{\bar{M}_n}{m}) and solving for $\bar{M}{n}$ yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
\bar{M}{n}=(D P) m \\
=(7950)(100.02 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=795,000 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Next, we are to determine the number-average molecular weight for $r=15 \mathrm{~nm}$. Solving for $N$ from equation (r=d \sqrt{N}) leads to

$$
N=\frac{r^{2}}{d^{2}}=\frac{(15 \mathrm{~nm})^{2}}{(0.154 \mathrm{~nm})^{2}}=9490
$$

which is the total number of bonds per average molecule. Since there are two $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$ bonds per repeat unit, then $D P$ $=\frac{N}{2}=\frac{9490}{2}=4745$. Now, using equation (D P=\frac{\bar{M}_n}{m}), we calculate the number-average molecular weight as follows:

$$
\bar{M}{\mathrm{n}}=(D P) m=(4745)(100.02 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=474,600 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
$$

This problem asks for us to calculate the number-average molecular weight of a random poly(isobutyleneisoprene) copolymer. The isobutylene repeat unit consists of four carbon atoms and eight hydrogen atoms ( table 4.5 ). Therefore, its repeat unit molecular weight $\left(m{\mathrm{Ib}}\right)$ is

$$
\begin{gathered}
m{\mathrm{Ib}}=4\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+8\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right) \\
=(4)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(8)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=56.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

The isoprene repeat unit is composed of five carbon and eight hydrogen atoms ( table 4.5 ). Thus, its repeat unit molecular weight $\left(m{\mathrm{Ip}}\right)$ is

$$
\begin{gathered}
m{\mathrm{Ip}}=5\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+8\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right) \\
=(5)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(8)(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=68.11 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

From equation (\bar{m}=\sum f_j m_j), the average repeat unit molecular weight is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
\bar{m}=f{\mathrm{Ib}} m{\mathrm{lb}}+f{\mathrm{lp}} m{\mathrm{lp}} \\
=(0.25)(56.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(1-0.25)(68.11 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=65.11 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Since $D P=1500$ (as given in the problem statement), $\bar{M}{n}$ may be computed using a rearranged form of equation (D P=\frac{\bar{M}_n}{m}) as follows:

$$
\bar{M}{n}=\bar{m}(D P)=(65.11 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})(1500)=97,700 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
$$

question:
The density of totally crystalline nylon 6,6 at room temperature is $1.213 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$. Also, at room temperature the unit cell for this material is triclinic with the following lattice parameters:

$$
\begin{array}{rlr}
a & =0.497 \mathrm{~nm} & \alpha=48.4^{\circ} \\
b & =0.547 \mathrm{~nm} & \beta=76.6^{\circ} \\
c & =1.729 \mathrm{~nm} & \gamma=62.5^{\circ}
\end{array}
$$

If the volume of a triclinic unit cell, is a function of these lattice parameters as

$$
V_{\mathrm{tri}}=a b c \sqrt{1-\cos ^{2} \alpha-\cos ^{2} \beta-\cos ^{2} \gamma+2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma}
$$

determine the number of repeat units per unit cell.

solution:
For this problem we are given the density of nylon $6,6\left(1.213 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)$, an expression for the volume of its unit cell, and the lattice parameters, and are asked to determine the number of repeat units per unit cell. This computation necessitates the use of equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), in which we solve for $n$. Before this can be carried out we must first calculate $V_{C}$, the unit cell volume, and $A$ the repeat unit molecular weight. For $V_{C}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
V_{C}=a b c \sqrt{1-\cos ^{2} \alpha-\cos ^{2} \beta-\cos ^{2} \gamma+2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \cos \gamma} \\
=(0.497 \mathrm{~nm})(0.547 \mathrm{~nm})(1.729 \mathrm{~nm}) \sqrt{1-0.441-0.054-0.213+2(0.664)(0.232)(0.462)} \\
=\left(0.3098 \mathrm{~nm}^{3}\right)=\left(0.3098 \mathrm{~nm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{-7} \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{nm}\right)^{3} \\
=3.098 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

From  table 4.3 , the repeat unit for nylon 6,6 has 12 carbon atoms, 22 hydrogen atoms, 2 oxygen atoms and 2 nitrogen atoms. Therefore, the molecular weight for a repeat unit of nylon $6,6\left(M W_{\text {nylon }}\right)$ is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
M W_{\text {nylon }}=12\left(A_{\mathrm{C}}\right)+22\left(A_{\mathrm{H}}\right)+2\left(A_{\mathrm{O}}\right)+2\left(A_{\mathrm{N}}\right) \\
=12(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+22(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+2(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+2(14.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})
\end{gathered}
$$

Finally, solving for $n$ from equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) and incorporating values for $\rho\left(1.213 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right), V_{C}\left(3.098 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)$, and $M W_{\text {nylon }}(226.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})$ leads to the following value for $n$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=\frac{\rho V_{C} N_{\mathrm{A}}}{M W_{\text {nylon }}} \\
=\frac{\left(1.213 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(3.098 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { repeat units } / \mathrm{mol}\right)}{226.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=1 \text { repeat unit/unit cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem is solved using two steps: (1) calculate the total number of lattice sites in silver, $N{\mathrm{Ag}}$, using equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}); and (2) multiply this number by fraction of lattice that are vacant, $2 \times 10^{-6}$. The parameter $N{\mathrm{Ag}}$ is related to the density, $(\rho)$, Avogadro's number $\left(N{\mathrm{A}}\right)$, and the atomic weight $\left(A{\mathrm{Ag}}=107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}\right.$) according to equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Ag}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Ag}}}{A{\mathrm{Ag}}} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(10.35 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=5.78 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

The number of vacancies per meter cubed in silver at $700^{\circ} \mathrm{C}, N{v}$, is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{v}=\left(2 \times 10^{-6}\right) N{\mathrm{Ag}} \\
=\left(2 \times 10^{-6}\right)\left(5.78 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)=1.156 \times 10^{23} \text { vacancies } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem is solved using two steps: (1) calculate the total number of lattice sites in silver, $N$, using equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}), and (2) take the ratio of the equilibrium number of vacancies given in the problem statement ( $N{v}=2.3$ $\times 10^{25} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ ) and this value of $N$. From equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}})

$$
\begin{gathered}
N=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(7.40 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{85.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=5.21 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

The fraction of vacancies is equal to the $N{v} / N$ ratio, which is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{N{v}}{N}=\frac{2.3 \times 10^{25} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}}{5.21 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}} \\
=4.41 \times 10^{-4}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for the computation of the activation energy for vacancy formation in nickel. Upon examination of equation (N_v=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_v}{k T}\right)), all parameters besides $Q{v}$ are given except $N$, the total number of atomic sites. However, $N$ is related to the density, $(\rho)$, Avogadro's number $\left(N{\mathrm{A}}\right)$, and the atomic weight $(A)$ according to equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
N=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Ni}}}{A{\mathrm{Ni}}} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(8.80 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)}{58.69 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=9.03 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}=9.03 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, taking natural logarithms of both sides of equation (N_v=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_v}{k T}\right)) yields the following

$$
\ln N{v}=\ln N-\frac{Q{v}}{k T}
$$

We make $Q{v}$ the dependent variable after some algebraic manipulation as

$$
Q{v}=-k T \ln \left(\frac{N{v}}{N}\right)
$$

Incorporation into this expression, values for $N{v}$ (determined above as $9.03 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}$ ), $N$ (provided in the problem statement, $\left.4.7 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right) . T\left(850^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=1123 \mathrm{~K}\right)$ and $k$, leads to the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
Q{v}=-\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom-K }\right)(1123 \mathrm{~K}) \ln \left(\frac{4.7 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}}{9.03 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}}\right) \\
=1.40 \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom }
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to solve this problem it is necessary to use equation (N_s=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_s}{2 k T}\right)) and solve for the $N{s} / N$ ratio. Rearrangement of equation (N_s=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_s}{2 k T}\right)) and substituting values for temperature and the energy of defect formation $\left(Q{s}\right)$ given in the problem statement leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{N{s}}{N}=\exp \left(-\frac{Q{s}}{2 k T}\right) \\
=\exp \left[-\frac{1.86 \mathrm{eV}}{(2)\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}\right)(645+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=7.87 \times 10^{-6}
\end{gathered}
$$

Solution of this problem is possible using equation (N_{f r}=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_{f r}}{2 k T}\right)). However, we must first determine the value of $N$, the number of lattice sites per cubic meter, which is possible using a modified form of equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{K}}+A_{\mathrm{Cl}}}), which is given as follows:

$$
N=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A{\mathrm{Ag}}+A{\mathrm{Cl}}}
$$

in which $A{\mathrm{Ag}}$ and $A{\mathrm{Cl}}$ are, respectively, the atomic weights of Ag and Cl (i.e., $107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ and $35.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ ). Thus, using the above equation we calculate the value for $N$

$$
\begin{gathered}
N=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(5.50 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+35.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=2.31 \times 10^{28} \text { lattice sites } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, finally the value of $N{f r}$ is computed using equation (N_{f r}=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q_{f r}}{2 k T}\right)) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{f r}=N \exp \left(-\frac{Q{f r}}{2 k T}\right) \\
=\left(2.31 \times 10^{28} \text { lattice sites } / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{1.1 \mathrm{eV}}{(2)\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}\right)(350+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=8.24 \times 10^{23} \text { defects } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

question:
What is the composition, in atom percent, of an alloy that consists of $92.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Ag}$ and $7.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Cu}$ ? 
\begin{aligned}
& A_{\mathrm{Ag}}=107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A_{\mathrm{Cu}}=63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}

Give your answer as (the atom percent of Ag, the atom percent of Cu).

solution:
In order to compute composition, in atom percent, of a $92.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Ag}-7.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Cu}$ alloy, we employ equation (\begin{aligned}
&C_1^{\prime}=\frac{C_1 A_2}{C_1 A_2+C_2 A_1} \times 100\\
&C_2^{\prime}=\frac{C_2 A_1}{C_1 A_2+C_2 A_1} \times 100
\end{aligned}) given the atomic weights of silver and copper:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& A{\mathrm{Ag}}=107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A{\mathrm{Cu}}=63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

These compositions in atom percent are determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{Ag}}{ }^{\prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{Ag}} A{\mathrm{Cu}}}{C{\mathrm{Ag}} A{\mathrm{Cu}}+C{\mathrm{Cu}} A{\mathrm{Ag}}} \times 100 \\
=\frac{(92.5)(63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{(92.5)(63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(7.5)(107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})} \times 100 \\
=87.9 \mathrm{at} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

and

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{Cu}}{ }^{\prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{Cu}} A{\mathrm{Ag}}}{C{\mathrm{Ag}} A{\mathrm{Cu}}+C{\mathrm{Cu}} A{\mathrm{Ag}}} \times 100 \\
=\frac{(7.5)(107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{(92.5)(63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+(7.5)(107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})} \times 100 \\
=12.1 \mathrm{at} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

question:
What is the composition, in atom percent, of an alloy that consists of $5.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{~Pb}$ and $94.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Sn}$ ?
\begin{aligned}
& A_{\mathrm{Pb}}=207.2 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A_{\mathrm{Sn}}=118.71 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
Give your answer as (the atom percent of Pb, the atom percent of Sn).

What is the composition, in weight percent, of an alloy that consists of $5 \mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{Cu}$ and $95 \mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{Pt}$ ?
\begin{aligned}
& A_{\mathrm{Cu}}=63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A_{\mathrm{Pt}}=195.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
Give your answer as (the weight percent of Cu, the weight percent of Pt)

What is the composition, in atom percent, of an alloy that contains 33 g of copper and 47 g of zinc?
\begin{aligned}
& A_{\mathrm{Cu}}=63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A_{\mathrm{Zn}}=65.41 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
Give your answer as a tuple (the atom percent of Cu, the atom percent of Zn)

solution:
In this problem we are asked to determine the concentrations, in atom percent, of the $\mathrm{Ag}-\mathrm{Au}-\mathrm{Cu}$ alloy. It is first necessary to convert the amounts of $\mathrm{Ag}, \mathrm{Au}$, and Cu into grams, by multiplying the mass (in pound-mass) for each component by the conversion factor for pound-mass to grams-i.e., $453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}$. Therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime}=\left(44.5 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)=20,185 \mathrm{~g} \\
& m{\mathrm{Au}}^{\prime}=\left(83.7 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)=37,966 \mathrm{~g} \\
& m{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\prime}=\left(5.3 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(453.6 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)=2,404 \mathrm{~g}
\end{aligned}
$$

These masses must next be converted into moles (equation (n_{m 1}=\frac{m_1^{\prime}}{A_1})), using atomic weight values for $\mathrm{Ag}, \mathrm{Au}$, and Cu. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{m{\mathrm{Ag}}}=\frac{m{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime}}{A{\mathrm{Ag}}}=\frac{20,185 \mathrm{~g}}{107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}=187.1 \mathrm{~mol} \\
n{m{\mathrm{Au}}}=\frac{37,966 \mathrm{~g}}{196.97 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}=192.8 \mathrm{~mol} \\
n{m{\mathrm{Cu}}}=\frac{2,404 \mathrm{~g}}{63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}=37.8 \mathrm{~mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, employment of equation (C_1^{\prime}=\frac{n_{m 1}}{n_{m 1}+n_{m 2}+n_{m 3}+\ldots+n_{m n}} \times 100), gives

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime}=\frac{n{m{\mathrm{Ag}}}}{n{m{\mathrm{Ag}}}+n{m{\mathrm{Au}}}+n{m{\mathrm{Cu}}}} \times 100 \\
=\frac{187.1 \mathrm{~mol}}{187.1 \mathrm{~mol}+192.8 \mathrm{~mol}+37.8 \mathrm{~mol}} \times 100=44.8 \mathrm{at} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C{\mathrm{Au}}^{\prime}=\frac{192.8 \mathrm{~mol}}{187.1 \mathrm{~mol}+192.8 \mathrm{~mol}+37.8 \mathrm{~mol}} \times 100=46.2 \mathrm{at} \% \\
& C{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\prime}=\frac{37.8 \mathrm{~mol}}{187.1 \mathrm{~mol}+192.8 \mathrm{~mol}+37.8 \mathrm{~mol}} \times 100=9.0 \mathrm{at} \%
\end{aligned}
$$

This problem calls for a determination of the number of atoms per cubic meter for lead. In order to solve this problem, one must employ equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}),

$$
N=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Pb}}}{A{\mathrm{Pb}}}
$$

The density of Pb is $11.35 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, while its atomic weight is $207.2 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& N=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(11.35 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)}{207.2 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
= & 3.30 \times 10^{22} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}=3.30 \times 10^{28} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

This problem calls for a determination of the number of atoms per cubic meter for chromium. In order to solve this problem, one must employ equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}),

$$
N=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Cr}}}{A{\mathrm{Cr}}}
$$

The density of Cr is $7.19 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, while its atomic weight is $52.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& N=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(7.19 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)}{52.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
& =8.33 \times 10^{22} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}=8.33 \times 10^{28} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

In order to compute the concentration in $\mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}$ of Si in a $0.25 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Si}-99.75 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Fe}$ alloy we must employ equation (\begin{aligned}
&C_1^{\prime \prime}=\left(\frac{C_1}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}\right) \times 10^3\\
&C_2^{\prime \prime}=\left(\frac{C_2}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}\right) \times 10^3
\end{aligned}) as

$$
C{\mathrm{Si}}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{Si}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{Si}}}{P{\mathrm{Si}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}} \times 10^{3}
$$

Densities for silicon and iron are 2.33 and $7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, respectively; therefore

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{Si}}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{0.25}{\frac{0.25}{2.33 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{99.75}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \times 10^{3} \\
=19.6 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to solve this problem, equation (\rho_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}), which is modified to take the following form:

$$
\rho{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{C{\mathrm{Ti}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Ti}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{Al}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Al}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{V}}}{\rho{\mathrm{V}}}}
$$

And, using the density values for $\mathrm{Ti}, \mathrm{Al}$, and V -i.e., $4.51 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}, 2.71 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, and $6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, the density is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{90 \mathrm{wt} \%}{4.51 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{6 \mathrm{wt} \%}{2.71 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{4 \mathrm{wt} \%}{6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \\
=4.38 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to determine the number of molybdenum atoms per cubic centimeter for a $16.4 \mathrm{wt} \%$ Mo-83.6 wt\% W solid solution. To solve this problem, employment of equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)}) is necessary, using the following values:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C{1}=C{\mathrm{Mo}}=16.4 \mathrm{wt} \% \\
& \rho{1}=\rho{\mathrm{Mo}}=10.22 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& \rho{2}=\rho{\mathrm{W}}=19.30 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& A{1}=A{\mathrm{Mo}}=95.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Mo}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} C{\mathrm{Mo}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{Mo}} A{\mathrm{Mo}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Mo}}}+\frac{A{\mathrm{Mo}}}{\rho{\mathrm{W}}}\left(100-C{\mathrm{Mo}}\right)} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)(16.4 \mathrm{wt} \%)}{\frac{(16.4 \mathrm{wt} \%)(95.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{10.22 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{95.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{19.3 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}(100-16.4 \mathrm{wt} \%)} \\
=1.73 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to determine the number of niobium atoms per cubic centimeter for a $24 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Nb}-76$ $\mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{~V}$ solid solution. To solve this problem, employment of equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)}) is necessary, using the following values:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C{1}=C{\mathrm{Nb}}=24 \mathrm{wt} \% \\
& \rho{1}=\rho{\mathrm{Nb}}=8.57 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& \rho{2}=\rho{\mathrm{V}}=6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& A{1}=A{\mathrm{Nb}}=92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Nb}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} C{\mathrm{Nb}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{Nb}} A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Nb}}}+\frac{A{\mathrm{Nb}}}{\rho{\mathrm{V}}}\left(100-C{\mathrm{Nb}}\right)} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)(24 \mathrm{wt} \%)}{\frac{(24 \mathrm{wt} \%)(92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{8.57 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{92.91 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}(100-24 \mathrm{wt} \%)} \\
=1.02 \times 10^{22} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

The following strategy will be used to solve this problem:
Step 1: compute the number of Fe atoms per centimeter cubed using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)})
Step 2: compute the number of C atoms per centimeter cubed also using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)})
Step 3: compute the number of unit cells per centimeter cubed by dividing the number of Fe atoms per centimeter cubed (Step 1) by two since there are two Fe atoms per BCC unit cell

Step 4: compute the number of total interstitial sites per centimeter cubed by multiplying the number of tetrahedral interstitial sites by the number of unit cells per cubic centimeter (from Step 3)

Step 5: The fraction of tetrahedral sites occupied by carbon atoms is computed by dividing the number of carbon atoms per centimeter cubed (Step 3) by the total number of interstitial sites per cubic centimeter

The solution to this problem involves using the following values:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C{\mathrm{C}}=0.2 \mathrm{wt} \% \\
& C{\mathrm{Fe}}=99.8 \mathrm{wt} \% \\
& \rho{\mathrm{C}}=2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& \rho{\mathrm{Fe}}=7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& A{\mathrm{C}}=12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& A{\mathrm{Fe}}=55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Step 1: We compute the number of Fe atoms per cubic centimeter using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)}) as:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Fe}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} C{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{Fe}} A{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}+\frac{A{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\rho{\mathrm{C}}}\left(100-C{\mathrm{Fe}}\right)} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)(99.8 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Fe})}{\frac{(99.8 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Fe})(55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{(55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\left(100 \mathrm{wt} \%-99.8 \mathrm{wt} \%\right)} \\
8.43 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{Fe} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Step 2: We can compute the number of C atoms per cubic centimeter also using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)}) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{C}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} C{\mathrm{C}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{C}} A{\mathrm{C}}}{\rho{\mathrm{C}}}+\frac{A{\mathrm{C}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}\left(100-C{\mathrm{C}}\right)} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)(0.2 \mathrm{wt} \%)}{\frac{(0.2 \mathrm{wt} \%)(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\left(100 \mathrm{wt} \%-0.2 \mathrm{wt} \%\right)} \\
=7.85 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{C} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Step 3: the number of unit cells per centimeter cubed is determined by dividing the number of Fe atoms per centimeter cubed (Step 1) by two since there are two Fe atoms per BCC unit cell-that is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\text { no. unit cells } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}=\frac{N{\mathrm{Fe}}}{2} \\
=\frac{8.43 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{Fe} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}{2}=4.22 \times 10^{22}
\end{gathered}
$$

Step 4: We compute the number of total interstitial sites per centimeter cubed by multiplying the number of tetrahedral interstitial sites per unit cell by the number of unit cells per cubic centimeter (from Step 3). From  figure 5.6b , there are 4 tetrahedral sites located on the front face plane of the unit cell-one site for each of the unit cell edges in this plane. Inasmuch as there are 6 faces on this unit cell there are $6 \times 4=24$ interstitial sites for this unit cell. However, each of these sites is shared by 2 unit cells, which means that only 12 sites belong to each unit cell. Therefore the number of tetrahedral sites per centimeter cubed corresponds to 12 times the number of unit cells per cubic centimeter $\left(n{s}\right)$-that is

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{s}=(12 \text { sites } / \text { unit cell })\left(4.22 \times 10^{22} \text { unit cells } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right) \\
=5.06 \times 10^{23} \text { sites } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Step 5: The fraction of tetrahedral sites occupied by carbon atoms is computed by dividing the number of carbon atoms per centimeter cubed (Step 3) by the total number of interstitial sites per cubic centimeter, that is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\text { fraction sites occupied }=\frac{N{\mathrm{C}}}{n{s}} \\
=\frac{7.85 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{C} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}{5.06 \times 10^{23} \text { sites } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}=1.55 \times 10^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is first necessary to compute the number of carbon atoms per cubic centimeter of alloy using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)}). For this problem

$$
\begin{aligned}
& A{1}=A{\mathrm{C}}=12.011 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
& C{1}=C{\mathrm{C}}=0.1 \mathrm{wt} \% \\
& \rho{1}=\rho{\mathrm{C}}=2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
& \rho{2}=\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}=7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now using equation (N_1=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} C_1}{\frac{C_1 A_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{A_1}{\rho_2}\left(100-C_1\right)})

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{C}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} C{\mathrm{C}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{C}} A{\mathrm{C}}}{\rho{\mathrm{C}}}+\frac{A{\mathrm{C}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}\left(100-C{\mathrm{C}}\right)} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)(0.1 \mathrm{wt} \%)}{\frac{(0.1 \mathrm{wt} \%)(12.011 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{(12.011 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}(100-0.1 \mathrm{wt} \%)} \\
=3.94 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{C} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

We now perform the same calculation for iron atoms, where
$A{1}=A{\mathrm{Fe}}=55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$
$C{1}=C{\mathrm{Fe}}=100 \%-0.1 \mathrm{wt} \%=99.9 \mathrm{wt} \%$
$\rho{1}=\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}=7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$
$\rho{2}=\rho{\mathrm{C}}=2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$
Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Fe}}=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)(99.9 \mathrm{wt} \%)}{\frac{(99.9 \mathrm{wt} \%)(55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{(55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}(100-99.9 \mathrm{wt} \%)} \\
=8.46 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{Fe} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

From Section 3.4 there are two Fe atoms associated with each unit cell; hence, the number of unit cells in a centimeter cubed, $n{f}$, is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{i}=\frac{\text { No. Fe atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}{\text { No. \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }} \\
=\frac{8.46 \times 10^{22} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}{2 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }}=4.23 \times 10^{22} \text { unit cells } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, the fraction of unit cells that contain carbon atoms, $n{f}$, is just the number of carbon atoms per centimeter cubed $\left(3.94 \times 10^{20}\right)$ divided by the number of unit cells per centimeter cubed $\left(4.23 \times 10^{22}\right)$, or

$$
\begin{aligned}
n{f} & =\frac{3.94 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{C} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}{4.23 \times 10^{22} \text { unit cells } / \mathrm{cm}^{3}} \\
& =9.31 \times 10^{-3} \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }
\end{aligned}
$$

The reciprocal of $n{f}$ is the number of unit cells per atom—viz.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{n{f}} & =\frac{1}{9.31 \times 10^{-3} \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }} \\
& =107.5 \text { unit \frac{cells}{atom} }
\end{aligned}
$$

That is, there is one carbon atom per 107.5 unit cells.

This problem asks that we compute the unit cell edge length for a $90 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Fe}-10 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{~V}$ alloy. First of all, the atomic radii for Fe and V  are 0.124 and 0.132 nm , respectively. Also, using equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) it is possible to compute the unit cell volume, and inasmuch as the unit cell is cubic, the unit cell edge length is just the cube root of the volume. However, it is first necessary to calculate the density and average atomic weight of this alloy using equation ((\rho_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}) and (A_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{A_1}+\frac{C_2}{A_2}})). Inasmuch as the densities of iron and vanadium are $7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ and $6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$, respectively, the average density is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{C{\mathrm{V}}}{P{\mathrm{V}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}} \\
=\frac{100}{\frac{10 \mathrm{wt} \%}{6.10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{90 \mathrm{wt} \%}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \\
=7.65 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

And for the average atomic weight

$$
\begin{gathered}
A{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{C{\mathrm{V}}}{A{\mathrm{V}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{Fe}}}{A{\mathrm{Fe}}}} \\
=\frac{100}{\frac{10 \mathrm{wt} \%}{50.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}+\frac{90 \mathrm{wt} \%}{55.85 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}} \\
=55.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, $V{C}$ is determined from a rearranged form equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) as (taking the number of atoms per unit cell, $n=2$, since the crystal structure of the alloy is BCC)

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=\frac{n A{\text {ave }}}{\rho{\text {ave }} N{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{(2 \text { atoms } / \text { unit cell })(55.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})}{\left(7.65 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)} \\
=2.40 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }
\end{gathered}
$$

And, finally, because the unit cell is of cubic symmetry $\left(V{C}=a^{3}\right)$ then

$$
\begin{gathered}
a=\left(V{C}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
=\left(2.40 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
=2.89 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}=0.289 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

To begin, it is necessary to employ equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}), and solve for the unit cell volume, $V_{C}$, as

$$
V_{C}=\frac{n A_{\text {ave }}}{\rho_{\text {ave }} N_{\mathrm{A}}}
$$

where $A_{\text {ave }}$ and $\rho_{\text {ave }}$ are the atomic weight and density, respectively, of the $\mathrm{Pt}-\mathrm{Cu}$ alloy. Inasmuch as both of these materials have the FCC crystal structure, which has cubic symmetry, $V_{C}$ is just the cube of the unit cell length, $a$. That is

$$
\begin{gathered}
V_{C}=a^{3}=(0.390 \mathrm{~nm})^{3} \\
=\left(3.90 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}=5.932 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now necessary to construct expressions for $A_{\text {ave }}$ and $\rho_{\text {ave }}$ in terms of the concentration of copper, $C_{\mathrm{Cu}}$, using equation ((\rho_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}) and (A_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{A_1}+\frac{C_2}{A_2}})). For $A_{\text {ave }}$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& A_{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_{\mathrm{Cu}}}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}+\frac{\left(100-C_{\mathrm{Cu}}\right)}{A_{\mathrm{Pt}}}} \\
& =\frac{100}{\frac{C_{\mathrm{Cu}}}{63.55 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}+\frac{\left(100-C_{\mathrm{Cu}}\right)}{195.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

since the atomic weights for Cu and Pt are, respectively, 63.55 and $195.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Now, the expression for $\rho_{\text {ave }}$ (i.e., equation (\rho_{\mathrm{ave}}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}})) is as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \rho_{\text {ave }}=\frac{100}{\frac{C_{\mathrm{Cu}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{Cu}}}+\frac{\left(100-C_{\mathrm{Cu}}\right)}{\rho_{\mathrm{Pt}}}} \\
& =\frac{100}{\frac{C_{\mathrm{Cu}}}{8.94 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{\left(100-C_{\mathrm{Cu}}\right)}{21.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

given the densities of 8.94 and $21.45 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ for the respective metals. Within the FCC unit cell there are 4 equivalent atoms, and thus, the value of $n$ in equation (\rho=\frac{n A}{V_C N_{\mathrm{A}}}) is 4 ; hence, the expression for $V_{C}$ may be written in terms of the concentration of Cu in weight percent as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
V_{C}=5.932 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \\
=\frac{n A_{\text {ave }}}{\rho_{\text {ave }} N_{\mathrm{A}}}
\end{gathered}
$$

And solving this expression for $C_{\mathrm{Cu}}$ leads to $C_{\mathrm{Cu}}=2.83 \mathrm{wt} \%$.

This problem calls for the mass of hydrogen, per hour, that diffuses through a Pd sheet. It first becomes necessary to employ both equation ((J=\frac{M}{A t}) and (J=-D \frac{d C}{d x})). Combining these expressions and solving for the mass yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
M=J A t=-D A t \frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x} \\
=-\left(1.7 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)\left(0.25 \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)(3600 \mathrm{~s} / \mathrm{h})\left[\frac{0.4-2.0 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}}{6 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}\right] \\
=4.1 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{h}
\end{gathered}
$$

Let us first convert the carbon concentrations from weight percent to kilograms carbon per meter cubed using equation (C_1^{\prime \prime}=\left(\frac{C_1}{\frac{C_1}{\rho_1}+\frac{C_2}{\rho_2}}\right) \times 10^3); the densities of carbon and iron are $2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ and $7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$. For $0.015 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{C}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{C}}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{C}}}{\frac{C{\mathrm{C}}}{P{\mathrm{C}}}+\frac{C{\mathrm{Fe}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Fe}}}} \times 10^{3} \\
=\frac{0.015}{\frac{0.015}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{99.985}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \times 10^{3} \\
1.18 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly, for $0.0068 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{C}$

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{C}}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{0.0068}{\frac{0.0068}{2.25 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{99.9932}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \times 10^{3} \\
=0.535 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, using a rearranged form of equation (J=-D \frac{d C}{d x})

$$
D=-J \frac{\Delta x}{\Delta C}=-J\left[\frac{x{\mathrm{A}}-x{\mathrm{B}}}{C{\mathrm{A}}-C{\mathrm{B}}}\right]
$$

and incorporating values of plate thickness and diffusion flux, provided in the problem statement, as well as the two concentrations of carbon determined above, the diffusion coefficient is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=-\left(7.36 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{2}-\mathrm{s}\right)\left[\frac{2 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{0.535 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}-1.18 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}}\right] \\
=2.3 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problems asks for us to compute the diffusion flux of nitrogen gas through a $1.5-\mathrm{mm}$ thick plate of iron at $300^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ when the pressures on the two sides are 0.10 and 5.0 MPa . Ultimately we will employ equation (J=-D \frac{d C}{d x}) to solve this problem. However, it first becomes necessary to determine the concentration of hydrogen at each face using equation (C_{\mathrm{N}}=4.90 \times 10^{-3} \sqrt{p_{\mathrm{N}_2}} \exp \left(-\frac{37,600 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{R T}\right)). At the low pressure (or B) side

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~B})}=\left(4.90 \times 10^{-3}\right) \sqrt{0.10 \mathrm{MPa}} \exp \left[-\frac{37,600 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(300+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
5.77 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{wt} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

Whereas, for the high pressure (or A) side

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~A})}=\left(4.90 \times 10^{-3}\right) \sqrt{5.0 \mathrm{MPa}} \exp \left[-\frac{37,600 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(300+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
4.08 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{wt} \%
\end{gathered}
$$

We now convert concentrations in weight percent to mass of nitrogen per unit volume of solid. At face B there are $5.77 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~g}$ (or $5.77 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~kg}$ ) of hydrogen in 100 g of Fe , which is virtually pure iron. From the density of iron $\left(7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)$, the volume iron in $100 \mathrm{~g}\left(V{\mathrm{B}}\right)$ is just

$$
V{\mathrm{B}}=\frac{100 \mathrm{~g}}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}=12.7 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}=1.27 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{3}
$$

Therefore, the concentration of hydrogen at the B face in kilograms of N per cubic meter of alloy $\left[C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{B})}^{\prime \prime}\right]$ is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~B})}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~B})}}{V{\mathrm{B}}} \\
=\frac{5.77 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~kg}}{1.27 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{3}}=4.54 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

At the A face the volume of iron in $100 \mathrm{~g}\left(V{\mathrm{A}}\right)$ will also be $1.27 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{3}$, and

$$
\begin{gathered}
C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~A})}^{\prime \prime}=\frac{C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~A})}}{V{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{4.08 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~kg}}{1.27 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{3}}=3.21 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, the concentration gradient is just the difference between these concentrations of nitrogen divided by the thickness of the iron membrane; that is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x}=\frac{C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~B})}^{\prime \prime}-C{\mathrm{N}(\mathrm{~A})}^{\prime \prime}}{x{\mathrm{B}}-x{\mathrm{A}}} \\
=\frac{4.54 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}-3.21 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{3}}{1.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}=-0.184 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{4}
\end{gathered}
$$

At this time it becomes necessary to calculate the value of the diffusion coefficient at $300^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)). Thus,

$$
D=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right)
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=\left(5.0 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{77,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(300+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=4.74 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, finally, the diffusion flux is computed using equation (J=-D \frac{d C}{d x}) by taking the negative product of this diffusion coefficient and the concentration gradient, as

$$
\begin{gathered}
J=-D \frac{\Delta C}{\Delta x} \\
=-\left(4.74 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)\left(-0.184 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{4}\right)=8.72 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{2}-\mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

We are asked to compute the diffusion coefficients of C in both $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ iron at $900^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. Using the data in
Table 6.2,

$$
\begin{gathered}
D_\alpha=\left(1.1 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{87,400 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1173 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=1.40 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s} \\
\begin{aligned}
& D_\gamma=\left(2.3 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{148,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1173 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
&= 5.86 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
\end{gathered}
$$


The $D$ for diffusion of C in BCC $\alpha$ iron is larger, the reason being that the atomic packing factor is smaller than for FCC $\gamma$ iron ( 0.68 versus 0.74); this means that there is slightly more interstitial void space in the BCC Fe, and, therefore, the motion of the interstitial carbon atoms occurs more easily.

This problem asks us to compute the magnitude of $D$ for the diffusion of Mg in Al at $400^{\circ} \mathrm{C}(673 \mathrm{~K})$. Incorporating the appropriate data from  table 6.2 -i.e.,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& D{0}=1.2 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \\
& Q{d}=130,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

into equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(1.2 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{130,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(673 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=9.64 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Note: This problem may also be solved using the "Diffusion" module in the VMSE software. Open the "Diffusion" module, click on the "D vs \frac{1}{T} Plot" submodule, and then do the following:

