3. A $\log \mathrm{D}$ versus $1 / \mathrm{T}$ plot then appears, with a line for the temperature dependence of the diffusion coefficient for Mg in Al . At the top of this curve is a diamond-shaped cursor. Click-and-drag this cursor down the line to the point at which the entry under the "Temperature (T):" label reads 673 K (inasmuch as this is the Kelvin equivalent of $400^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ). Finally, the diffusion coefficient value at this temperature is given under the label "Diff Coeff (D):". For this problem, the value is $8.0 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}$.

This problem asks us to compute the magnitude of $D$ for the diffusion of N in FCC Fe at $950^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. Incorporating the appropriate data from  table 6.2 -i.e.,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& D{0}=9.1 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \\
& Q{d}=168,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

into equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(9.1 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{168,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{\left(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K}\right)\left(950^{\circ} \mathrm{C}+273\right)}\right] \\
=6.0 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Note: this problem may also be solved using the "Diffusion" module in the VMSE software. Open the "Diffusion" module, click on the "D vs \frac{1}{T} Plot" submodule, and then do the following:

1. In the left-hand window that appears, click on the "Custom 1 under the "Diffusing Species" heading (since none of the preset systems is for the diffusion of nitrogen in FCC iron).
2. Under "Dq" within the "Diffusion Coefficients" box enter "9.1e-5"; and under "Qq" enter "168".
3. It is necessary to enter maximum and minimum temperatures within the "Temperature Range" box. Because our temperature of interest is $950^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, enter " 900 " in the "T Min" "C" box, and "1000" in the T Max "C" box.
4. Upon clicking on the "Add Curve" box, a log D versus $1 / \mathrm{T}$ plot then appears, with a line for the temperature dependence of the diffusion coefficient for N in FCC iron. At the top of this curve is a diamond-shaped cursor. Click-and-drag this cursor down the line to the point at which the entry under the "Temperature (T):" label reads 1223 K (inasmuch as this is the Kelvin equivalent of $950^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ). Finally, the diffusion coefficient value at this temperature is given under the label "Diff Coeff (D):". For this problem, the value is $6.0 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}$.

(a) Using equation (\ln D=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)), we set up two simultaneous equations (at temperatures $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ ) with $Q_{d}$ and $D_{0}$ as unknowns as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \ln D_{1}=\ln D_{0}-\frac{Q_{d}}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_{1}}\right) \\
& \ln D_{2}=\ln D_{0}-\frac{Q_{d}}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, solving for $Q_{d}$ in terms of temperatures $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ ( 1473 K and 1673 K ) and $D_{1}$ and $D_{2}\left(2.2 \times 10^{-15}\right.$ and $4.8 \times$ $10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}$ ), we get

$$
\begin{gathered}
Q_{d}=-R \frac{\ln D_{1}-\ln D_{2}}{\frac{1}{T_{1}}-\frac{1}{T_{2}}} \\
=-\left(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K}\right) \frac{\left[\ln \left(2.2 \times 10^{-15}\right)-\ln \left(4.8 \times 10^{-14}\right)\right]}{\frac{1}{1473 \mathrm{~K}}-\frac{1}{1673 \mathrm{~K}}} \\
=315,700 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving for $D_{0}$ using a rearranged form of equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) (and using the 1473 K value of $D$ )

$$
\begin{gathered}
D_{0}=D_{1} \exp \left(\frac{Q_{d}}{R T_{1}}\right) \\
=\left(2.2 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[\frac{315,700 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1473 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=3.5 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Using these values of $D_{0}$ and $Q_{d}, D$ at 1573 K is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=\left(3.5 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{315,700 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1573 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=1.1 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) Using Equation (\ln D=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)), we set up two simultaneous equations (at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$ ) with $Q_d$ and $D_0$ as unknowns as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \ln D_1=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_1}\right) \\
& \ln D_2=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$


Solving for $Q_d$ in terms of temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2\left(873 \mathrm{~K}\left[600^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right]\right.$ and $\left.973 \mathrm{~K}\left[700^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right]\right)$ and $D_1$ and $D_2\left(5.5 \times 10^{-14}\right.$ and $3.9 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}$ ), we get

$$
Q_d=-R \frac{\ln D_1-\ln D_2}{\frac{1}{T_1}-\frac{1}{T_2}}
$$


$$
\begin{gathered}
=-\frac{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})\left[\ln \left(5.5 \times 10^{-14}\right)-\ln \left(3.9 \times 10^{-13}\right)\right]}{\frac{1}{873 \mathrm{~K}}-\frac{1}{973 \mathrm{~K}}} \\
=138,300 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving for $D_0$ from a rearranged form of Equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) (and using the $600^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ value of $D$ )


(b) Using these values of $D_0$ and $Q_d, D$ at $1123 \mathrm{~K}\left(850^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)$ is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=\left(1.05 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{138,300 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1123 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=3.8 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Note: this problem may also be solved using the "Diffusion" module in the VMSE software. Open the "Diffusion" module, click on the "D0 and Qd from Experimental Data" submodule, and then do the following:
1. In the left-hand window that appears, enter the two temperatures from the table in the book (converted from degrees Celsius to Kelvins) (viz. " 873 " $\left(600^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)$ and " 973 " $\left(700^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)$, in the first two boxes under the column labeled "T (K)". Next, enter the corresponding diffusion coefficient values (viz. "5.5e-14" and "3.9e-13").
3. Next, at the bottom of this window, click the "Plot data" button.
4. A $\log \mathrm{D}$ versus $1 / \mathrm{T}$ plot then appears, with a line for the temperature dependence for this diffusion system. At the top of this window are give values for $D_0$ and $Q_d$; for this specific problem these values are $1.04 \times$ $10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^2 / \mathrm{s}$ ("Do=1.04E-05") and $138 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$ ("Qd=138"), respectively
