This problem asks us to determine the values of $Q{d}$ and $D{0}$ for the diffusion of Au in Ag from the plot of $\log D$ versus $\frac{1}{T}$. According to equation (\log D=\log D_0-\frac{Q_d}{2.3 R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)) the slope of this plot is equal to $-\frac{Q{d}}{2.3 R}$ (rather than $-\frac{Q{d}}{R}$ since we are using $\log D$ rather than $\ln D$ ); furthermore, the intercept at $\frac{1}{T}=0$ gives the value of $\log D{0}$. The slope is equal to

$$
\text { slope }=\frac{\Delta(\log D)}{\Delta\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)}=\frac{\log D{1}-\log D{2}}{\frac{1}{T{1}}-\frac{1}{T{2}}}
$$

Taking $\frac{1}{T}{1}$ and $\frac{1}{T}{2}$ as $1.0 \times 10^{-3}$ and $0.90 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$, respectively, then the corresponding values of $\log D{1}$ and $\log D{2}$ are -14.68 and -13.57 . Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
Q{d}=-2.3 R(\text { slope }) \\
Q{d}=-2.3 R \frac{\log D{1}-\log D{2}}{\frac{1}{T{1}}-\frac{1}{T{2}}}
\end{gathered}
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=-(2.3)(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})\left[\frac{-14.68-(-13.57)}{\left(1.0 \times 10^{-3}-0.90 \times 10^{-3}\right) \mathrm{K}^{-1}}\right] \\
=212,200 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Rather than trying to make a graphical extrapolation to determine $D{0}$, a more accurate value is obtained analytically using a rearranged form of equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) taking a specific value of both $D$ and $T$ (from $\frac{1}{T}$ ) from the plot given in the problem; for example, $D=1.0 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}$ at $T=1064 \mathrm{~K}\left(\frac{1}{T}=0.94 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}\right)$. Therefore

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{0}=D \exp \left(\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(1.0 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[\frac{212,200 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1064 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=2.65 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to determine the values of $Q{d}$ and $D{0}$ for the diffusion of V in Mo from the plot of log $D$ versus $\frac{1}{T}$. According to equation (\log D=\log D_0-\frac{Q_d}{2.3 R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)) the slope of this plot is equal to $-\frac{Q{d}}{2.3 R}$ (rather than $-\frac{Q{d}}{R}$ since we are using $\log D$ rather than $\ln D$ ); furthermore, the intercept at $\frac{1}{T}=0$ gives the value of $\log D{0}$. The slope is equal to

$$
\text { slope }=\frac{\Delta(\log D)}{\Delta\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)}=\frac{\log D{1}-\log D{2}}{\frac{1}{T{1}}-\frac{1}{T{2}}}
$$

Taking $\frac{1}{T}{1}$ and $\frac{1}{T}{2}$ as $0.50 \times 10^{-3}$ and $0.55 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$, respectively, then the corresponding values of $\log D{1}$ and $\log D{2}$ are -15.90 and -17.13 . Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
Q{d}=-2.3 R(\text { slope }) \\
Q{d}=-2.3 R \frac{\log D{1}-\log D{2}}{\frac{1}{T{1}}-\frac{1}{T{2}}} \\
=-(2.3)(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})\left[\frac{-15.90-(-17.13)}{\left(0.50 \times 10^{-3}-0.55 \times 10^{-3}\right) \mathrm{K}^{-1}}\right] \\
=470,200 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Rather than trying to make a graphical extrapolation to determine $D{0}$, a more accurate value is obtained analytically using a rearranged form of equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) taking a specific value of both $D$ and $T$ (from $\frac{1}{T}$ ) from the plot given in the problem; for example, $D=1.26 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}$ at $T=2000 \mathrm{~K}\left(\frac{1}{T}=0.50 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}\right)$. Therefore

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{0}=D \exp \left(\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(1.26 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[\frac{470,200 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(2000 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=2.44 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

To solve this problem it is necessary to employ equation (D t=\text { constant }), that is

$$
D t=\text { constant }
$$

which, for this problem, takes the form

$$
D{1000} t{1000}=D{\mathrm{T}} t{\mathrm{T}}
$$

At $1000^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, and using the data from  table 6.2 , for the diffusion of carbon in $\gamma$-iron-i.e.,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& D{0}=2.3 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \\
& Q{d}=148,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

the diffusion coefficient is computed using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{1000}=\left(2.3 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{148,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1000+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=1.93 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, from equation (D t=\text { constant })

$$
\left(1.93 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(12 \mathrm{~h})=D{\mathrm{T}}(4 \mathrm{~h})
$$

And, solving this expression for $D{\mathrm{T}}$

$$
D{\mathrm{T}}=\frac{\left(1.93 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(12 \mathrm{~h})}{4 \mathrm{~h}}=5.79 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
$$

Now, solving for $T$ from equation (\ln D=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)) gives

$$
T=-\frac{Q{d}}{R\left(\ln D{\mathrm{T}}-\ln D{0}\right)}
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=-\frac{148,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})\left[\ln \left(5.79 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)-\ln \left(2.3 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)\right]} \\
=1381 \mathrm{~K}=1108^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) We are asked to calculate the diffusion coefficient for Mg in Al at $450^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. From  table 6.2 , for this diffusion system

$$
\begin{aligned}
& D{0}=1.2 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \\
& Q{d}=130,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) and these data, the value of $D$ is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(1.2 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{130,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(450+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=4.81 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) This portion of the problem calls for the time required at $550^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ to produce the same diffusion result as for 15 h at $450^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. equation (D t=\text { constant }) is employed as follows:

$$
$D{450} t{450}=D{550} t{550}$
$$

Now, from equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) the value of the diffusion coefficient at $550^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ is calculated as

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{550}=\left(1.2 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{130,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(550+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=6.67 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, solving for the diffusion time at $550^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ (using equation (D_{450} t_{450}=D_{550} t_{550}) above) yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
t{550}=\frac{D{450} t{450}}{D{550}} \\
=\frac{\left(4.81 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(15 \mathrm{~h})}{\left(6.67 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)}=1.08 \mathrm{~h}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to determine the temperature to which the diffusion couple must be heated so as to produce a concentration of $3.0 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Ni}$ at the $2.0-\mathrm{mm}$ position, we must first utilize equation (\frac{x^2}{D t}=\mathrm{constant}) with time $t$ being a constant. That is, because time $(t)$ is a constant, then

$$
\frac{x^{2}}{D}=\text { constant }
$$

Or

$$
\frac{x{1000}^{2}}{D{1000}}=\frac{x{\mathrm{T}}^{2}}{D{\mathrm{T}}}
$$

Now, solving for $D{\mathrm{T}}$ from this equation yields

$$
D{\mathrm{T}}=\frac{x{\mathrm{T}}^{2} D{1000}}{x{1000}^{2}}
$$

and incorporating into this expressions the temperature dependence of $D{1000}$ utilizing equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)), leads to

$$
D{\mathrm{T}}=\frac{\left(x{\mathrm{T}}^{2}\right)\left[D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right)\right]}{x{1000}^{2}}
$$

$$
=\frac{(2 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}\left[\left(1.9 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left(-\frac{230,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1273 \mathrm{~K})}\right)\right]}{(1 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}}
$$

$$
=2.74 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
$$

We now need to find the temperature $T$ at which $D$ has this value. This is accomplished by rearranging equation (\ln D=\ln D_0-\frac{Q_d}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T}\right)) and solving for $T$ as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
T=\frac{Q{d}}{R\left(\ln D{0}-\ln D\right)} \\
=\frac{230,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})\left[\ln \left(1.9 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)-\ln \left(2.74 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)\right]} \\
=1360 \mathrm{~K}=1087^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to determine the position within the diffusion couple at which the concentration of A in B is 2.5 $\mathrm{wt} \%$, we must employ equation (\frac{x^2}{D t}=\mathrm{constant}) with $t$ constant. That is

$$
\frac{x^{2}}{D}=\text { constant }
$$

Or

$$
\frac{x{800}^{2}}{D{800}}=\frac{x{1000}^{2}}{D{1000}}
$$

It is first necessary to compute values for both $D{800}$ and $D{1000}$; this is accomplished using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{800}=\left(1.5 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{125,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(800+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
1.22 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s} \\
D{1000}=\left(1.5 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{125,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(1000+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
1.11 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving equation (\frac{x_{800}^2}{D_{800}}=\frac{x_{1000}^2}{D_{1000}}) (above) for $x{1000}$ yields

$$
x{1000}=x{800} \sqrt{\frac{D{1000}}{D{800}}}
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=\left(5 \mathrm{~mm}\right) \sqrt{\frac{1.11 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}}{1.22 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}}} \\
=15.1 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to determine the position within this diffusion system at which the concentration of X in Y is 2.0 $\mathrm{wt} \%$ after 17.5 h , we must employ equation (\frac{x^2}{D t}=\mathrm{constant}) with $D$ constant (since the temperature is constant). (Inasmuch as $D$ is constant it is not necessary to employ preexponential and activation energy values cited in the problem statement.) Under these circumstances, equation (\frac{x^2}{D t}=\mathrm{constant}) takes the form

$$
\frac{x^{2}}{t}=\text { constant }
$$

Or

$$
\frac{x{1}^{2}}{t{1}}=\frac{x{2}^{2}}{t{2}}
$$

If we assume the following:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& x{1}=0.5 \mathrm{~mm} \\
& t{1}=10 \mathrm{~h} \\
& t{2}=17.5 \mathrm{~h}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now upon solving the above expression for $x{2}$ and incorporation of these values we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
x{2}=\sqrt{\frac{x{1}^{2} t{2}}{t{1}}} \\
=\sqrt{\frac{(0.5 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}(17.5 \mathrm{~h})}{10 \mathrm{~h}}} \\
=0.66 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) For this portion of the problem we are asked to determine the value of $Q{0}$. This is possible using equation (Q_0=2 C_s \sqrt{\frac{D_p t_p}{\pi}}). However, it is first necessary to determine the value of $D$ for the predeposition treatment $\left[D{p}\right.$ at $\left.T{p}=\right)$ $900^{\circ} \mathrm{C}(1173 \mathrm{~K})]$ using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)). Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{p}=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{k T{p}}\right) \\
=\left(2.14 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{3.65 \mathrm{eV}}{\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom } \cdot \mathrm{K}\right)(1173 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=4.5 \times 10^{-21} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

The value of $Q{0}$ is determined (using equation (Q_0=2 C_s \sqrt{\frac{D_p t_p}{\pi}})) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{Q}{0}=2 \mathrm{C}{8} \sqrt{\frac{D{p} I{p}}{\pi}} \\
=(2)\left(8.0 \times 10^{25} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right) \sqrt{\frac{\left(4.5 \times 10^{-21} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(1 \mathrm{~h})(60 \mathrm{~min} / \mathrm{h})(60 \mathrm{~s} / \mathrm{min})}{\pi}} \\
=3.63 \times 10^{17} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Computation of the junction depth requires that we use equation (x_j=\left[\left(4 D_d t_d\right) \ln \left(\frac{Q_0}{C_B \sqrt{\pi D_d t_d}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}). However, before this is possible it is necessary to calculate $D$ at the temperature of the drive-in treatment $\left[D{d}\right.$ at $\left.1200^{\circ} \mathrm{C}(1473 \mathrm{~K})\right]$, again using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)). Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{d}=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{k T{d}}\right) \\
=\left(2.14 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{3.65 \mathrm{eV}}{\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom } \cdot \mathrm{K}\right)(1473 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=7.02 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now from equation (x_j=\left[\left(4 D_d t_d\right) \ln \left(\frac{Q_0}{C_B \sqrt{\pi D_d t_d}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2})

$$
\begin{gathered}
x{j}=\left[\left(4 D{d} t{d}\right) \ln \left(\frac{Q{0}}{C{B} \sqrt{\pi D{d} t{d}}}\right)\right]^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
=\left\{\left.(4)\left(7.02 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(1.75 \mathrm{~h})(60 \mathrm{~min} / \mathrm{h})(60 \mathrm{~s} / \mathrm{min})\right) \ln \left[\frac{3.63 \times 10^{17} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{2}}{\left(2 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right) \sqrt{(\pi)\left(7.02 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(1.75 \mathrm{~h})(60 \mathrm{~min} / \mathrm{h})(60 \mathrm{~s} / \mathrm{min})}}\right]\right\}^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
=1.23 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}=1.23 \mu \mathrm{~m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(c) For a concentration of $5 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{Sb}$ atoms $/ \mathrm{m}^{3}$ for the drive-in treatment, we compute the value of $x$ using equation (C(x, t)=\frac{Q_0}{\sqrt{\pi D t}} \exp \left(-\frac{x^2}{4 D t}\right)). However, it is first necessary to manipulate equation (C(x, t)=\frac{Q_0}{\sqrt{\pi D t}} \exp \left(-\frac{x^2}{4 D t}\right)) so that $x$ is the dependent variable. Taking natural logarithms of both sides leads to

$$
\ln C(x, t)=\ln \left(\frac{Q{0}}{\sqrt{\pi D{d} t{d}}}\right)-\frac{x^{2}}{4 D{d} t{d}}
$$

Now, rearranging and solving for $x$ leads to

$$
x=\left\{\left(4 D{d} l{d}\right) \ln \left[\frac{Q{0}}{G(x, t) \sqrt{\pi D{d} l{d}}}\right]\right\}^{\frac{1}{2}}
$$

Now, incorporating values for $Q{0}$ and $D{d}$ determined above and taking $C(x, t)=5 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{Sb}$ atoms $/ \mathrm{m}^{3}$ yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
x=\left\{(4)\left(7.02 \times 10^{-18}\right)(6300) \ln \left[\frac{3.63 \times 10^{17}}{\left(5 \times 10^{23}\right) \sqrt{(\pi)\left(7.02 \times 10^{-18}\right)(6300)}}\right]\right\}^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
=3.43 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}=0.343 \mu \mathrm{~m}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we compute the time for the predeposition heat treatment for the diffusion of In in Si. In order to do this it is first necessary to determine the value of $Q{0}$ from equation (x_j=\left[\left(4 D_d t_d\right) \ln \left(\frac{Q_0}{C_B \sqrt{\pi D_d t_d}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}). However, before doing this we must first calculate $D{d}$, using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)). Therefore

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{d}=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{k T{d}}\right) \\
=\left(7.85 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{3.63 \mathrm{eV}}{\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom } \cdot \mathrm{K}\right)\left(1175^{\circ} \mathrm{C}+273 \mathrm{~K}\right)}\right] \\
=1.84 \times 10^{-17} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving for $Q{0}$ in equation (x_j=\left[\left(4 D_d t_d\right) \ln \left(\frac{Q_0}{C_B \sqrt{\pi D_d t_d}}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}) leads to

$$
\mathrm{Q}{0}=\left(\mathrm{C}{B} \sqrt{\pi D{d} t{d}}\right) \exp \left(\frac{x{j}^{2}}{4 D{d} t{d}}\right)
$$

In the problem statement we are given the following values:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C{B}=2 \times 10^{20} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3} \\
& t{d}=2 \mathrm{~h}(7,200 \mathrm{~s}) \\
& x{j}=2.35 \mu \mathrm{~m}=2.35 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, incorporating these values into the above equation yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{Q}{0}=\left[\left(2 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right) \sqrt{(\pi)\left(1.84 \times 10^{-17} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(7,200 \mathrm{~s})}\right] \exp \left[\frac{\left(2.35 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}}{(4)\left(1.84 \times 10^{-17} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)(7,200 \mathrm{~s})}\right] \\
=4.33 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

We may now compute the value of $t{p}$ using equation (Q_0=2 C_s \sqrt{\frac{D_p t_p}{\pi}}). However, before this is possible it is necessary to determine $D{p}$ (at $925^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ) using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) , as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{p}=\left(7.85 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{3.63 \mathrm{eV}}{\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \text { atom } \cdot \mathrm{K}\right)\left(925^{\circ} \mathrm{C}+273 \mathrm{~K}\right)}\right] \\
=4.25 \times 10^{-20} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving for $t{p}$ in equation (Q_0=2 C_s \sqrt{\frac{D_p t_p}{\pi}}) we get

$$
t{p}=\frac{\pi Q{0}^{2}}{4 G{S}^{2} D{p}}
$$

And incorporating the value of $C{s}$ provided in the problem statement $\left(2 \times 10^{25} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)$ as well as values for $Q{0}$ and $D{p}$ determined above, leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
t{p}=\frac{\pi\left(4.33 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)^{2}}{(4)\left(2.5 \times 10^{26} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)^{2}\left(4.25 \times 10^{-20} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)} \\
=5.54 \times 10^{3} \mathrm{~s}=92.3 \mathrm{~min}=1.53 \mathrm{~h}
\end{gathered}
$$

This is a permeability problem in which we are asked to compute the diffusion flux of oxygen through a $15-\mathrm{mm}$ thick sheet of low-density polyethylene. In order to solve this problem it is necessary to employ equation (J=-P_M \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}). The permeability coefficient of $\mathrm{O}{2}$ through LDPE is given in  table 6.4  as $2.2 \times 10^{-13}\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)-\mathrm{cm} / \mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}$. Thus, from equation (J=-P_M \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x})

$$
J=-P{M} \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}=-P{M} \frac{P{2}-P{1}}{\Delta x}
$$

and taking $P{1}=2000 \mathrm{kPa}(2,000,000 \mathrm{~Pa})$ and $P{2}=150 \mathrm{kPa}(150,000 \mathrm{~Pa})$ we get the following value for the flux:

$$
\begin{gathered}
J=\left[-2.2 \times 10^{-13} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)(\mathrm{cm})}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}}\right]\left(\frac{150,000 \mathrm{~Pa}-2,000,000 \mathrm{~Pa}}{1.5 \mathrm{~cm}}\right) \\
=2.7 \times 10^{-7} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to compute the permeability coefficient for carbon dioxide through high-density polyethylene at 325 K given a steady-state permeability situation. It is necessary for us to use equation (J=-P_M \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}) in to solve this problem. Rearranging this expression and solving for the permeability coefficient gives the following:

$$
P{M}=\frac{-J \Delta x}{\Delta P}=\frac{-J \Delta x}{P{2}-P{1}}
$$

Taking $P{1}=4000 \mathrm{kPa}(4,000,000 \mathrm{~Pa})$ and $P{2}=2500 \mathrm{kPa}(2,500,000 \mathrm{~Pa})$, we compute the permeability coefficient of $\mathrm{CO}{2}$ through HDPE as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
P{M} & =\frac{\left[-2.2 \times 10^{-8} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}}\right](5 \mathrm{~cm})}{(2,500,000 \mathrm{~Pa}-4,000,000 \mathrm{~Pa})} \\
& =0.73 \times 10^{-13} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)(\mathrm{cm})}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}}
\end{aligned}
$$

This problem asks that we compute the diffusion flux at 350 K for water in polystyrene. It is first necessary to compute the value of the permeability coefficient at 350 K . The temperature dependence of $P_{M}$ is given in the problem statement, as follows:

$$
P_{M}=P_{M_{0}} \exp \left(-\frac{Q_{p}}{R T}\right)
$$

Incorporating values provided for the constants $P_{M_{0}}$ and $Q_{p}$, we get

$$
\begin{gathered}
P_{M}=\left[9.0 \times 10^{-5} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)(\mathrm{cm})}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}}\right] \exp \left[-\frac{42,300 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.314 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(350 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=4.4 \times 10^{-11} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)(\mathrm{cm})}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, using equation (J=-P_M \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}), the diffusion flux is equal to

$$
J=-P_{M} \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}=-P_{M} \frac{P_{S}-P_{1}}{\Delta x}
$$

Since

$$
\begin{aligned}
& P_{1}=20 \mathrm{kPa}=20,000 \mathrm{~Pa} \\
& P_{2}=1 \mathrm{kPa}=1,000 \mathrm{~Pa} \\
& \Delta x=30 \mathrm{~mm}=3 \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

it is possible to solve for the value of the flux as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
J=-\left[4.4 \times 10^{-11} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)(\mathrm{cm})}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}-\mathrm{Pa}}\right]\left(\frac{1,000 \mathrm{~Pa}-20,000 \mathrm{~Pa}}{3 \mathrm{~cm}}\right) \\
=2.8 \times 10^{-7} \frac{\left(\mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{STP}\right)}{\mathrm{cm}^{2}-\mathrm{s}}
\end{gathered}
$$

We are asked to calculate the diffusion coefficient for Cu in Al at $600^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, given values for $D_{0}$ and $Q_{d}$. This determination is possible using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=D_{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q_{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(6.5 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{136,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(600+273 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=4.7 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for us to calculate the elastic strain that results for a copper specimen stressed in tension. The cross-sectional area is just $(15.2 \mathrm{~mm}) \times(19.1 \mathrm{~mm})=290 \mathrm{~mm}^{2}\left(=2.90 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2}=0.45 \mathrm{in} .^{2}\right)$; also, the elastic modulus for Cu is given in  table 7.1  as 110 GPa (or $110 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}$ ). Combining equation ((\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}) and (\sigma=E \varepsilon)) and solving for the strain yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
\varepsilon=\frac{\sigma}{E}=\frac{\frac{F}{A{0}}}{E}=\frac{F}{A{0} E} \\
=\frac{44,500 \mathrm{~N}}{\left(2.90 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)\left(110 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}=1.39 \times 10^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

We are asked to compute the maximum length of a cylindrical nickel specimen (before deformation) that is deformed elastically in tension. For a cylindrical specimen the original cross-sectional area $A{0}$ is equal to

$$
A{0}=\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}
$$

where $d{0}$ is the original diameter. Combining equations (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}), (\varepsilon=\frac{l_i-l_0}{l_0}=\frac{\Delta l}{l_0})  and (\sigma=E \varepsilon)and solving for $l{0}$ leads to

$$
l{0}=\frac{\Delta l}{\varepsilon}=\frac{\Delta l}{\frac{\sigma}{E}} E=\frac{\Delta l E}{\frac{F}{A{0}}}=\frac{\Delta l E \pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}}{F}=\frac{\Delta l E \pi d{0}^{2}}{4 F}
$$

Substitution into this expression, values of $d{0}, \Delta l, E$, and $F$ given in the problem statement yields the following

$$
\begin{gathered}
l{0}=\frac{\left(0.25 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)\left(207 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)\left(10.2 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}}{(4)(8900 \mathrm{~N})} \\
=0.475 \mathrm{~m}=475 \mathrm{~mm} \text { (18.7 in.) }
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we derive an expression for the dependence of the modulus of elasticity, $E$, on the parameters $A, B$, and $n$ in equation (E_N=-\frac{A}{r}+\frac{B}{r^n}). It is first necessary to take $d E{N} / d r$ in order to obtain an expression for the force $F$; this is accomplished as follows:

$$
F=\frac{d E{N}}{d r}=\frac{d\left(-\frac{A}{r}\right)}{d r}+\frac{d\left(\frac{B}{r^{n}}\right)}{d r}
$$

$$
=\frac{A}{r^{(1+1)}}-\frac{n B}{r^{(n+1)}}
$$

The second step is to set this $d E{N} / d r$ expression equal to zero and then solve for $r\left(=r{0}\right)$. The algebra for this procedure is carried out in Problem 2.18, with the result that

$$
r{0}=\left(\frac{A}{n B}\right)^{1 /(1-n)}
$$

Next it becomes necessary to take the derivative of the force $(d \frac{F}{d} r)$, which is accomplished as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{d F}{d r}=\frac{d\left(\frac{A}{r^{2}}\right)}{d r}+\frac{d\left(-\frac{n B}{r^{n+1}}\right)}{d r} \\
& \quad-\frac{2 A}{r^{3}}+\frac{(n)(n+1) B}{r^{(n+2)}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, substitution of the above expression for $r{0}$ into this equation yields

$$
\left(\frac{d F}{d r}\right){r{0}}=-\frac{2 A}{\left(\frac{A}{n B}\right)^{3 /(1-n)}}+\frac{(n)(n+1) B}{\left(\frac{A}{n B}\right)^{(n+2) /(1-n)}}
$$

which is the expression to which the modulus of elasticity is proportional.

answer:
$$
\left(\frac{d F}{d r}\right){r{0}}=-\frac{2 A}{\left(\frac{A}{n B}\right)^{3 /(1-n)}}+\frac{(n)(n+1) B}{\left(\frac{A}{n B}\right)^{(n+2) /(1-n)}}
$$

solution:
(a) We are asked to compute the Brinell hardness for the given indentation. It is necessary to use the equation in  table 7.5  for HB , where $P=1000 \mathrm{~kg}, d=2.50 \mathrm{~mm}$, and $D=10 \mathrm{~mm}$. Thus, the Brinell hardness is computed as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{HB}=\frac{2 P}{\pi D\left[D-\sqrt{D^{2}-d^{2}}\right]} \\
=\frac{(2)(1000 \mathrm{~kg})}{(\pi)(10 \mathrm{~mm})\left[10 \mathrm{~mm}-\sqrt{(10 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}-(2.50 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}}\right]}=200.5
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) This part of the problem calls for us to determine the indentation diameter $d$ that will yield a 300 HB when $P=500 \mathrm{~kg}$. Solving for $d$ from the equation in  table 7.5  gives

$$
\begin{gathered}
d=\sqrt{D^{2}-\left[D-\frac{2 P}{(\mathrm{HB}) \pi D}\right]^{2}} \\
=\sqrt{(10 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}-\left[10 \mathrm{~mm}-\frac{(2)(500 \mathrm{~kg})}{(300)(\pi)(10 \mathrm{~mm})}\right]^{2}}=1.45 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

The average of the given yield strength values is calculated using equation (\bar{x}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{n}) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\overline{\sigma_{x}}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{15}\left(\sigma_{y}\right)_{i}}{15} \\
=\frac{274.3+267.5+255.4+\ldots+260.5}{15}=265.9 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

And we compute the standard deviation using equation (s=\left[\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n\left(x_i-\bar{x}\right)^2}{n-1}\right]^{1 / 2}) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
s=\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{15}\left(\left(\sigma_{y}\right)_{i}-\bar{\sigma}_{y}\right)^{2}}{15-1}} \\
=\left[\frac{(274.3-265.9)^{2}+(267.5-265.9)^{2}+\ldots+(260.5-265.9)^{2}}{14}\right]^{1 / 2} \\
=\sqrt{\frac{753.75}{14}}=7.34 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to solve this problem it is necessary to employ equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }}), but first we need to solve for $\lambda$ and $\phi$ angles for the three slip systems.

For each of these three slip systems, the $\phi$ will be the same-i.e., the angle between the direction of the applied stress, [100] and the normal to the (111) plane, that is, the [111] direction. The angle $\phi$ may be determined using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]) as

$$
\phi=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{\left\langle u{1} u{2}+v{1} v{2}+w{1} w{2}\right.}{\sqrt{\left(u{1}^{2}+v{1}^{2}+w{1}^{2}\right)\left(u{2}^{2}+v{2}^{2}+w{2}^{2}\right)}}\right]
$$

where (for [100]) $u{1}=1, v{1}=0, w{1}=0$, and (for [111]) $u{2}=1, v{2}=1, w{2}=1$. Therefore, $\phi$ is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\phi=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{(1)(1)+(0)(1)+(0)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(0)^{2}\right]\left[(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right] \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right)=54.7^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

Let us now determine $\lambda$ for the $[1 \overline{1} 0]$ slip direction. Again, using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]) where $u{1}=1, v{1}=0, w{1}=0$ (for [100]), and $u{2}=1, v{2}=-1, w{2}=0$ (for [1 $\left.\overline{1} 0\right]$ ). Therefore, $\lambda$ is determined as

$$
\lambda{[100]-[1 \overline{1} 0]}=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{(1)(1)+(0)(-1)+(0)(0)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(0)^{2}\right]\left[(1)^{2}+(-1)^{2}+(0)^{2}\right]}}\right]
$$

$$
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)=45^{\circ}
$$

Now, we solve for the yield strength for this (111) $1 \overline{1} 0]$ slip system using equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }}) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma{y}=\frac{\tau{\text {ciss }}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)} \\
=\frac{0.5 \mathrm{MPa}}{\cos \left(54.7^{\circ}\right) \cos \left(45^{\circ}\right)}=\frac{0.5 \mathrm{MPa}}{(0.578)(0.707)}=1.22 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, we must determine the value of $\lambda$ for the (111)-(10 $\overline{1}]$ slip system-that is, the angle between the [100] and $[10 \overline{1}]$ directions. Again using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right])

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda{[100]-[10 \overline{1}]}=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{(1)(1)+(0)(0)+(0)(-1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(0)^{2}\right]\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(-1)^{2}\right]}}\right] \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)=45^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, since the values of $\phi$ and $\lambda$ for this (111)-(10 $\overline{1}]$ slip system are the same as for (111) $1 \overline{1} 0]$, so also will $\sigma{y}$ be the same-viz. 1.22 MPa .

And, finally, for the (111)-(0 $\overline{1} 1]$ slip system, $\lambda$ is computed using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda{[100]-[0 \overline{1} 1]}=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{(1)(0)+(0)(-1)+(0)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(0)^{2}\right]\left[(0)^{2}+(-1)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right] \\
=\cos ^{-1}(0)=90^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, from equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }}), the yield strength for this slip system is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma{y}=\frac{\tau{\text {cros }}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)} \\
=\frac{0.5 \mathrm{MPa}}{\cos \left(54.7^{\circ}\right) \cos \left(90^{\circ}\right)}=\frac{0.5 \mathrm{MPa}}{(0.578)(0)}=\infty
\end{gathered}
$$

which means that slip will not occur on this (111)-[0 $\overline{1} 1]$ slip system.

To solve this problem we use equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }}); however it is first necessary to determine the values of $\phi$ and $\lambda$. These determinations are possible using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]). Now, $\lambda$ is the angle between [121] and [ $\overline{1} 11$ ] directions. Therefore, relative to equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]) let us take $u{1}=1, v{1}=2$, and $w{1}=1$, as well as $u{2}=-1, v{2}=1$, and $w{2}=1$. This leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u{1} u{2}+v{1} v{2}+w{1} w{2}}{\sqrt{\left(u{1}^{2}+v{1}^{2}+w{1}^{2}\right)\left(u{2}^{2}+v{2}^{2}+w{2}^{2}\right)}}\right] \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left\{\frac{(1)(-1)+(2)(1)+(1)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(2)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]\left[(-1)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right\} \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{18}}\right)=61.9^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now for the determination of $\phi$, the normal to the (101) slip plane is the [101] direction. Again using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]), where we now take $u{1}=1, v{1}=2, w{1}=1$ (for [121]), and $u{2}=1, v{2}=0, w{2}=1$ (for [101]). Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\phi=\cos ^{-1}\left\{\frac{(1)(1)+(2)(0)+(1)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(2)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]\left[(1)^{2}+(0)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right\} \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{12}}\right)=54.7^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now possible to compute the yield stress (using equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }})) as

$$
\sigma{y}=\frac{r{\text {cras }}}{\cos \phi \cos \lambda}=\frac{2.4 \mathrm{MPa}}{\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{12}}\right)\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{18}}\right)}=8.82 \mathrm{MPa}
$$

To solve this problem we use equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }}); however it is first necessary to determine the values of $\phi$ and $\lambda$. These determinations are possible using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]). Now, $\lambda$ is the angle between [112] and [011] directions. Therefore, relative to equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]) let us take $u{1}=1, v{1}=1$, and $w{1}=2$, as well as $u{2}=0, v{2}=1$, and $w{2}=1$. This leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u{1} u{2}+v{1} v{2}+w{1} w{2}}{\sqrt{\left(u{1}^{2}+v{1}^{2}+w{1}^{2}\right)\left(u{2}^{2}+v{2}^{2}+w{2}^{2}\right)}}\right] \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left\{\frac{(1)(0)+(1)(1)+(2)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(2)^{2}\right]\left[(0)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right\} \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{\sqrt{12}}\right)=30^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now for the determination of $\phi$, the normal to the (111) slip plane is the [111] direction. Again using equation (\theta=\cos ^{-1}\left[\frac{u_1 u_2+v_1 v_2+w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{\left(u_1^2+v_1^2+w_1^2\right)\left(u_2^2+v_2^2+w_2^2\right)}}\right]), where we now take $u{1}=1, v{1}=1, w{1}=2$ (for [112]), and $u{2}=1, v{2}=1, w{2}=1$ (for [111]). Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\phi=\cos ^{-1}\left\{\frac{(1)(1)+(1)(1)+(2)(1)}{\sqrt{\left[(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(2)^{2}\right]\left[(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}+(1)^{2}\right]}}\right\} \\
=\cos ^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{\sqrt{18}}\right)=19.5^{\circ}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now possible to compute the critical resolved shear stress (using equation (\sigma_y=\frac{\tau_{\mathrm{crss}}}{(\cos \phi \cos \lambda)_{\max }})) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\tau{\text {cros }}=\sigma{y}(\cos \phi \cos \lambda) \\
=(5.12 \mathrm{MPa})\left(\frac{4}{\sqrt{18}}\right)\left(\frac{3}{\sqrt{12}}\right)=4.18 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

To solve this problem requires that we use equation (d^n-d_0^n=K t) with $n=2$. It is first necessary to solve for the parameter $K$ in this equation, using values given in the problem statement of $d{0}\left(2.1 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)$ and the grain diameter after the 3-h heat treatment $\left(7.2 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)$. The computation for $K$ using a rearranged form of equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t) in which $K$ becomes the dependent parameter is as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
K=\frac{d^{2}-d{0}^{2}}{t} \\
=\frac{\left(7.2 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2}-\left(2.1 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2}}{3 \mathrm{~h}} \\
=1.58 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~mm}^{2} / \mathrm{h}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now possible to solve for the value of $d$ after a heat treatment of 1.7 h using a rearranged form of equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t):

$$
\begin{gathered}
d=\sqrt{d{0}^{2}+K t} \\
=\sqrt{\left(2.1 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2}+\left(1.58 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~mm}^{2} / \mathrm{h}\right)(1.7 \mathrm{~h})} \\
=5.59 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

To solve this problem requires that we use equation (d^n-d_0^n=K t) with $n=2.1$. It is first necessary to solve for the parameter $K$ in this equation, using values given in the problem statement of $d{0}\left(1.7 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)$ and the grain diameter after the $250-\mathrm{min}$ heat treatment $\left(4.5 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)$. The computation for $K$ using a rearranged form of equation (d^n-d_0^n=K t) in which $K$ becomes the dependent parameter is as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
K=\frac{d^{2.1}-d{0}^{2.1}}{t} \\
=\frac{\left(4.5 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2.1}-\left(1.7 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2.1}}{250 \mathrm{~min}} \\
=5.17 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~mm}^{2.1} / \mathrm{min}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now possible to solve for the time required to yield a value of $8.7 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}$ for $d$ using a rearranged form of equation (d^n-d_0^n=K t):

$$
\begin{gathered}
t=\frac{d^{2.1}-d{0}^{2.1}}{K} \\
=\frac{\left(8.7 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2.1}-\left(1.7 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)^{2.1}}{5.17 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~mm}^{2.1} / \mathrm{min}} \\
=1110 \mathrm{~min}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for us to calculate the yield strength of a brass specimen after it has been heated to an elevated temperature at which grain growth was allowed to occur; the yield strength ( 150 MPa ) was given at a grain size of 0.01 mm . It is first necessary to calculate the constant $k{y}$ in equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2}), using values for $\sigma{y}(150 \mathrm{MPa}), \sigma{0}$ ( 25 MPa ), and $d(0.01 \mathrm{~mm})$, and as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
k{y}=\frac{\sigma{y}-\sigma{0}}{d^{-\frac{1}{2}}} \\
=\frac{150 \mathrm{MPa}-25 \mathrm{MPa}}{(0.01 \mathrm{~mm})^{-\frac{1}{2}}} \\
=12.5 \mathrm{MPa}-\mathrm{mm}^{\frac{1}{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Next, we must determine the average grain size after the heat treatment. From  figure 8.25  at $500^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ after 1000 s ( 16.7 min ) the average grain size of a brass material is about 0.016 mm . Therefore, calculating $\sigma{\mathrm{y}}$ at this new grain size using equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2}) we get

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma{y}=\sigma{0}+k{y} d^{-\frac{1}{2}} \\
=25 \mathrm{MPa}+\left(12.5 \mathrm{MPa}-\mathrm{mm}^{\frac{1}{2}}\right)(0.016 \mathrm{~mm})^{-\frac{1}{2}} \\
=124 \mathrm{MPa}(18,000 \mathrm{psi})
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem is solved using the following steps:

1. From data given in the problem statement, determine values of $d{0}$ and $K$ in equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t).
2. Incorporation of these data into equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t) , compute the value of $d$ after the heat treatment $\left(800^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right.$ for 3 h$)$.
3. From data provided in the problem statement, determine values of $\sigma{0}$ and $k{y}$ in equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2}).
4. Calculate the value of $\sigma{y}$ using equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2}) incorporating the $d$ value determined in step 2 .

Step 1
Using grain diameter-heat treating time data provided in the problem statement, we set up two simultaneous expressions of equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t)-i.e.,

$$
$d^{2}-d{0}^{2}=K t$
$$

as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& (0.028 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}-d{0}^{2}=K(10 \mathrm{~h}) \\
& (0.010 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}-d{0}^{2}=K(1 \mathrm{~h})
\end{aligned}
$$

From these expressions it is possible to solve for values of $d{0}$ and $K$, which are as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& d{0}=0.0049 \mathrm{~mm} \\
& K=7.60 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~mm}^{2} / \mathrm{h}
\end{aligned}
$$

Step 2

We now compute the grain size $d$ after the three-hour heat treatment using a rearranged form of equation (d^2-d_0^2=K t) and the above values for $d{0}$ and $K$ as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
d=\sqrt{K t+d{0}^{2}} \\
=\sqrt{\left(7.60 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~mm}^{2} / \mathrm{h}\right)(3 \mathrm{~h})+(0.0049 \mathrm{~mm})^{2}} \\
=0.0159 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

# Step 3 

Using grain diameter-yield strength data provided in the problem statement, we set up two simultaneous expressions of equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2})-i.e.,

$$
\sigma{y}=\sigma{0}+k{y} d^{-\frac{1}{2}}
$$

as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 300 \mathrm{MPa}=\sigma{0}+k{y}(0.028 \mathrm{~mm})^{-\frac{1}{2}} \\
& 385 \mathrm{MPa}=\sigma{0}+k{y}(0.010 \mathrm{~mm})^{-\frac{1}{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

from which we determine values for $k{y}$ and $\sigma{0}$; these values are as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& k{y}=21.25 \mathrm{MPa}-\mathrm{mm}^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
& \sigma{0}=172.5 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{aligned}
$$

Step 4
Finally, it is possible to calculate the value of $\sigma{y}$ using equation (\sigma_y=\sigma_0+k_y d^{-1 / 2}) incorporating the $d$ value determined in step 2. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma{y}=\sigma{0}+k{y} d^{-\frac{1}{2}} \\
=172.5 \mathrm{MPa}+\left(21.25 \mathrm{MPa} \cdot \mathrm{~mm}^{\frac{1}{2}}\right)(0.0159 \mathrm{~mm})^{-\frac{1}{2}} \\
=341 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem gives us the tensile strengths and associated number-average molecular weights for two polyethylene materials and then asks that we estimate the $\bar{M}_{n}$ required for a tensile strength of 140 MPa . equation (T S=T S_{\infty}-\frac{A}{\bar{M}_n}) cites the dependence of the tensile strength on $\bar{M}_{n}$-that is

$$
T S=T S_{\infty}-\frac{A}{\bar{M}_{n}}
$$

Using data provided in the problem statement, we may set up two simultaneous equations from which it is possible to solve for the two constants $T S_{\infty}$ and $A$. These equations are as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 90 \mathrm{MPa}=T S_{\infty}-\frac{A}{20,000 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
& 180 \mathrm{MPa}=T S_{\infty}-\frac{A}{40,000 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Values of the two constants are: $T S_{\infty}=270 \mathrm{MPa}$ and $A=3.6 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{MPa}-\mathrm{g} / \mathrm{mol}$. Solving for $\bar{M}_{n}$ in equation (T S=T S_{\infty}-\frac{A}{\bar{M}_n}) and substituting $T S=140 \mathrm{MPa}$ as well as the above values for $T S_{\infty}$ and $A$ leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\bar{M}_{n}=\frac{A}{T S_{\infty}-T S} \\
=\frac{3.6 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{MPa}-\mathrm{g} / \mathrm{mol}}{270 \mathrm{MPa}-140 \mathrm{MPa}}=27,700 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

We may determine the critical stress required for the propagation of an internal crack in aluminum oxide using equation (\sigma_c=\left(\frac{2 E \gamma_s}{\pi a}\right)^{1 / 2}). Taking the value of 393 GPa ( table 7.1 ) as the modulus of elasticity, and realizing that values for $\gamma{s}\left(0.90 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$ and $2 a(0.40 \mathrm{~mm})$ are given in the problem statement, leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma{c}=\left(\frac{2 E \gamma{s}}{\pi a}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
=\left[\frac{(2)\left(393 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(0.90 \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m})}{(\pi)\left(\frac{0.4 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)}\right]^{\frac{1}{2}} \\
=33.6 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}=33.6 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to determine the maximum allowable surface crack length without fracture for a structural component for a specified fracture toughness $(51 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{m}})$, given that fracture occurs for the same component using the same stress level ( 250 MPa ) and another fracture toughness $(62 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{m}})$. (Note: Because the cracks surface cracks, their lengths are equal to $a$.) The maximum crack length without fracture $a{c}$ may be calculated using equation (a_c=\frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{K_{I c}}{\sigma Y}\right)^2)-i.e.,

$$
a{c}=\frac{1}{\pi\left(\frac{K{I c}}{\sigma Y}\right)^{2}}
$$

where $K{\mathrm{Ic}}$ is the plane strain fracture toughness, $\sigma$ is the applied stress, and $Y$ is a design parameter. Using data for the first alloy $\left[K{I c}=62 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{m}}, a{c}=1.6 \mathrm{~mm}\left(1.6 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right), \sigma=250 \mathrm{MPa}\right]$, it is possible to calculate the value of $Y$ using a rearranged form of the above equation as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
Y=\frac{K{I c}}{\sigma \sqrt{\pi a{c}}} \\
=\frac{62 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{~m}}}{(250 \mathrm{MPa}) \sqrt{(\pi)\left(1.6 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}} \\
$=3.50$
\end{gathered}
$$

Using this value of $Y$, the maximum crack length for the second alloy is determined, again using equation (a_c=\frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{K_{I c}}{\sigma Y}\right)^2) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
a{c}=\frac{1}{\pi\left(\frac{K{I c}}{\sigma Y}\right)^{2}} \\
=\frac{1}{\pi}\left[\frac{51 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{~m}}}{(250 \mathrm{MPa})(3.50)}\right]^{2} \\
=0.00108 \mathrm{~m}=1.08 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

We are asked for the critical crack tip radius for a glass specimen. From equation (\sigma_m=2 \sigma_0\left(\frac{a}{\rho_t}\right)^{1 / 2})

$$
\sigma{m}=2 \sigma{0}\left(\frac{a}{\rho{t}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
$$

Fracture will occur when $\sigma{m}$ reaches the fracture strength of the material, which is given as $\frac{E}{10}$; thus

$$
\frac{E}{10}=2 \sigma{0}\left(\frac{a}{\rho{t}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
$$

Or, solving for $\rho{t}$

$$
\rho{t}=\frac{400 a \sigma{0}^{2}}{E^{2}}
$$

From  table 7.1 , for glass (soda-lime), $E=69 \mathrm{GPa}$ (or $69 \times 10^{3} \mathrm{MPa}$ )—thus, we compute the value of $\rho{t}$ as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho{t}=\frac{(400)\left(1 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{~mm}\right)(70 \mathrm{MPa})^{2}}{\left(69 \times 10^{3} \mathrm{MPa}\right)^{2}} \\
=4.1 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~mm}=4.1 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

From  figure 9.27 , the ductile cast iron has a fatigue limit (maximum stress) of magnitude 220 MPa . For rotating-bending tests and a cylindrical bar of diameter $d{0}$ ( figure 9.25b ), maximum stress may be determined using equation (\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3})-i.e.,

$$
\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d{0}^{3}}
$$

Here $L$ is equal to the distance between the two load-bearing points ( figure 9.25b ), $\sigma$ is the maximum stress (in our case the fatigue limit), and $F$ is the maximum applied load. When $\sigma$ is divided by the factor of safety $(N)$ equation (\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3}) takes the form of equation (\frac{\sigma}{N}=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3})-that is

$$
\frac{\sigma}{N}=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d{0}^{3}}
$$

and solving this expression for $F$ leads to

$$
F=\frac{\sigma \pi d{0}^{3}}{16 N L}
$$

Incorporating into this expression values for $d{0}\left(9.5 \mathrm{~mm}=9.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right) L\left(55.5 \mathrm{~mm}=55.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$, and $N(2.25)$ provided in the problem statement as well as the fatigue limit taken from  figure 9.27 \left(220 \mathrm{MPa}\right.$ or $\left.220 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$ yields the following

$$
\begin{gathered}
F=\frac{\left(220 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)\left(9.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}}{(16)(2.25)\left(55.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)} \\
=297 \mathrm{~N}
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, for cyclic reversed and rotating-bending, a maximum load of 297 N may be applied without causing the ductile cast iron bar to fail by fatigue.

From  figure 9.27 , the fatigue limit for this steel is 480 MPa . For rotating-bending tests on a cylindrical specimen of diameter $d{0}$, stress is defined in equation (\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3}) as

$$
\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d{0}^{3}}
$$

When we divide stress by the factor of safety $(N)$, the above equation becomes equation (\frac{\sigma}{N}=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3})-that is

$$
\frac{\sigma}{N}=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d{0}^{3}}
$$

And solving for $d{0}$ realizing that $\sigma$ is the fatigue limit ( 480 MPa or $480 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}$ ) and incorporating values for $F$ $(5,000 \mathrm{~N}), L\left(55.0 \mathrm{~mm}=55 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$, and $N(2.25)$ provided in the problem statement, leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
d{0}=\left(\frac{16 F L N}{\sigma \pi}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} \\
{\left[\frac{(16)(5,000 \mathrm{~N})\left(55.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)(2.25)}{\left(480 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}}} \\
0.0187 \mathrm{~m}=18.7 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

From  figure 9.27 , the fatigue strength at $10^{7}$ cycles for this aluminum alloy is 170 MPa . For a cylindrical specimen having an original diameter of $d{0}$, the stress may be computed using equation (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}), which is equal to

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma=\frac{F}{A{0}} & =\frac{F}{\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}} \\
& =\frac{4 F}{\pi d{0}^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

When we divide $\sigma$ by the factor of safety, the above equation takes the form

$$
\frac{\sigma}{N}=\frac{4 F}{\pi d{0}^{2}}
$$

Solving the above equation for $F$ leads to

$$
F=\frac{\sigma \pi d{0}^{2}}{4 N}
$$

Now taking $\sigma$ to be the fatigue strength (i.e., $170 \mathrm{MPa}=170 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}$ ) and incorporating values for $d{0}$ and $N$ provided in the problem statement [i.e., $12.0 \mathrm{~mm}\left(12.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$ and 3.0 , respectively], we calculate the maximum load as follows:

$$
F=\frac{\left(170 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)\left(12.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}}{(4)(3.0)}
$$

$6,400 \mathrm{~N}$

In order to solve this problem we compute the maximum stress using equation (\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3}), and then determine the fatigue life from the curve in  figure 9.27  for the brass material. In equation (\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d_0^3}), $F$ is the maximum applied load, which for this problem is +120 N . Values for $L$ and $d{0}$ are provided in the problem statement—viz. $67.5 \mathrm{~mm}(67.5 \times$ $\left.10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$ and $6.7 \mathrm{~mm}\left(6.7 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$, respectively. Therefore the maximum stress $\sigma$ is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=\frac{16 F L}{\pi d{0}^{3}} \\
=\frac{(16)(120 \mathrm{~N})\left(67.5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{(\pi)\left(6.7 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}} \\
=137 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}=137 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

From  figure 9.27  and the curve for brass, the logarithm of the fatigue life $\left(\log N{\mathrm{f}}\right)$ at 137 MPa is about 6.5 , which means that the fatigue life is equal to

$$
N{f}=10^{6.5} \text { cycles }=3 \times 10^{6} \text { cycles }
$$

This problem asks that we compute the maximum and minimum loads to which a 14.7 mm diameter Ti-5Al-2.5Sn titanium alloy specimen may be subjected in order to yield a fatigue life of $1.0 \times 10^{6}$ cycles;  figure 9.27  is to be used assuming that data were taken for repeated axial tension-compression tests and a mean stress of 50 MPa. Upon consultation of  figure 9.27 , for this titanium alloy, a fatigue life of $1.0 \times 10^{6}$ cycles corresponds to a stress amplitude of 510 MPa . Or, from equation (\sigma_a=\frac{\sigma_r}{2}=\frac{\sigma_{\max }-\sigma_{\min }}{2})

$$
\sigma{\max }-\sigma{\min }=2 \sigma{a}=(2)(510 \mathrm{MPa})=1020 \mathrm{MPa}
$$

Since $\sigma{\mathrm{m}}=50 \mathrm{MPa}$, then from equation (\sigma_m=\frac{\sigma_{\max }+\sigma_{\min }}{2})

$$
\sigma{\max }+\sigma{\min }=2 \sigma{m}=(2)(50 \mathrm{MPa})=100 \mathrm{MPa}
$$

Simultaneous solution of these two expressions for $\sigma{\max }$ and $\sigma{\min }$ yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma{\max } & =+560 \mathrm{MPa} \\
\sigma{\min } & =-460 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, inasmuch as from equation (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}) and for a cylindrical rod

$$
\sigma=\frac{F}{A{0}}=\frac{F}{\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}}=\frac{4 F}{\pi d{0}^{2}}
$$

then the load, $F$, is equal to

$$
F=\frac{\sigma \pi d{0}^{2}}{4}
$$

It is now possible to compute maximum and minimum loads from the $\sigma{\max }$ and $\sigma{\min }$ values determined above:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& F{\max }=\frac{\sigma{\max } \pi d{0}^{2}}{4}=\frac{\left(560 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)\left(14.7 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}}{4}=95,000 \mathrm{~N} \\
& F{\min }=\frac{\sigma{\min } \pi d{0}^{2}}{4}=\frac{\left(-460 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(\pi)\left(14.7 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{2}}{4}=-78,000 \mathrm{~N}
\end{aligned}
$$

It is first necessary to calculate the steady state creep rate so that we may utilize  figure 9.40  in order to determine the tensile stress. The steady state elongation, $\Delta I{s}$, is just the difference between the total elongation and the sum of the instantaneous and primary creep elongations; that is,

$$
\Delta I{s}=8.2 \mathrm{~mm}-0.6 \mathrm{~mm}=7.6 \mathrm{~mm}
$$

Now the steady state creep rate, $\dot{\varepsilon}{s}$ is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
\dot{\varepsilon}{s}=\frac{\Delta \varepsilon}{\Delta t} \\
=\frac{\frac{\Delta I{s}}{I{0}}}{\Delta t}=\frac{7.6 \mathrm{~mm}}{1500 \mathrm{~h}} \\
=1.01 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~h}^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

From the $650^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ line in  figure 9.40 , a steady state creep rate of $1.01 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~h}^{-1}$ corresponds to a stress $\sigma$ of about 300 MPa. Now from equation (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}) and for a cylindrical specimen having a diameter of $d{0}$

$$
\sigma=\frac{F}{A{0}}=\frac{F}{\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

Solving for $d{0}$ and realizing that $\sigma=300 \mathrm{MPa}\left(300 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$ and $F=70,000 \mathrm{~N}$ leads to

$$
d{0}=\sqrt{\frac{4 F}{\pi \sigma}}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\sqrt{\frac{(4)(70,000 \mathrm{~N})}{(\pi)\left(300 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}} \\
& =0.0172 \mathrm{~m}=17.2 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let us first determine the stress imposed on this specimen using values of cross-section diameter and applied load; this is possible using equation (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}) as

$$
\sigma=\frac{F}{A{0}}=\frac{F}{\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

Inasmuch as $d{0}=13.2 \mathrm{~mm}\left(13.2 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)$ and $F=27,000 \mathrm{~N}$, the stress is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=\frac{27,000 \mathrm{~N}}{\pi\left(\frac{13.2 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}} \\
=197 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}=197 \mathrm{MPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

or approximately 200 MPa . From  figure 9.40  the point corresponding $10^{-3} \mathrm{~h}^{-1}$ and 200 MPa lies approximately midway between $730^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $815^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ lines; therefore, the temperature would be approximately $775^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.

From  figure 9.39  on the $925^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, the stress corresponding to a rupture lifetime of 100 h is approximately 70 MPa.). In order to determine the minimum diameter, we use the expression used to compute stress, as given in equation (\sigma=\frac{F}{A_0}), which for a cylindrical specimen takes the form:

$$
\sigma=\frac{F}{A{0}}=\frac{F}{\pi\left(\frac{d{0}}{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

Solving for $d{0}$ and realizing that $\sigma=70 \mathrm{MPa}\left(70 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$ and $F=20,000 \mathrm{~N}$ leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
d{0}=\sqrt{\frac{4 F}{\pi \sigma}} \\
=\sqrt{\frac{(4)(20,000 \mathrm{~N})}{(\pi)\left(70 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}} \\
=0.0191 \mathrm{~m}=19.1 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

From equation (\dot{\varepsilon}_s=K_1 \sigma^n), if the logarithm of $\hat{\varepsilon}{s}$ is plotted versus the logarithm of $\sigma$, then a straight line should result, the slope of which is the stress exponent $n$. Using  figure 9.40 , determine the value of $n$ for the $S$-590 alloy at $925^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, and for the initial (lower-temperature) straight line segments at each of $650^{\circ} \mathrm{C}, 730^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, and $815^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.

This problem states that ice homogeneously nucleates at $-40^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, and we are to calculate the critical radius given the latent heat of fusion $\left(-3.1 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)$ and the surface free energy $\left(25 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$. Solution to this problem requires the utilization of equation (r^*=\left(-\frac{2 \gamma T_m}{\Delta H_f}\right)\left(\frac{1}{T_m-T}\right)) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
r^{}=\left(-\frac{2 \gamma T{m}}{\Delta H{f}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{T{m}-T}\right) \\
=\left[-\frac{(2)\left(25 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(273 \mathrm{~K})}{-3.1 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{3}}\right]\left(\frac{1}{40 \mathrm{~K}}\right) \\
=1.10 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}=1.10 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) This portion of the problem asks that we compute $r^{}$ and $\Delta G^{}$ for the homogeneous nucleation of the solidification of Ni. First of all, equation (r^*=\left(-\frac{2 \gamma T_m}{\Delta H_f}\right)\left(\frac{1}{T_m-T}\right)) is used to compute the critical radius. The melting temperature for nickel is $1455^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$; also values of $\Delta H{f}\left(-2.53 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)$ and $\gamma\left(0.255 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)$ are given in the problem statement, and the supercooling value found in  table 11.1  is $319^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ (which is also 319 K because this value is really $T{m}-T$, which is the same for Celsius and Kelvin). Thus, from equation (r^*=\left(-\frac{2 \gamma T_m}{\Delta H_f}\right)\left(\frac{1}{T_m-T}\right)) we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
r^{}=\left(-\frac{2 \gamma T{m}}{\Delta H{f}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{T{m}-T}\right) \\
=\left[-\frac{(2)\left(0.255 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)(1455+273 \mathrm{~K})}{-2.53 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{3}}\right]\left(\frac{1}{319 \mathrm{~K}}\right) \\
=1.09 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}=1.09 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{gathered}
$$

For computation of the activation free energy, equation (\Delta G^*=\left(\frac{16 \pi \gamma^3 T_m^2}{3 \Delta H_f^2}\right) \frac{1}{\left(T_m-T\right)^2}) is employed as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta G^{}=\left(\frac{16 \pi \gamma^{3} T{m}^{2}}{3 \Delta H{f}^{2}}\right) \frac{1}{\left(T{m}-T\right)^{2}} \\
=\left[\frac{(16)(\pi)\left(0.255 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)^{3}(1455+273 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}{(3)\left(-2.53 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)^{2}}\right]\left[\frac{1}{(319 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}\right] \\
=1.27 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~J}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) In order to compute the number of atoms in a nucleus of critical size (assuming a spherical nucleus of radius $r^{}$ ), it is first necessary to determine the number of unit cells, which we then multiply by the number of atoms per unit cell. The number of unit cells found in this critical nucleus is just the ratio of critical nucleus and unit cell volumes. Inasmuch as nickel has the FCC crystal structure, its unit cell volume is just $a^{3}$ where $a$ is the unit cell length (i.e., the lattice parameter); this value is 0.360 nm , as cited in the problem statement. Therefore, the number of unit cells found in a radius of critical size is just

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { \# unit \frac{cells}{particle} }=\frac{\frac{4}{3} \pi r^{ 3}}{a^{3}} \\
& =\frac{\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)(\pi)(1.09 \mathrm{~nm})^{3}}{(0.360 \mathrm{~nm})^{3}}=116 \text { unit cells }
\end{aligned}
$$

Inasmuch as 4 atoms are associated with each FCC unit cell, the total number of atoms per critical nucleus is just
(116 unit \frac{cells}{critical} nucleus)(4 \frac{atoms}{unit} cell)

$$
=464 \text { \frac{atoms}{critical} nucleus }
$$

This problem calls for us to compute the electrical conductivity and resistance of a silicon specimen.
(a) We use equation ((\rho=\frac{V A}{I l}) and (\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho})) for the conductivity, as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho} \\
=\frac{1}{\frac{V A}{I I}}=\frac{I I}{V A} \\
=\frac{I I}{V \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

Since the cross-sectional area of a cylinder having a diameter $d$ is

$$
A=\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}
$$

Now, incorporation of values for the several parameters provided in the problem statement, leads to the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=\frac{I l}{V \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}} \\
=\frac{(0.25 \mathrm{~A})\left(45 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{(24 \mathrm{~V})(\pi)\left(\frac{7.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}}=12.2(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The resistance, $R$, over the entire specimen length may be computed by combining and rearranging equation ((\rho=\frac{R A}{l}) and (\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho})) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\frac{l \rho}{A} \\
=\frac{l\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\right)}{A}=\frac{l}{\sigma A} \\
=\frac{l}{\sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

The value of $R$ may be computed upon entering values given in the problem statement into the preceding expression:

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\frac{l}{\sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}} \\
=\frac{57 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{\left[12.2(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right](\pi)\left(\frac{7.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}}=121.4 \Omega
\end{gathered}
$$

For this problem, given that an aluminum wire 10 m long must experience a voltage drop of less than 1.0 V when a current of 5 A passes through it, we are to compute the minimum diameter of the wire. We first of all solve for the cross-sectional $A$ in equation (\rho=\frac{V A}{I l}) as follows:

$$
A=\frac{\rho I I}{V}
$$

Next we make the substitution of a rearranged form of equation (\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho}), which leads to

$$
A=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\right) I I}{V}=\frac{I I}{\sigma V}
$$

From  table 12.1 , for aluminum, the conductivity, $\sigma=3.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$. Furthermore, inasmuch as $A=\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}$ for a cylindrical wire, then we may rewrite the previous equation as follows:

$$
\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{I I}{\sigma V}
$$

And, solving for the diameter $d$ yields the following expression:

$$
d=\sqrt{\frac{4 I I}{\pi \sigma V}}
$$

When values for the several parameters given in the problem statement are incorporated into this expression, we obtain the following value for $d$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
d=\sqrt{\frac{(4)(5 \mathrm{~A})(10 \mathrm{~m})}{(\pi)\left[3.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right](1.0 \mathrm{~V})}} \\
=1.29 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}=1.29 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we compute, for a plain carbon steel wire of 3 mm diameter, the maximum length such that the resistance will not exceed $20 \Omega$. From  table 12.1  for a plain carbon steel $\sigma=0.6 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$. If $d$ is the wire diameter then, combining equation ((\rho=\frac{R A}{l}) and (\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho})) and then solving for the length $l$ leads to the following:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& l=\frac{R A}{\rho} \\
= & \frac{R A}{\frac{1}{\sigma}}=R \sigma A \\
= & R \sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

since the area of a cylindrical wire is equal to

$$
A=\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}
$$

Upon inserting values for $R$ and $d$ given in the problem statement and the value of $\sigma$ taken from  table 12.1  yields the following value for the wire length:

$$
\begin{gathered}
l=R \sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2} \\
=(20 \Omega)\left[0.6 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right](\pi)\left(\frac{3 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}=848 \mathrm{~m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) In order to compute the resistance of this aluminum wire it is necessary to combine equation ((\rho=\frac{R A}{l}) and (\sigma=\frac{1}{\rho})), and then solve for the resistance in terms of the conductivity; this is done as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\frac{\rho l}{A} \\
=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\right) l}{A}=\frac{l}{\sigma A} \\
=\frac{l}{\sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

since the area $A$ of a cylindrical wire is equal to

$$
A=\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}
$$

From  table 12.1 , the conductivity of aluminum is $3.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$. Therefore, we solve for the resistance using equation (\begin{aligned}
&R=\frac{\rho l}{A}\\
&=\frac{\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\right) l}{A}=\frac{l}{\sigma A}\\
&=\frac{l}{\sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2}
\end{aligned}) as follows:

$$
R=\frac{l}{\sigma \pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}}
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=\frac{5 \mathrm{~m}}{\left[3.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right](\pi)\left(\frac{5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}} \\
=6.70 \times 10^{-3} \Omega
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) If $V=0.04 \mathrm{~V}$ then, from equation (V=I R), the current, $I$, is computed as follows:

$$
I=\frac{V}{R}=\frac{0.04 \mathrm{~V}}{6.70 \times 10^{-3} \Omega}=6.00 \mathrm{~A}
$$

(c) The current density is equal to the current divided by the specimen cross-sectional area as

$$
J=\frac{I}{A}=\frac{I}{\pi\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^{2}}=\frac{6.00 \mathrm{~A}}{\pi\left(\frac{5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{2}\right)^{2}}=3.06 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}^{2}
$$

(d) The electric field $(E)$ is computed using equation (\mathscr{E}=\frac{V}{l}) as follows:

$$
E=\frac{V}{l}=\frac{0.04 \mathrm{~V}}{5 \mathrm{~m}}=8.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}
$$

(a) The drift velocity of electrons in Si may be determined using equation (v_d=\mu_e^{\mathscr{E}}). Since the room temperature mobility of electrons is $0.145 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$ ( table 12.3 ), and the electric field is $500 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}$ (as stipulated in the problem statement), the drift velocity is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
v{d}=\mu{e} E \\
=\left(0.145 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)(500 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m})=72.5 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The time, $t$, required to traverse a given length, $l(=25 \mathrm{~mm})$, is just the length divided by the drift velocity, as follows:

$$
t=\frac{l}{v{d}}=\frac{25 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}{72.5 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}}=3.45 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~s}
$$

(a) The number of free electrons per cubic meter for aluminum at room temperature may be computed using rearranged form of equation (\sigma=n|e| \mu_e+p|e| \mu_h) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=\frac{\sigma}{|e| \mu{e}} \\
=\frac{3.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}}{\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.0012 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)} \\
=1.98 \times 10^{29} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) In order to calculate the number of free electrons per aluminum atom, we must first determine the number of copper atoms per cubic meter, $N{\mathrm{Al}}$. From equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}) (and using the atomic weight for Al -viz. $26.98 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ ) then the values of $N{\mathrm{Al}}$ is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Al}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho^{\prime}}{A{\mathrm{Al}}} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(2.7 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{26.98 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=6.03 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

(Note: in the above expression, density is represented by $\rho^{\prime}$ in order to avoid confusion with resistivity which is designated by $\rho$.) And, finally, the number of free electrons per aluminum atom $\left(\frac{n}{N}{\mathrm{Al}}\right)$ is equal to the following:

$$
\frac{n}{N{\mathrm{Al}}}=\frac{1.98 \times 10^{29} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}}{6.03 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}}=3.28 \text { electrons } / \mathrm{Al} \text { atom }
$$

(a) This portion of the problem asks that we calculate, for silver, the number of free electrons per cubic meter ( $n$ ) given that there are 1.3 free electrons per silver atom, that the electrical conductivity is $6.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$, and that the density $\left(\rho{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime}\right)$ is $10.49 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$. (Note: in this discussion, the density of silver is represented by $\rho{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime}$ in order to avoid confusion with resistivity, which is designated by $\square$.) Since $n=1.3 N{\mathrm{Ag}}$, and $N{\mathrm{Ag}}$ is defined in equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}) (and using the atomic weight of Ag -viz., $107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$ ), we compute the value of $n$ as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=1.3 N{\mathrm{Ag}}=1.3\left[\frac{\rho{\mathrm{Ag}}^{\prime} N{\mathrm{A}}}{A{\mathrm{Ag}}}\right] \\
=1.3\left[\frac{\left(10.49 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}{107.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}\right] \\
=7.61 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3} \\
=\left(7.61 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)\left(\frac{10^{2} \mathrm{~cm}}{\mathrm{~m}}\right)^{3}=7.61 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Now we are asked to compute the electron mobility, $\mu{e}$. Using equation (\sigma=n|e| \mu_e+p|e| \mu_h), and incorporating this value of $n$ and the value of $\sigma$ given in the problem statement, the electron mobility is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu{e}=\frac{\sigma}{n|e|} \\
=\frac{6.8 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}}{\left(7.61 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)}=5.58 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

For this part of the problem, we first read, from  figure 12.16 , the number of free electrons (i.e., the intrinsic carrier concentration) at room temperature ( 298 K ). These values are as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& n{i}(\mathrm{Ge}) \cong 4 \times 10^{19} \mathrm{~m}^{-3} \\
& n{i}(\mathrm{Si}) \cong 1 \times 10^{17} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now, the number of atoms per cubic meter for Ge and $\mathrm{Si}\left(N{\mathrm{Ge}}\right.$ and $N{\mathrm{Si}}$, respectively) may be determined using equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}), which involves the densities $\left(\rho{\mathrm{Ge}}^{s}\right.$ and $\rho{\mathrm{Si}}^{s}$ ) and atomic weights $\left(A{\mathrm{Ge}}\right.$ and $\left.A{\mathrm{Si}}\right)$. (Note: here we use $\rho^{\prime}$ to represent density in order to avoid confusion with resistivity, which is designated by $\rho$. Also, the atomic weights for Ge and $\mathrm{Si}, 72.64$ and $28.09 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$, respectively.) Therefore, the number of Ge atoms per cubic meter is computed using equation (N=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}} \rho}{A_{\mathrm{Cu}}}), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Ge}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Ge}}^{s}}{A{\mathrm{Ge}}} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(5.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{72.64 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
=4.41 \times 10^{28} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly, for Si , the number of atoms per cubic meter is

$$
\begin{gathered}
N{\mathrm{Si}}=\frac{N{\mathrm{A}} \rho{\mathrm{Si}}^{s}}{A{\mathrm{Si}}} \\
=\frac{\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)\left(2.33 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)}{28.09 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}
\end{gathered}
$$

$$
=5.00 \times 10^{28} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
$$

Finally, the ratio of the number of free electrons per atom is calculated by dividing $n{i}$ by $N$. For Ge, this ratio is as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{n{i}(\mathrm{Ge})}{N{\mathrm{Ge}}}=\frac{\sim 4 \times 10^{19} \text { electrons } / \mathrm{m}^{3}}{4.41 \times 10^{28} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}} \\
\cong 9 \times 10^{-10} \text { \frac{electron}{atom} }
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly, for Si this ratio is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{n{i}(\mathrm{Si})}{N{\mathrm{Si}}}=\frac{\sim 1 \times 10^{17} \text { electrons } / \mathrm{m}^{3}}{5.00 \times 10^{28} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}} \\
\cong 2 \times 10^{-12} \text { \frac{electron}{atom} }
\end{gathered}
$$

In this problem we are asked to compute the intrinsic carrier concentration for PbS at room temperature. Since the conductivity and both electron and hole mobilities are provided in the problem statement, all we need do is solve for $n$ or $p$ (i.e., $n{i}$ ) using equation (\begin{aligned}
\sigma & =n|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right)=p|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right) \\
& =n_i|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right)
\end{aligned}). Making the appropriate rearrangement of equation (\begin{aligned}
\sigma & =n|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right)=p|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right) \\
& =n_i|e|\left(\mu_e+\mu_h\right)
\end{aligned}) such that $n{i}$ is the dependent variable leads to the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{i}=\frac{\sigma}{|e|\left(\mu{e}+\mu{h}\right)} \\
=\frac{25(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}}{\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)(0.06+0.02) \mathrm{m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}} \\
=1.95 \times 10^{21} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

For this problem we are to determine the electrical conductivity of and $n$-type semiconductor, given that $n$ $=5 \times 10^{17} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ and the electron drift velocity is $350 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ in an electric field of $1000 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}$. The conductivity of this material may be computed using equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e). But before this is possible, it is necessary to calculate the value of $\mu{e}$ using equation (v_d=\mu_e^{\mathscr{E}}), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu{e}=\frac{v{d}}{E} \\
=\frac{350 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}}{1000 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}}=0.35 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is now possible to compute the conductivity using equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e),

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=n|e| \mu{e} \\
=\left(5 \times 10^{17} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.35 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=0.028(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

In this problem, for a Si specimen, we are given values for $p\left(2.0 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)$ and $\sigma\left[500(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right]$, while values for $\mu{h}$ and $\mu{e}\left(0.05\right.$ and $0.145 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$, respectively) are found in  table 12.3 . In order to solve for $n$ we must use equation (\sigma=n|e| \mu_e+p|e| \mu_h), which, after rearrangement, leads to the following expression:

$$
n=\frac{\sigma-p|e| \mu{h}}{|e| \mu{e}}
$$

Incorporation of values of parameters on the right-hand side of this equation leads to the following value for $n$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
n=\frac{500(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}-\left(2.0 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.05 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)}{\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.145 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)} \\
=1.46 \times 10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

This germanium material to which has been added $10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ As atoms is $n$-type since As is a donor in Ge. (Arsenic is from group VA of the periodic table-Ge is from group IVA.)
Since this material is $n$-type extrinsic, equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e) is valid. Furthermore, each As atom will donate a single electron, or the electron concentration is equal to the As concentration since all of the As atoms are ionized at room temperature; that is $n=10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$, and, as given in the problem statement, $\mu{e}=0.1 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$. Thus, the conductivity is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=n|e| \mu{e} \\
=\left(10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.1 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=1.60 \times 10^{4}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

In order to solve for the electron and hole mobilities for GaSb , we must write conductivity expressions for the two materials, of the form of equation (\sigma=n|e| \mu_e+p|e| \mu_h)-i.e.,

$$
\sigma=n|e| \mu{e}+p|e| \mu{h}
$$

For the intrinsic material, incorporation of values of the relevant constants in the problem statement into equation (\sigma=n|e| \mu_e+p|e| \mu_h) gives the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
8.9 \times 10^{4}\left(\Omega-\mathrm{m}\right)^{-1}=\left(8.7 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right) \mu{e} \\
+\left(8.7 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right) \mu{h}
\end{gathered}
$$

which reduces to

$$
0.639=\mu{e}+\mu{h}
$$

Whereas, for the extrinsic GaSb, we use equation (\sigma \cong p|e| \mu_h)

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=p|e| \mu{h} \\
2.3 \times 10^{5}\left(\Omega-\mathrm{m}\right)^{-1}=\left(1.0 \times 10^{25} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right) \mu{h}
\end{gathered}
$$

which simplifies to the following:

$$
\mu{h}=0.144 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}
$$

Thus, we determine the value for $\mu{e}$ by substitution of this value for $\mu{h}$ into equation (0.639=\mu_e+\mu_h) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu{e}=0.639-\mu{h} \\
=0.639 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}-0.144 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s} \\
=0.495 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we estimate the temperature at which GaAs has an electrical conductivity of $1.6 \times$ $10^{-3}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$ assuming that the conductivity has a temperature dependence as shown in equation (\sigma=C T^{-3 / 2} \exp \left(-\frac{E_g}{2 k T}\right)). From the room temperature ( 298 K ) conductivity $\left[3 \times 10^{-7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right]$ and band gap energy $(1.42 \mathrm{eV})$ of  table 12.3  we determine the value of $\ln C$ (equation (\sigma=C T^{-3 / 2} \exp \left(-\frac{E_g}{2 k T}\right))) by taking natural logarithms of both sides of the equation, and after rearrangement the following results:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\ln C=\ln \sigma+\frac{3}{2} \ln T+\frac{E{g}}{2 k T} \\
=\ln \left[3 \times 10^{-7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right]+\frac{3}{2} \ln (298 \mathrm{~K})+\frac{1.42 \mathrm{eV}}{(2)\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}\right)(298 \mathrm{~K})} \\
$=21.17$
\end{gathered}
$$

Again, taking logarithms of both sides of equation (\sigma=C T^{-3 / 2} \exp \left(-\frac{E_g}{2 k T}\right)) leads to

$$
\ln \sigma=\ln C-\frac{3}{2} \ln T-\frac{E{g}}{2 k T}
$$

Now we substitute this value of $C$ as well as the value of the band gap energy $(1.42 \mathrm{eV})$ into equation (\ln \sigma=\ln C-\frac{3}{2} \ln T-\frac{E_g}{2 k T}) in order to determine the value of $T$ for which $\sigma=1.6 \times 10^{-3}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}$; thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
\ln \sigma=\ln C-\frac{3}{2} \ln T-\frac{E{g}}{2 k T} \\
\ln \left[1.6 \times 10^{-3}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right]=21.17-\frac{3}{2} \ln T-\frac{1.42 \mathrm{eV}}{(2)\left(8.62 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}\right)(T)}
\end{gathered}
$$

Using an equation solver (root solver) the value of $T$ is determined as $T=446$, which value is the temperature in K ; this corresponds to $T\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)=446-273=173^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.

This problem asks that we determine the room-temperature electrical conductivity of silicon that has been doped with $10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ of arsenic atoms. Inasmuch as As is a group VA element in the periodic table ( figure 2.8 ) it acts as a donor in silicon. Thus, this material is $n$-type extrinsic, and it is necessary to use equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e), with $n=$ $10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ since at room temperature all of the As donor impurities are ionized. The electron mobility, from  figure 12.18  at an impurity concentration of $10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$, is $0.065 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$. Therefore, the conductivity is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=n|e| \mu{e} \\
=\left(10^{23} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.065 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=1040(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

Here we are asked to calculate the room-temperature electrical conductivity of silicon that has been doped with $2 \times 10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ of boron atoms. Inasmuch as B is a group IIIA element in the periodic table ( figure 2.8 ) it acts as an acceptor in silicon. Thus, this material is $p$-type extrinsic, and it is necessary to use equation (\sigma \cong p|e| \mu_h), with $p=2 \times$ $10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ since at room temperature all of the B acceptor impurities are ionized. The hole mobility, from  figure 12.18  at an impurity concentration of $2 \times 10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$, is $0.0070 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$. Therefore, the conductivity is equal to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=p|e| \mu{e} \\
=\left(2 \times 10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.0070 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=2240(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

In this problem we are to estimate the electrical conductivity, at $75^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, of silicon that has been doped with $10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ of phosphorous atoms. Inasmuch as P is a group VA element in the periodic table ( figure 2.8 ) it acts as a donor in silicon. Thus, this material is $n$-type extrinsic, and it is necessary to use equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e); $n$ in this expression is $10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ since at $75^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ all of the P donor impurities are ionized. The electron mobility is determined using  figure 12.19a . From the $10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ impurity concentration curve and at $75^{\circ} \mathrm{C}(348 \mathrm{~K}), \mu{e}=0.080 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$. Therefore, the conductivity is calculated using equation (\sigma \cong n|e| \mu_e) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=n|e| \mu{e} \\
=\left(10^{22} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.080 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=128(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

In this problem we are to estimate the electrical conductivity, at $135^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, of silicon that has been doped with $10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ of aluminum atoms. Inasmuch as Al is a group IIIA element in the periodic table ( figure 2.8 ) it acts as an acceptor in silicon. Thus, this material is $p$-type extrinsic, and it is necessary to use equation (\sigma \cong p|e| \mu_h); $p$ in this expression is $10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ since at $135^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ all of the Al acceptor impurities are ionized. The hole mobility is determined using  figure 12.19b . From the $10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ impurity concentration curve and at $135^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\left(408 \mathrm{~K}{v}\right) \mu{h}=0.007 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}$. Therefore, we compute the conductivity of this material using equation (\sigma \cong p|e| \mu_h) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=p|e| \mu{h} \\
=\left(10^{24} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.007 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right) \\
=1120(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

In this problem we are asked to determine the magnetic field required to produce a Hall voltage of $-3.5 \times$ $10^{-7} \mathrm{~V}$, given that $\sigma=1.2 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}, \mu{e}=0.0050 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}, I{x}=40 \mathrm{~A}$, and $d=35 \mathrm{~mm}$. We now take a rearranged form of equation (\mu_e=\left|R_{\mathrm{H}}\right| \sigma)

$$
\left|R{\mathrm{H}}\right|=\frac{\mu{e}}{\sigma}
$$

and incorporate into it equation (V_{\mathrm{H}}=\frac{R_{\mathrm{H}} I_x B_z}{d}) as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
V{\mathrm{H}} & =\frac{R{\mathrm{H}} I{x} B{z}}{d} \\
& =\frac{\mu{e} I{x} B{z}}{\sigma d}
\end{aligned}
$$

We now rearrange this expression such that $B{z}$ is the dependent variable, and after inserting values for the remaining parameters that were given in the problem statement, the value of $B{z}$ is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
B{z}=\frac{\left|V{H}\right| \sigma d}{I{x} \mu{e}} \\
=\frac{\left(\left|-3.5 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~V}\right|\right)\left[1.2 \times 10^{7}(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}\right]\left(35 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{(40 \mathrm{~A})\left(0.0050 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)} \\
=0.735 \text { tesla }
\end{gathered}
$$

We are asked in this problem to determine the electrical conductivity for the nonstoichiometric $\mathrm{Fe}{(1-x)} \mathrm{O}$, given $x=0.040$ and that the hole mobility is $1.0 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}$-s. It is first necessary to compute the number of vacancies per cubic meter for this material. For this determination let us use as our basis 10 unit cells. For the sodium chloride crystal structure there are four cations and four anions per unit cell. Thus, in ten unit cells of FeO there will normally be forty $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ and forty $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ ions. However, when $x=0.04,(0.04)(40)=1.6$ of the $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ sites will be vacant. (Furthermore, there will be $3.2 \mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$ ions in these ten unit cells inasmuch as two $\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$ ions are created for every vacancy). Therefore, each unit cell will, on the average contain 0.16 vacancies. Now, the number of vacancies per cubic meter is just the number of vacancies per unit cell divided by the unit cell volume; this volume is just the unit cell edge length $(0.437 \mathrm{~nm})$ cubed. Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\# \text { vacancies }}{\mathrm{m}^{3}}=\frac{0.16 \text { \frac{vacancies}{unit} cell }}{\left(0.437 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}} \\
=1.92 \times 10^{27} \text { vacancies } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

Inasmuch as it is assumed that the vacancies are saturated, the number of holes $(p)$ is also $1.92 \times 10^{27} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$. It is now possible, using equation (\sigma \cong p|e| \mu_h), to compute the electrical conductivity of this material as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma=p|e| \mu{h} \\
=\left(1.92 \times 10^{27} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}\right)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(1.0 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}\right)=3076(\Omega-\mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

For this problem, we are given, for NaCl , the activation energy ( $173,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}$ ) and preexponential ( $4.0 \times$ $\left.10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)$ for the diffusion coefficient of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$and are asked to compute the mobility for a $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ion at 873 K . The mobility, $\mu{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}$, may be computed using equation (\mu_I=\frac{n_I e D_I}{k T}); however, this expression also includes the diffusion coefficient $D{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}$, which is determined using equation (D=D_0 \exp \left(-\frac{Q_d}{R T}\right)) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}=D{0} \exp \left(-\frac{Q{d}}{R T}\right) \\
=\left(4.0 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right) \exp \left[-\frac{173,000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}}{(8.31 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}-\mathrm{K})(873 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=1.76 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now solving for $\mu{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}$using equation (\mu_I=\frac{n_I e D_I}{k T}) (assuming that $n{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}=1$, since the valence of the $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ion is +1 ) yields the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}=\frac{n{\mathrm{Na}^{+}} e D{\mathrm{Na}^{+}}}{k T} \\
=\frac{(1)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C} / \text { atom }\right)\left(1.76 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{s}\right)}{\left(1.38 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~J} / \text { atom-K }\right)(873 \mathrm{~K})} \\
=2.34 \times 10^{-13} \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{V}-\mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) We are first asked to compute the capacitance. Combining equation ((C=\varepsilon \frac{A}{l}) and (\varepsilon_r=\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0})) leads to the following expression:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C=\varepsilon \frac{A}{l} \\
& =\frac{\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0} A}{l}
\end{aligned}
$$

Incorporation of values given in the problem statement for parameters on the right-hand side of this expression, and solving for $C$ yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
C=\frac{\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0} A}{l} \\
=\frac{(3.5)\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(3225 \mathrm{~mm}^{2}\right)\left(1 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / 10^{6} \mathrm{~mm}^{2}\right)}{10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=10^{-10} \mathrm{~F}=100 \mathrm{pF}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Now we are asked to compute the electric field that must be applied in order for $2 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{C}$ to be stored on each plate. First we need to solve for $V$ in equation (C=\frac{Q}{V}) as

$$
V=\frac{Q}{C}=\frac{2 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{C}}{10^{-10} \mathrm{~F}}=200 \mathrm{~V}
$$

The electric field $E$ may now be determined using equation (\mathscr{E}=\frac{V}{l}), as follows:

$$
E=\frac{V}{l}=\frac{200 \mathrm{~V}}{10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}}=2.0 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}
$$

(a) For this part of the problem we want to solve for the voltage when $Q=2.0 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{C}, A=650 \mathrm{~mm}^{2}, l=$ 4.0 mm , and $\varepsilon{r}=3.5$. Combining equation ((C=\frac{Q}{V}), (C=\varepsilon \frac{A}{l}) and (\varepsilon_r=\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0})) yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C=\frac{Q}{V} \\
& =\varepsilon \frac{A}{l} \\
& =\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0} \frac{A}{l}
\end{aligned}
$$

Or

$$
\frac{Q}{V}=\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0} \frac{A}{l}
$$

Now, solving for $V$, and incorporating values provided in the problem statement, leads to the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
V=\frac{Q l}{\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0} A} \\
=\frac{\left(2.0 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(4.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{(3.5)\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(650 \mathrm{~mm}^{2}\right)\left(1 \mathrm{~m}^{2} / 10^{6} \mathrm{~mm}^{2}\right)} \\
=39.7 \mathrm{~V}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) For this same capacitor, if a vacuum is used, then the value of $\varepsilon{r}$ in the preceding equation is equal to unity (i.e., 1); now, we solve for $V$ using a revised form of equation (V=\frac{Q l}{\varepsilon_r \varepsilon_0 A}), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
V=\frac{Q l}{\varepsilon{0} A} \\
=\frac{\left(2.0 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(4.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(650 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)} \\
=139 \mathrm{~V}
\end{gathered}
$$

(c) The capacitance for part (a) is computed using equation (C=\frac{Q}{V}) as follows:

$$
C=\frac{Q}{V}=\frac{2.0 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{C}}{39.7 \mathrm{~V}}=5.04 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F}
$$

While for part (b) the capacitance is

$$
C=\frac{Q}{V}=\frac{2.0 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{C}}{139 \mathrm{~V}}=1.44 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F}
$$

(d) The dielectric displacement may be computed by combining equation ((D=\varepsilon_0 \mathscr{E}+P), (P=\varepsilon_0\left(\varepsilon_r-1\right) \mathscr{E}) and (\mathscr{E}=\frac{V}{l})), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=\varepsilon{0} E+P \\
=\varepsilon{0} E+\varepsilon{0}\left(\varepsilon{r}-1\right) E \\
=\varepsilon{0} \varepsilon{r} E \\
=\frac{\varepsilon{0} \varepsilon{r} V}{l}
\end{gathered}
$$

And incorporating values for $\varepsilon{r}$ and $l$ provided in the problem statement, as well as the value of $V$ computed in part (a) results in the following value for $D$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=\frac{\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)(3.5)(39.7 \mathrm{~V})}{4.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=3.07 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{m}^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

(e) The polarization is determined using equation ((P=\varepsilon_0\left(\varepsilon_r-1\right) \mathscr{E}) and (\mathscr{E}=\frac{V}{l})) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
P=\varepsilon{0}\left(\varepsilon{r}-1\right) E \\
=\varepsilon{0}\left(\varepsilon{r}-1\right) \frac{V}{l} \\
=\frac{\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)(3.5-1)(39.7 \mathrm{~V})}{4.0 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=2.20 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{m}^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) This portion of the problem asks that we compute the magnitude of the dipole moment associated with each unit cell of $\mathrm{BaTiO}{3}$, which is illustrated in  figure 12.35 . The dipole moment $p$ is defined by equation (p=q d) as $p=q d$ in which $q$ is the magnitude of each dipole charge, and $d$ is the distance of separation between the charges. Each $\mathrm{Ti}^{4+}$ ion has four units of charge associated with it, and thus $q=(4)\left(1.602 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)=6.41 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}$. Furthermore, $d$ is the distance the $\mathrm{Ti}^{4+}$ ion has been displaced from the center of the unit cell, which is just 0.006 nm $+0.006 \mathrm{~nm}=0.012 \mathrm{~nm}$ ( figure 12.35b ). Hence

$$
\begin{gathered}
p=q d=\left(6.41 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}\right)\left(0.012 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right) \\
=7.69 \times 10^{-30} \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Now it becomes necessary to compute the maximum polarization that is possible for this material. The maximum polarization will exist when the dipole moments of all unit cells are aligned in the same direction. Furthermore, it is computed by dividing the above value of $p$ by the volume of each unit cell, which is equal to the product of three unit cell edge lengths, as shown in  figure 12.35 . Thus

$$
\begin{gathered}
P=\frac{p}{V{C}} \\
=\frac{7.69 \times 10^{-30} \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{m}}{\left(0.403 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)\left(0.398 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)\left(0.398 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)} \\
=0.120 \mathrm{C} / \mathrm{m}^{2}
\end{gathered}
$$

To solve this problem it first becomes necessary to compute mass fractions using the lever rule. From the iron-carbon phase diagram ( figure 13.2 ), a tie-line in the $\alpha$ and graphite phase field extends from essentially $0 \mathrm{wt} \%$ C to $100 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{C}$. Thus, for a $2.5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{C}$ cast iron the mass fractions of ferrite and graphite phases ( $W{\alpha}$ and $W{\mathrm{Gr}}$, respectively) are determined using this tie-line and the following expressions:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& W{\alpha}=\frac{C{\mathrm{Gr}}-C{0}}{C{\mathrm{Gr}}-C{\alpha}}=\frac{100-2.5}{100-0}=0.975 \\
& W{\mathrm{Gr}}=\frac{C{0}-C{\alpha}}{C{\mathrm{Gr}}-C{\alpha}}=\frac{2.5-0}{100-0}=0.025
\end{aligned}
$$

Conversion from weight fraction to volume fraction of graphite is possible using equation (V_\alpha=\frac{\frac{W_\alpha}{\rho_\alpha}}{\frac{W_\alpha}{\rho_\alpha}+\frac{W_\beta}{\rho_\beta}}) as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& V{\mathrm{Gr}}=\frac{\frac{W{\mathrm{Gr}}}{W{\alpha}}}{\frac{W{\mathrm{Gr}}}{P{\alpha}}}+\frac{W{\mathrm{Gr}}}{P{\mathrm{Gr}}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{\frac{0.025}{2.3 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}}{\frac{0.975}{7.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}+\frac{0.025}{2.3 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}} \\
& =0.081 \text { or } 8.1 \mathrm{vol} \%
\end{aligned}
$$

We are asked to compute the weight of soda ash and limestone that must be added to $125 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}$ of $\mathrm{SiO}{2}$ to yield a glass composition of $78 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{SiO}{2}, 17 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}$, and $5 \mathrm{wt} \% \mathrm{CaO}$. Let $x=$ the weight of $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}$ and $y=$ the weight of CaO . Then, employment of equation (C_1=\frac{m_1}{m_1+m_2+m_3+\ldots+m_n} \times 100), we may write the following expressions for the concentrations of $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}\left(\mathrm{C}{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}}\right)$ and $\mathrm{CaO}\left(\mathrm{C}{\mathrm{CaO}}\right)$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{C}{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}}=17 \mathrm{wt} \%=\frac{x}{125+x+y} \times 100 \\
& \mathrm{C}{\mathrm{CaO}}=5 \mathrm{wt} \%=\frac{y}{125+x+y} \times 100
\end{aligned}
$$

Solving for $x$ and $y$ from these two expressions yields $x=27.2 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}} \mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}$ and $y=8.0 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}} \mathrm{CaO}$.
Now, in order to compute the weights of $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}$ and $\mathrm{CaCO}{3}$, we must employ molecular weights. The formula weights of $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}\left(M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}}\right)$ and $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}\left(M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}}\right)$ are as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}}=2\left(A{\mathrm{Na}}\right)+A{\mathrm{C}}+3\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=2(22.99 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+3(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=105.99 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}}=2\left(A{\mathrm{Na}}\right)+A{\mathrm{O}} \\
=2(22.99 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}=61.98 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, finally, the mass of $\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}\left(m{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}}\right)$ is equal to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}}=\left(27.2 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(\frac{M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{CO}{3}}}{M W{\mathrm{Na}{2} \mathrm{O}}}\right) \\
& =\left(27.2 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(\frac{105.99 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{61.98 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}\right)=46.5 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Likewise, the formula weights of $\mathrm{CaCO}{3}\left(M W{\mathrm{CaCO}{3}}\right)$ and $\mathrm{CaO}\left(M W{\mathrm{CaO}}\right)$ are as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
M W{\mathrm{CaCO}{3}}=A{\mathrm{Ca}}+A{\mathrm{C}}+3\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=40.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+(3)(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=100.09 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
M W{\mathrm{CaO}}=A{\mathrm{Ca}}+A{\mathrm{O}} \\
=40.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}+16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}=56.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

Such that the mass of $\mathrm{CaCO}{3}\left(m{\mathrm{CaCO}{3}}\right)$ is equal to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& m{\mathrm{CaCO}{3}}=\left(8.0 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(\frac{M W{\mathrm{CaCO}{3}}}{M W{\mathrm{CaO}}}\right) \\
= & \left(8.0 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}\right)\left(\frac{100.09 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}{56.08 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}\right)=14.3 \mathrm{lb}{\mathrm{m}}
\end{aligned}
$$

This problem asks for us to calculate the masses of hexamethylene diamine and adipic acid necessary to yield 20 kg of completely linear nylon 6,6 . The chemical equation for this reaction, the answer to Concept Check 14.8 , is as follows:



From this equation we may calculate the molecular weights of these molecules.

$$
\begin{gathered}
M W(\text { adipic acid })=6\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+10\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+4\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right) \\
=6(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+10(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+4(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=146.14 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
M W(\text { hexamethylene })=6\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+16\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{N}}\right) \\
=6(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+16(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+2(14.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=116.21 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol} \\
M W(\text { nylon })=12\left(A{\mathrm{C}}\right)+22\left(A{\mathrm{H}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{N}}\right)+2\left(A{\mathrm{O}}\right)
\end{gathered}
$$

$$
\begin{gathered}
=12(12.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+22(1.008 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+2(14.01 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})+2(16.00 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}) \\
=226.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

The mass of 20 kg of nylon 6,6 equals $20,000 \mathrm{~g}$ or

$$
m(\text { nylon })=\frac{20,000 \mathrm{~g}}{226.32 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}}=88.37 \mathrm{~mol}
$$

Since, according to the chemical equation given above, each mole of nylon 6,6 that is produced requires one mole each of adipic acid and hexamethylene diamine, with two moles of water as the by-product. The masses corresponding to 88.37 moles of adipic acid and hexamethylene diamine are as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
m(\text { adipic acid })=(88.37 \mathrm{~mol})(146.14 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=12,914 \mathrm{~g}=12.914 \mathrm{~kg} \\
m(\text { hexamethylene })=(88.37 \mathrm{~mol})(116.21 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=10,269 \mathrm{~g}=10.269 \mathrm{~kg}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks for the maximum and minimum thermal conductivity values for a TiC-Ni cermet. Using a modified form of equation (E_c(u)=E_m V_m+E_p V_p) the maximum thermal conductivity $k{\max }$ is calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
k{\max }=k{m} V{m}+k{p} V{p}=k{\mathrm{Ni}} V{\mathrm{Ni}}+k{\mathrm{TiC}} V{\mathrm{TiC}} \\
=(67 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})(0.10)+(27 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})(0.90)=31.0 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

Using a modified form of equation (E_c(l)=\frac{E_m E_p}{V_m E_p+V_p E_m}), the minimum thermal conductivity $k{\min }$ is

$$
\begin{gathered}
k{\min }=\frac{k{\mathrm{Ni}} k{\mathrm{TiC}}}{V{\mathrm{Ni}} k{\mathrm{TiC}}+V{\mathrm{TiC}} k{\mathrm{Ni}}} \\
=\frac{(67 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})(27 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})}{(0.10)(27 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})+(0.90)(67 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})} \\
=28.7 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

There are two approaches that may be applied to solve this problem. The first is to estimate the upper limits for both the elastic modulus $\left[E{c}(u)\right]$ and specific gravity $\left(\rho{c}\right)$ for the composite, using expressions of the form of equation (E_c(u)=E_m V_m+E_p V_p), and then take their ratio. Using this approach

$$
\begin{gathered}
E{c}(u)=E{\mathrm{Cu}} V{\mathrm{Cu}}+E{\mathrm{W}} V{\mathrm{W}} \\
=(110 \mathrm{GPa})(0.30)+(407 \mathrm{GPa})(0.70) \\
=318 \mathrm{GPa}
\end{gathered}
$$

And for the specific gravity

$$
\begin{gathered}
\rho{c}=\rho{\mathrm{Cu}} V{\mathrm{Cu}}+\rho{\mathrm{W}} V{\mathrm{W}} \\
$=(8.9)(0.30)+(19.3)(0.70)=16.18$
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, we compute the specific stiffness as follows:

$$
\text { Specific Stiffness }=\frac{E{c}(u)}{\rho{c}}=\frac{318 \mathrm{GPa}}{16.18}=19.65 \mathrm{GPa}
$$

With the alternate approach, the specific stiffness is calculated, again employing a modification of equation (E_c(u)=E_m V_m+E_p V_p), but using the specific stiffness-volume fraction product for both metals, as follows:

$$
\text { Specific Stiffness }=\frac{E{\mathrm{Cu}}}{\rho{\mathrm{Cu}}} V{\mathrm{Cu}}+\frac{E{\mathrm{W}}}{\rho{\mathrm{W}}} V{\mathrm{W}}
$$

$$
=\frac{110 \mathrm{GPa}}{8.9}(0.30)+\frac{407 \mathrm{GPa}}{19.3}(0.70)=18.47 \mathrm{GPa}
$$

answer:
$$
E{c t}=\frac{E{m} E{f 1} E{f 2}}{V{m} E{f 1} E{f 2}+V{f 1} E{m} E{f 2}+V{f 2} E{m} E{f 1}}
$$

solution:
We are asked to compute the voltage of a nonstandard $\mathrm{Pb}-\mathrm{Sn}$ electrochemical cell. Since tin is lower in the standard emf series ( table 16.1 ), we will begin by assuming that tin is oxidized and lead is reduced, as

$$
\mathrm{Sn}+\mathrm{Pb}^{2+} \rightarrow \mathrm{Sn}^{2+}+\mathrm{Pb}
$$

such that equation (\Delta V=\left(V_2^0-V_1^0\right)-\frac{0.0592}{n} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{M}_1^{n+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{M}_2^{n+}\right]}) takes the form

$$
\Delta V=\left(V{\mathrm{Pb}}^{0}-V{\mathrm{Sn}}^{0}\right)-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{Sn}^{2+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}\right]}
$$

 table 16.1  gives the following standard electrode potentials:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& V{\mathrm{Pb}}^{0}=-0.126 \mathrm{~V} \\
& V{\mathrm{Sn}}^{0}=-0.136 \mathrm{~V}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the voltage of this electrochemical cell is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta V=\left(V{\mathrm{Pb}}^{0}-V{\mathrm{Sn}}^{0}\right)-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{Sn}^{2+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}\right]} \\
=[-0.126 \mathrm{~V}-(-0.136 \mathrm{~V})]-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \left[\frac{0.25 \mathrm{M}}{5 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{M}}\right] \\
=-0.0107 \mathrm{~V}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for us to determine whether or not a voltage is generated in a $\mathrm{Fe} / \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ concentration cell, and, if so, its magnitude. Let us label the Fe cell having a $0.5 \mathrm{M} \mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ solution as cell 1 , and the other as cell 2 . Furthermore, assume that oxidation occurs within cell 2 , wherein $\left[\mathrm{Fe}{2}^{2+}\right]=2 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{M}$. Hence, we write the electrochemical reaction as follows:

$$
\mathrm{Fe}{2}+\mathrm{Fe}{1}^{2+} \rightarrow \mathrm{Fe}{2}^{2+}+\mathrm{Fe}{1}
$$

and, employing equation (\Delta V=\left(V_2^0-V_1^0\right)-\frac{0.0592}{n} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{M}_1^{n+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{M}_2^{n+}\right]}) leads to

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta V=-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \frac{\mathrm{Fe}{2}^{2+}}{\mathrm{Fe}{1}^{2+}} \\
=-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \frac{2 \times 10^{-2} M}{0.5 M}=+0.0414 \mathrm{~V}
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, a voltage of 0.0414 V is generated when oxidation occurs in cell 2 , the one having the lower $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ concentration-i.e., $2 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{M}$.

We are asked to calculate the concentration of $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ions in a copper-cadmium electrochemical cell. The electrochemical reaction that occurs within this cell is as follows:

$$
\mathrm{Cd}+\mathrm{Cu}^{2+} \rightarrow \mathrm{Cd}^{2+}+\mathrm{Cu}
$$

while $\Delta V=0.775 \mathrm{~V}$ and $\left[\mathrm{Cd}^{2+}\right]=6.5 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{M}$. Thus, equation (\Delta V=\left(V_2^0-V_1^0\right)-\frac{0.0592}{n} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{M}_1^{n+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{M}_2^{n+}\right]}) is written in the following form (taking $n=$ 2 since 2 electrons are involved in the above reaction):

$$
\Delta V=\left(V{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{o}}-V{\mathrm{Cd}}^{\mathrm{o}}\right)-\frac{0.0592}{2} \log \frac{\left[\mathrm{Cd}^{2+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\right]}
$$

Furthermore, this equation may be rewritten as follows:

$$
-\frac{\Delta V-\left(V{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{o}}-V{\mathrm{Cd}}^{\mathrm{o}}\right)}{0.0296}=\log \frac{\left[\mathrm{Cd}^{2+}\right]}{\left[\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\right]}
$$

Solving this expression for $\left[\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\right]$ yields the following equation:

$$
\left[\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\right]=\left[\mathrm{Cd}^{2+}\right] \exp \left[+(2.303) \frac{\Delta V-\left(V{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{o}}-V{\mathrm{Cd}}^{\mathrm{o}}\right)}{0.0296}\right]
$$

The standard potentials from  table 16.1  are as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& V{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{o}}=+0.340 \mathrm{~V} \\
& V{\mathrm{Cd}}^{\mathrm{o}}=-0.403 \mathrm{~V}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, we compute the concentration of the copper ion as

$$
\begin{gathered}
{\left[\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}\right]=\left(6.5 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{M}\right) \exp \left[+(2.303) \frac{0.775 \mathrm{~V}-\{0.340 \mathrm{~V}-(-0.403 \mathrm{~V})\}}{0.0296}\right]} \\
=0.784 \mathrm{M}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for us to compute the time of submersion of a metal plate. In order to solve this problem, we must first rearrange equation (\mathrm{CPR}=\frac{K W}{\rho A t}) such that time, $t$, is the dependent variable:

$$
t=\frac{K W}{\rho A(\mathrm{CPR})}
$$

Thus, using values for the various parameters given in the problem statement yields the following value for $t$ :

$$
\begin{gathered}
t=\frac{(87.6)(7.6 \mathrm{~kg})\left(10^{6} \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}\right)}{\left(4.5 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(800 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}\right)(4 \mathrm{~mm} / \mathrm{yr})} \\
=4.62 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~h}=5.27 \mathrm{yr}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks for us to calculate the CPR in both mpy and $\mathrm{mm} / \mathrm{yr}$ for a thick steel sheet of area $100 \mathrm{in.}^{2}$ which experiences a weight loss of 485 g after one year. Employment of equation (\mathrm{CPR}=\frac{K W}{\rho A t}) (and taking the density of steel to be $7.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$) leads to the following CPR values

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{CPR}(\mathrm{~mm} / \mathrm{yr})=\frac{K W}{\rho A t} \\
=\frac{(87.6)(485 \mathrm{~g})\left(10^{3} \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{g}\right)}{\left(7.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(100 \mathrm{in.}^{2}\right)(2.54 \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{in.})^{2}(24 \mathrm{~h} / \mathrm{day})(365 \mathrm{day} / \mathrm{yr})(1 \mathrm{yr})} \\
=0.952 \mathrm{~mm} / \mathrm{yr}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now for the CPR in mpy we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{CPR}(\mathrm{mpy})=\frac{(534)(485 \mathrm{~g})\left(10^{3} \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{g}\right)}{\left(7.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)\left(100 \mathrm{in.}^{2}\right)(24 \mathrm{~h} / \mathrm{day})(365 \mathrm{day} / \mathrm{yr})(1 \mathrm{yr})} \\
=37.4 \mathrm{mpy}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we calculate the values of $c{v}$ for aluminum and iron at room temperature using equation (c_p-c_v=\frac{\alpha_v^2 v_0 T}{\beta}), the data in  table 17.1 , given that $\alpha{v}=3 \alpha{l}$, and also values of the compressibility. Rearrangement of equation (c_p-c_v=\frac{\alpha_v^2 v_0 T}{\beta}) such that $c{v}$ is the dependent variable leads to the following:

$$
c{v}=c{p}-\frac{\alpha{v}^{2} v{0} T}{\beta}
$$

And, from  table 17.1  and the problem statement we have the following values for parameters in this equation for both Al and Fe :

$$
\begin{aligned}
& c{p}(\mathrm{Al})=900 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K} \\
& c{p}(\mathrm{Fe})=448 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K} \\
& \alpha{\mathrm{v}}(\mathrm{Al})=(3)\left[23.6 \times 10^{-6}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1}\right]=7.08 \times 10^{-5}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1} \\
& \alpha{\mathrm{v}}(\mathrm{Fe})=(3)\left[\left(11.8 \times 10^{-6}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1}\right]=3.54 \times 10^{-5}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1}\right. \\
& \beta(\mathrm{Al})=1.77 \times 10^{-11}(\mathrm{~Pa})^{-1} \\
& \beta(\mathrm{Fe})=2.65 \times 10^{-12}(\mathrm{~Pa})^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

The specific volume is just the reciprocal of the density; thus, for units of $\mathrm{m}^{3} / \mathrm{kg}$

$$
v{0}(\mathrm{Al})=\frac{1}{\rho}=\left(\frac{1}{2.71 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)\left(\frac{1000 \mathrm{~g}}{\mathrm{~kg}}\right)\left(\frac{1 \mathrm{~m}}{100 \mathrm{~cm}}\right)^{3}=3.69 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{3} / \mathrm{kg}
$$

$$
v{0}(\mathrm{Fe})=\left(\frac{1}{7.87 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)\left(\frac{1000 \mathrm{~g}}{\mathrm{~kg}}\right)\left(\frac{1 \mathrm{~m}}{100 \mathrm{~cm}}\right)^{3}=1.27 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{3} / \mathrm{kg}
$$

Therefore, we compute the value of $c{v}$ for aluminum as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
c{v}(\mathrm{Al})=c{p}(\mathrm{Al})-\frac{\alpha{v}^{2}(\mathrm{Al}) v{0}(\mathrm{Al}) T}{\beta(\mathrm{Al})} \\
=900 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K}-\frac{\left[7.08 \times 10^{-5}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1}\right]^{2}\left(3.69 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{3} / \mathrm{kg}\right)(293 \mathrm{~K})}{1.77 \times 10^{-11}\left(\mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)^{-1}} \\
=869 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

Likewise for iron:

$$
\begin{gathered}
c{v}(\mathrm{Fe})=448 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K}-\frac{\left[3.54 \times 10^{-5}\left({ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)^{-1}\right]^{2}\left(1.27 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}^{3} / \mathrm{kg}\right)(293 \mathrm{~K})}{2.65 \times 10^{-12}\left(\mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)^{-1}} \\
=430 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{kg}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks that we treat a porous material as a composite wherein one of the phases is a pore phase, and that we estimate upper and lower limits for the room-temperature thermal conductivity of an aluminum oxide material having a 0.25 volume fraction of pores. The upper limit of $k\left(k{\text {upper }}\right)$ may be determined using equation (E_c(u)=E_m V_m+E_p V_p) with thermal conductivity substituted for the elastic modulus, $E$. From  table 17.1 , the value of $k$ for $\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}$ is $39 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}$, while for still air in the pore phase, $k=0.02 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}$. Thus, using the modified form of equation (E_c(u)=E_m V_m+E_p V_p), the upper limit of the thermal conductivity is determined as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
k{\text {upper }}=V{p} k{\text {air }}+V{\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}} k{\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}} \\
=(0.25)(0.02 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})+(0.75)(39 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}) \\
=29.3 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

For the lower limit we employ a modification of equation (E_c(l)=\frac{E_m E_p}{V_m E_p+V_p E_m}) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
k{\text {lower }}=\frac{k{\text {air }} k{\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}}}{V{p} k{\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}}+V{\mathrm{Al}{2} \mathrm{O}{3}} k{\text {air }}} \\
=\frac{(0.02 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})(39 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})}{(0.25)(39 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})+(0.75)(0.02 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K})}=0.080 \mathrm{~W} / \mathrm{m}-\mathrm{K}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) We calculate the magnetic field strength generated by this coil using equation (H=\frac{N I}{l}) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
H=\frac{N I}{l} \\
=\frac{(400 \text { turns })(15 \mathrm{~A})}{0.25 \mathrm{~m}}=24,000 \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{turns} / \mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) In a vacuum, the flux density is determined using equation (B_0=\mu_0 H). Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
B{0}=\mu{0} H \\
=\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)(24,000 \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{turns} / \mathrm{m})=3.0168 \times 10^{-2} \text { tesla }
\end{gathered}
$$

(c) When a bar of chromium is positioned within the coil, we must combine equation ((B=\mu_0 H+\mu_0 M) and (M=\chi_m H)) in order to compute the flux density given the magnetic susceptibility. Inasmuch as $\chi{m}=3.13 \times 10^{-4}$ ( table 18.2 ), then

$$
\begin{gathered}
B=\mu{0} H+\mu{0} M \\
=\mu{0} H+\mu{0} \chi{m} H \\
=\mu{0} H\left(1+\chi{m}\right) \\
=\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)(24,000 \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{turns} / \mathrm{m})\left(1+3.13 \times 10^{-4}\right) \\
=3.0177 \times 10^{-2} \text { tesla }
\end{gathered}
$$

which is essentially the same result as part (b). This is to say that the influence of the chromium bar within the coil makes an imperceptible difference in the magnitude of the $B$ field.
(d) The magnetization is computed from equation (M=\chi_m H) as follows:

$$
M=\chi{m} H=\left(3.13 \times 10^{-4}\right)(24,000 \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{turns} / \mathrm{m})=7.51 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}
$$

(a) The magnetic permeability of this material may be determined according to a rearranged form of equation (B=\mu H) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu=\frac{B}{H} \\
=\frac{0.630 \text { tesla }}{5 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}}=1.260 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) The magnetic susceptibility is calculated using a combined form of equation ((\mu_r=\frac{\mu}{\mu_0}) and (\chi_m=\mu_r-1)) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\chi{m}=\mu{r}-1=\frac{\mu}{\mu{0}}-1 \\
=\frac{1.260 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}}{1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}}-1=2.387 \times 10^{-3}
\end{gathered}
$$

We want to confirm that there are 1.72 Bohr magnetons associated with each cobalt atom. Therefore, let $n{\mathrm{B}}^{s}$ be the number of Bohr magnetons per atom, which we will calculate. This is possible using a modified and rearranged form of equation (M_s=0.60 \mu_{\mathrm{B}} N)-that is

$$
n{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\frac{M{s}}{\mu{\mathrm{B}} N}
$$

Now, $N$ is just the number of atoms per cubic meter, which is the number of atoms per unit cell (six for HCP) divided by the unit cell volume--that is,

$$
N=\frac{6}{V{C}}
$$

which, when substituted into equation (n_{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\frac{M_s}{\mu_{\mathrm{B}} N}) gives the following expression:

$$
n{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\frac{M{s} V{C}}{6 \mu{\mathrm{B}}}
$$

The unit cell volume for HCP metals is given in equation (\begin{aligned}
V_C =\frac{3 a^2 c \sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{aligned}) as follows:

$$
V{C}=\frac{3 a^{2} c \sqrt{3}}{2}
$$

And since $c=1.623 a$ (as given in the problem statement), we rewrite the above equation as follows:

$$
V{C}=\frac{3 a^{2}(1.632 a) \sqrt{3}}{2}
$$

Furthermore, for HCP the unit cell parameter $a$ and the atomic radius are related as follows:

$$
$a=2 R$
$$

such that we may rewrite the preceding equation as

$$
\begin{aligned}
V{C}= & \frac{(3)(1.632)(2 R)^{3} \sqrt{3}}{2} \\
& =19.58 R^{3} \sqrt{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

The atomic radius, $R$, was given in the problem statement as 0.1253 nm or $0.1253 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}$. We now compute the unit cell volume for cobalt as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
V{C}=(19.58)\left(0.1253 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}(\sqrt{3}) \\
=6.67 \times 10^{-29} \mathrm{~m}^{3}
\end{gathered}
$$

We now compute the number of Bohr magnetons per cobalt atom using equation (n_{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\frac{M_s V_C}{6 \mu_{\mathrm{B}}}), given above as

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\frac{M{s} V{C}}{6 \mu{\mathrm{B}}} \\
=\frac{\left(1.45 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(6.67 \times 10^{-29} \mathrm{~m}^{3} / \text { unit cell }\right)}{\left(6 \text { \frac{atoms}{unit} cell }\right)\left(9.27 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{m}^{2} / \text { Bohr magneton }\right)} \\
=1.74 \text { Bohr \frac{magnetons}{atom} }
\end{gathered}
$$

This value is very close to the 1.72 Bohr \frac{magnetons}{atom} cited in the problem statement.

We are to determine the number of Bohr magnetons per atom for a hypothetical metal that has a simple cubic crystal structure, an atomic radius of 0.125 nm , and a saturation flux density of 0.85 tesla. It becomes necessary to employ equation (B \cong \mu_0 M) and a modified form of equation (M_s=0.60 \mu_{\mathrm{B}} N) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{B}=\frac{M}{\mu{\mathrm{B}} N} \\
=\frac{\frac{B{s}}{\mu{0}}}{\mu{\mathrm{B}} N}=\frac{B{s}}{\mu{0} \mu{\mathrm{B}} N}
\end{gathered}
$$

Here $n{\mathrm{B}}$ is the number of Bohr magnetons per atom, and $N$ is just the number of atoms per cubic meter, which is the number of atoms per unit cell [one for simple cubic ( figure 3.3 )] divided by the unit cell volume-that is,

$$
N=\frac{1 \text { \frac{atom}{unit} cell }}{V{C}}
$$

which, when substituted into the above equation gives

$$
n{\mathrm{B}}=\frac{B{s} V{C}}{\mu{0} \mu{\mathrm{B}}}
$$

For the simple cubic crystal structure ( figure 3.3 ), $a=2 R$, where $R$ is the atomic radius, and $V{C}=a^{3}=(2 R)^{3}$. Substituting this relationship into the above equation yields

$$
n{\mathrm{B}}=\frac{B{s}(2 R)^{3}}{\mu{0} \mu{\mathrm{B}}}
$$

Values for the following parameters are provided in the problem statement:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& B{s}=0.85 \text { tesla } \\
& R=0.125 \mathrm{~nm}=0.125 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, we compute the number of Bohr magnetons per atom as follows using the previous equation

$$
\begin{gathered}
n{\mathrm{B}}=\frac{B{s}(2 R)^{3}}{\mu{0} \mu{\mathrm{B}}} \\
=\frac{(0.85 \text { tesla })(8)\left(0.125 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}}{\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(9.27 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~A} \cdot \mathrm{~m}^{2} / \mathrm{BM}\right)}=1.14 \text { Bohr \frac{magnetons}{atom} }
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) This portion of the problem asks that we compute the flux density in a coil of wire 0.5 m long, having 20 turns, and carrying a current of 1.0 A , that is situated in a vacuum. Combining equation ((H=\frac{N I}{l}) and (B_0=\mu_0 H)), and solving for $B$ yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
B{0}=\mu{0} H=\frac{\mu{0} N I}{l} \\
=\frac{\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)(20 \text { turns })(1.0 \mathrm{~A})}{0.5 \mathrm{~m}}=5.03 \times 10^{-5} \text { tesla }
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Now we are to compute the flux density with a bar of the iron-silicon alloy, the $B-H$ behavior for which is shown in  figure 18.29 . It is necessary to determine the value of $H$ using equation (H=\frac{N I}{l}) as follows:

$$
H=\frac{N I}{l}=\frac{(20 \text { turns })(1.0 \mathrm{~A})}{0.5 \mathrm{~m}}=40 \mathrm{~A}-\mathrm{turns} / \mathrm{m}
$$

Using the curve in  figure 18.29 , $B=1.30$ tesla at $H=40$ A-turns $/ \mathrm{m}$.
(c) Finally, we are to assume that a bar of Mo is situated within the coil, and to calculate the current that is necessary to produce the same $B$ field as when the iron-silicon alloy in part (b) was used. Molybdenum is a paramagnetic material having a $\chi{m}$ of $1.19 \times 10^{-4}$ ( table 18.2 ). Combining equation ((B=\mu H), (\mu_r=\frac{\mu}{\mu_0}) and (\chi_m=\mu_r-1)) and solving for $H$ leads to the following expression:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& H=\frac{B}{\mu} \\
& =\frac{B}{\mu{0} \mu{r}}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
=\frac{B}{\mu{0}\left(1+\chi{m}\right)}
$$

When Mo is positioned within the coil, then, from the above equation

$$
H=\frac{1.30 \text { tesla }}{\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(1+1.19 \times 10^{-4}\right)}=1.034 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~A} \text {-turns } / \mathrm{m}
$$

Now, the current may be determined using a rearranged form of equation (H=\frac{N I}{l}) as follows:

$$
I=\frac{H I}{N}=\frac{\left(1.034 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~A} \text {-turns } / \mathrm{m}\right)(0.5 \mathrm{~m})}{20 \text { turns }}=25,850 \mathrm{~A}
$$

In order to demagnetize a magnet having a coercivity of $7000 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}$, an $H$ field of $7000 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}$ must be applied in a direction opposite to that of magnetization. According to equation (H=\frac{N I}{l})

$$
\begin{gathered}
I=\frac{H l}{N} \\
=\frac{(7000 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m})(0.25 \mathrm{~m})}{150 \text { turns }}=11.7 \mathrm{~A}
\end{gathered}
$$

(a) Given equation (H_C(T)=H_C(0)\left(1-\frac{T^2}{T_C^2}\right)) and the data in  table 18.7 , we are asked to calculate the critical magnetic fields for lead at 2.5 and 5.0 K . From the table, for $\mathrm{Pb}, T{C}=7.19 \mathrm{~K}$ and $B{C}(0)=0.0803$ tesla. Thus, from a rearranged form of equation (B=\mu H) we write the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
H{C}(0)=\frac{B{C}(0)}{\mu{0}} \\
=\frac{0.0803 \text { tesla }}{1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}}=6.39 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, solving for $H{C}(2.5)$ and $H{C}(5.0)$ using equation (H_C(T)=H_C(0)\left(1-\frac{T^2}{T_C^2}\right)) yields

$$
\begin{gathered}
H{C}(T)=H{C}(0)\left[1-\frac{T^{2}}{T{C}^{2}}\right] \\
H{C}(2.5)=\left(6.39 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left[1-\frac{(2.5 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}{(7.19 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}\right]=5.62 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m} \\
H{C}(5.0)=\left(6.39 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left[1-\frac{(5.0 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}{(7.19 \mathrm{~K})^{2}}\right]=3.30 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

(b) Now we are to determine the temperature to which lead must be cooled in a magnetic field of 15,000 $\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{m}$ in order for it to be superconductive. All we need do is to solve for $T$ from equation (H_C(T)=H_C(0)\left(1-\frac{T^2}{T_C^2}\right))-i.e.,

$$
T=T{C} \sqrt{1-\frac{H{C}(T)}{H{C}(0)}}
$$

And, since the value of $H{C}(0)$ was computed in part (a), then

$$
T=(7.19 \mathrm{~K}) \sqrt{1-\frac{15,000 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}}{63,900 \mathrm{~A} / \mathrm{m}}}=6.29 \mathrm{~K}
$$

In order to compute the frequency $v$ of a photon of green light, we use a rearranged form of equation (c=\lambda \nu) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
v=\frac{c}{\lambda} \\
=\frac{3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}}{5 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=6 \times 10^{14} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

Now, for the energy computation, we employ equation (E=h \nu=\frac{h c}{\lambda}) as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
E=\frac{h c}{\lambda} \\
=\frac{\left(6.63 \times 10^{-34} \mathrm{~J}-\mathrm{s}\right)\left(3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}\right)}{5 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=3.98 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J} \quad(2.48 \mathrm{eV})
\end{gathered}
$$

We want to compute the velocity of light in diamond given that $\varepsilon{r}=5.5$ and $\chi{m}=-2.17 \times 10^{-5}$. The velocity is determined using equation (v=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\varepsilon \mu}}); but first, we must calculate the values of $\varepsilon$ and $\mu$ for diamond. According to equation (\varepsilon_r=\frac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0})

$$
\varepsilon=\varepsilon{r} \varepsilon{0}=(5.5)\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)=4.87 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}
$$

Now, combining equations leads to the following:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mu=\mu{0} \mu{r}=\mu{0}\left(\chi{m}+1\right) \\
=\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left[1+\left(-2.17 \times 10^{-5}\right)\right]=1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}
\end{gathered}
$$

And, finally, from equation (v=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\varepsilon \mu}}) the velocity of light is computed as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
v=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\varepsilon \mu}} \\
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(4.87 \times 10^{-11} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(1.257 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{H} / \mathrm{m}\right)}} \\
=1.28 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem calls for a calculation of the reflectivity between two quartz grains having different orientations and indices of refraction ( 1.544 and 1.553 ) in the direction of light propagation, when the light is at normal incidence to the grain boundary. We must employ equation (R=\left(\frac{n_2-n_1}{n_2+n_1}\right)^2) since the beam is normal to the grain boundary. Thus,

$$
\begin{gathered}
R=\frac{\left(n{2}-n{1}\right)^{2}}{\left(n{2}+n{1}\right)^{2}} \\
=\frac{(1.553-1.544)^{2}}{(1.553+1.544)^{2}} \\
=8.45 \times 10^{-6}
\end{gathered}
$$

This problem asks us to determine the range of visible light wavelengths over which $\mathrm{ZnSe}\left(E{g}=2.58 \mathrm{eV}\right)$ is transparent. Only photons having energies of 2.58 eV or greater are absorbed by valence-band-to-conduction-band electron transitions. Thus, photons having energies less than 2.58 eV are not absorbed; the minimum photon energy for visible light is 1.8 eV (equation (E_g(\min )=\frac{h c}{\lambda(\max )})), which corresponds to a wavelength of $0.7 \mu \mathrm{~m}$. From a rearranged form of equation (E=h \nu=\frac{h c}{\lambda}), the wavelength of a photon having an energy of 2.58 eV (i.e., the band-gap energy) is just

$$
\begin{gathered}
\lambda=\frac{h c}{E} \\
=\frac{\left(4.13 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{eV}-\mathrm{s}\right)\left(3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}\right)}{2.58 \mathrm{eV}} \\
=4.80 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}=0.48 \mu \mathrm{~m}
\end{gathered}
$$

Thus, pure ZnSe is transparent to visible light having wavelengths between 0.48 and $0.7 \mu \mathrm{~m}$.

This problem asks for the difference in energy between metastable and ground electron states for a ruby laser. The wavelength of the radiation emitted by an electron transition from the metastable to ground state is cited as $0.6943 \mu \mathrm{~m}$. The difference in energy between these states, $\Delta E$, may be determined from a combined form of equation ((\Delta E=h \nu) and (c=\lambda \nu)), as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta E=h v=\frac{h c}{\lambda} \\
=\frac{\left(4.13 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{eV}-\mathrm{s}\right)\left(3 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}\right)}{6.943 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}} \\
=1.78 \mathrm{eV}
\end{gathered}
$$

Using the equation for the total energy of the electron, $E_{\text{tot}} = -\frac{m e^{4}}{8 \varepsilon_{0}^{2} h^{2}}$, we substitute the given values:

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{\text{tot}} & = -\frac{\left(9.1 \times 10^{-31}\right)\left(1.6 \times 10^{-19}\right)^{4}}{8\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12}\right)^{2}\left(6.63 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2}} \\
& = -2.165 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~J} = -13.6 \mathrm{eV}
\end{aligned}
$$

This calculated value of -13.6 eV matches the experimentally derived ground state energy level of the electron in the hydrogen atom. This agreement between theory and experiment was one of the early successes of quantum mechanics. The negative sign indicates that the electron is bound to the proton, with its energy being lower than that of a free electron at an infinite distance, which is defined as zero energy.

The enthalpy content of Al at 298 K is zero by definition. To find the enthalpy content of Al at 900 K, integrate its $c_{p}$ from 298 K to 900 K:

$$
H_{\mathrm{Al}}^{900}-H_{\mathrm{Al}}^{298}=\int_{298}^{900}(20.7+0.0124 T) d T=16.93 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}
$$

For $\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$, at 298 K, its enthalpy content is equal to its enthalpy of formation, $-1675.7 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. To find its enthalpy content at 900 K, integrate its $c_{p}$ from 298 K to 900 K and add the result to its enthalpy of formation:

$$
\begin{gathered}
H_{\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}}^{900}-H_{\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}}^{298}=\int_{298}^{900}\left(106.6+0.0178 T-2,850,000 T^{-2}\right) d T=70.61 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol} \\
\therefore H_{\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}}^{900}=-1675.7+70.61=-1605.0 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{gathered}
$$

