question:
Calculate the chemical stability domains for the phases in the $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{O}$ system at 1000 K, given the following standard free energies of formation:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{FeO}} \text { at } 1000 \mathrm{~K} & = -206.95 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\
\Delta G_{\mathrm{Fe}_{3} \mathrm{O}_{4}} & = -792.6 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\
\Delta G_{\mathrm{Fe}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}} & = -561.8 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Suppose below pressure a, Fe is the stable phase; between an and b, FeO is stable; between b and c, Fe3O4 is stable; above c, Fw2O3 is stable. 


Give your answer as a tuple (pressure a, pressure b, pressure c)

solution:
(a) The pertinent reaction and its corresponding equilibrium mass action expression are, respectively,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Mg}+\frac{1}{2} \mathrm{O}_{2} & \Rightarrow \mathrm{MgO}(s) \\
\Delta G^{\circ}=-R T \ln K & =-R T \ln \frac{a_{\mathrm{MgO}}}{a_{\mathrm{Mg}} P_{\mathrm{O}_{2}^{1 / 2}}^{1 / 2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the MgO that forms in this case is pure, i.e., in its standard state (e.g., not in solid solution), it follows that by definition $a_{\mathrm{MgO}}=1$ on either side. On the metal side, $a_{\mathrm{Mg}}=1.0$, and solving for $P_{\mathrm{O}_{2}}$ yields $3.2 \times 10^{-52} \mathrm{~atm}$. or $3.2 \times 10^{-53} \mathrm{MPa}$.

Conversely, on the oxygen side, $P_{\mathrm{O}_{2}}=1 \mathrm{~atm}$. and $a_{\mathrm{Mg}}$ is calculated to be

$$
a_{\mathrm{Mg}}=1.8 \times 10^{-26}
$$

Based on the figures of merit stated, the electronic conductivity should not exceed

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma_{\text {elec }} & =t_{e} \sigma_{\text {tot }} \approx t_{e} \sigma_{\text {ion }}=0.01 \times 10^{-4}=1 \times 10^{-6}(\Omega \cdot \mathrm{cm})^{-1} \\
& =1 \times 10^{-4}(\Omega \cdot \mathrm{m})^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Inserting this value for $\sigma_{\text {elec }}$ in Eq. $\sigma = e \mu_n n + e \mu_p p = ne(\mu_n + \mu_p)$, assuming $\mu_{c}=\mu_{p}=0.01 \mathrm{m}^{2} /(\mathrm{V} \cdot \mathrm{s})$ at 1000 K, and solving for $n$ yields

$$
n=\frac{1 \times 10^{-4}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19}(0.01+0.01)}=3.12 \times 10^{18} \text { electrons } / \mathrm{m}^{3}
$$

Furthermore by assuming that $m_{e}=m_{c}^{*}$, it follows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
N_{c} & =2\left(\frac{2 \pi m_{e}^{*} k T}{h^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2}=2\left(\frac{2 \pi \times 9.1 \times 10^{-31} \times 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 1000}{\left(6.63 \times 10^{-34}\right)^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \\
& =1.5 \times 10^{26} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, assuming $N_{c}=N_{c}$, substituting the appropriate values in Eq. $n = p = \sqrt{N_c N_v} \, \exp\left( \frac{-E_g}{2kT} \right)$ and solving for $E_{g}$ give

$$
E_{g}=-2 k T \ln \frac{n}{N_{c}}=-2 \times 1000 \times 8.62 \times 10^{-5} \ln \frac{3.12 \times 10^{16}}{1.5 \times 10^{26}}=3.84 \mathrm{eV}
$$

(a) Converting to SI units and applying Eq. $r_c = \frac{2 \gamma_{sl} V_m}{\Delta H_f \left(1 - \frac{T}{T_m} \right)}$, one obtains
$$
r_c=\frac{2 \gamma_{\mathrm{sl}} V_m}{\Delta H_f\left(1-T / T_m\right)}=\frac{2\left(150 \times 10^{-3}\right)\left(60 \times 10^{-6}\right)}{53.000(0.38)}=8.93 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}
$$


Given that the $\mathrm{Si}-\mathrm{Si}$ distance in silicates is on the order of $3 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}$, this result is not unreasonable - the critical radius would appear to be made of a few $\mathrm{SiO}_4$ tetrahedra. The corresponding $\Delta G_c[(\mathrm{Eq}$. $\Delta G_c = \frac{16 \pi \gamma_{sl}^3 V_m^2}{3 \Delta H_f^2 \left(1 - \frac{T}{T_m} \right)^2}$] is
$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta G_c & =\frac{16 \pi \gamma_{s 1}^3 V_m^2}{3 \Delta H_f^2\left(1-T / T_m\right)^2}=\frac{16(3.14)\left(150 \times 10^{-3}\right)^3\left(60 \times 10^{-6}\right)^2}{3(53,000)^2(0.38)^2} \\
& \approx 5 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}
\end{aligned}
$$

With 1 mol as a basis, $N_\nu$ is simply $N_{\mathrm{Av}} / V_m$, or $1 \times 10^{22}$ molecular units per cubic centimeter; it follows [Eq. $N_n^{\text{eq}} = N_\nu \left[ \exp\left( \frac{-\Delta G_c}{kT} \right) \right]$] that
$$
\begin{aligned}
N_n^{\mathrm{eq}} & =N_\nu\left[\exp \left(-\frac{\Delta G_c}{k T}\right)\right]=1 \times 10^{22} \exp \left(-\frac{5 \times 10^{-19}}{1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 807}\right) \\
& =317 \text { nuclei } / \mathrm{cm}^3
\end{aligned}
$$

(a) If the molar volume is $10 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} / \mathrm{mol}$, then $\Omega=1.66 \times 10^{-29} \mathrm{~m}^{3}$. According to convention, $\sigma_{11}=-20 \mathrm{MPa}$ and $\sigma_{22}=-10 \mathrm{MPa}$, and the net energy recovered is given by Eq. $\Delta W_{A \Rightarrow B} = \Omega (P_B - P_A) = \Omega (\sigma_{11} - \sigma_{22})$, or 

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta W_{A \Rightarrow B} & =1.66 \times 10^{-29} \times 10^{6}\{-20-(-10)\} \\
& =-1.66 \times 10^{-22} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{atom}=-100 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

(b) Assuming the applied stress is 100 MPa, one obtains 

$$
\Omega \sigma=1.66 \times 10^{-29} \times 100 \times 10^{6}=1.66 \times 10^{-21} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{atom}=1000 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
$$

For the second part, assume Young's modulus to be 150 GPa. The elastic energy associated with a volume $\Omega$ is given by [see Eq. $U_{\text{elas}} = \frac{1}{2} \varepsilon \sigma_{\text{app}} = \frac{1}{2} \frac{\sigma_{\text{app}}^2}{Y}$] 

$$
\begin{aligned}
U_{\text {elas }} & =\frac{\Omega}{2} \frac{\sigma^{2}}{Y}=\frac{1}{2} \frac{\left(1.66 \times 10^{-29}\right)\left(100 \times 10^{6}\right)}{150 \times 10^{9}} \\
& =5.53 \times 10^{-25} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{atom}=0.33 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

which is roughly 3 orders of magnitude smaller than the $\sigma \Omega$ term. The fundamental conclusion is that atom movements that result in shape changes are much more energetically favorable than ones that do not result in such changes.

