In a cubic crystal, the normal to a plane has the same indices as the plane itself, thus the normal to the plane $(111)$ is the direction $[111]$. Also, in a cubic crystal, the cosine of the angle between two directions is determined by the dot product of the unit vectors in those directions. Specifically, the cosine of the angle between the directions $[u_1 v_1 w_1]$ and $[u_2 v_2 w_2]$ is given by:
\[
\cos{\theta} = \frac{u_1 u_2 + v_1 v_2 + w_1 w_2}{\sqrt{(u_1^2 + v_1^2 + w_1^2)(u_2^2 + v_2^2 + w_2^2)}}
\]
Now, if we designate the direction $[210]$ as $x$, the direction $[10\overline{1}]$ as $d$, and the direction $[111]$ as $n$, then the shear stress component $\tau_{nd}$ is calculated as:
\[
\tau_{nd} = \ell_{nx}\ell_{dx}\sigma_{xx}
\]
We have:
\[
\ell_{nx} = \frac{(2 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 1 + 0 \cdot 1)}{\sqrt{(2^2 + 1^2 + 0^2)(1^2 + 1^2 + 1^2)}}
= \frac{3}{\sqrt{5 \cdot 3}}
= \frac{3}{\sqrt{15}}
\]
and
\[
\ell_{dx} = \frac{(2 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot \overline{1})}{\sqrt{(2^2 + 1^2 + 0^2)(1^2 + 0^2 + (\overline{1})^2)}}
= \frac{2}{\sqrt{5 \cdot 2}}
= \frac{2}{\sqrt{10}}
\]
Therefore,
\[
\tau_{nd} = \frac{3}{\sqrt{15}} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{10}} \cdot 2.8\,\mathrm{MPa}
= 2.8 \cdot \frac{6}{\sqrt{150}}
= 2.8 \cdot \frac{6}{5\sqrt{6}}
= \frac{16.8}{5\sqrt{6}}
\]
Simplifying numerically gives:
\[
\tau_{nd} \approx 1.372\,\mathrm{MPa}
\]

First make a cut perpendicular to the axis of the tube, and consider the vertical (y-direction) forces. The force from the pressurization is the pressure, $P$, acting on the end area of the tube, $P \pi D^2 / 4$. The force in the wall is the stress, $\sigma_{y}$, acting on the cross-section of the wall, $\sigma_{y} \pi D t$. Balancing the forces, $P \pi D^2 / 4 = \sigma_{y} \pi D t$, and solving for $\sigma_{y}$,
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{y} = \frac{P D}{4 t}
\end{equation}

The hoop stress, $\sigma_{x}$, can be found from a force balance across a vertical cut). The force acting to separate the tube is the pressure, $P$, acting on the internal area, $D L$, where $L$ is the tube length. This is balanced by the hoop stress in the two walls, $\sigma_{x}$, acting on the cross-sectional area of the two walls, $2 L t$. (The force in the capped ends is neglected because the tube is long, and we are interested in the stress in regions remote from the ends.) Equating these two forces, $P D L = \sigma_{x} 2 L t$,
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{x} = \frac{P D}{2 t} = 2 \sigma_{y}
\end{equation}

The stress in the radial direction though the wall thickness, $\sigma_{z}$, is negligible relative to $\sigma_{x}$ and $\sigma_{y}$ if $D \gg t$. On the inside surface, $\sigma_{z} = -P$, and on the outside surface, $\sigma_{z} = 0$. The average, $-P / 2$, is much less than $P D /(2 t)$, so for engineering purposes we can take $\sigma_{z} = 0$.

Therefore, the largest stress is $\frac{P D}{2 t}$.

Consider a differential element of dimensions $(2 \pi r)(dr)$ in a tubular element at a radius, $r$, from the axis and of thickness, $dr$. The shear force acting on this element is the shear stress times the area, $\tau_{xy}(2 \pi r)(dr)$. The torque about the central axis caused by this element is the shear force times the distance from the axis, $r$, $dT = \tau_{xy}(2 \pi r)(r) dr$, so
\begin{equation}
T = 2 \pi \int_0^{R} \tau_{xy} r^2 dr
\end{equation}

First, realize that with a constant ratio of stresses, $\mathrm{d}\varepsilon_2 : \mathrm{d}\varepsilon_1 = \varepsilon_2 : \varepsilon_1$. Also, if the tools did not touch the surface, it can be assumed that $\sigma_3 = 0$. Then according to equation ($\begin{aligned} \mathrm{d} \varepsilon_1 & =\mathrm{d} \lambda\left[2\left(\sigma_1-\sigma_2\right)-2\left(\sigma_3-\sigma_1\right)\right] / 4=\mathrm{dl} \cdot\left[\sigma_1-\left(\sigma_2+\sigma_3\right) / 2\right] \\ \mathrm{d} \varepsilon_2 & =\mathrm{d} \lambda\left[\sigma_2-\left(\sigma_3+\sigma_1\right) / 2\right] \\ \mathrm{d} \varepsilon_3 & =\mathrm{d} \lambda\left[\sigma_3-\left(\sigma_1+\sigma_2\right) / 2\right]^{* *}\end{aligned}$), $\frac{\varepsilon_2}{\varepsilon_1} = \frac{\mathrm{d}\varepsilon_2}{\mathrm{d}\varepsilon_1} = \frac{\sigma_2 - \sigma_1/2}{\sigma_1 - \sigma_2/2}$. Substituting, $\alpha = \frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1}$, and
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \rho = \frac{\varepsilon_2}{\varepsilon_1}, \quad \frac{\alpha - 1/2}{1 - \alpha/2} = \rho . \text{ Solving for } \alpha, \\
& \alpha = \frac{\rho + 1/2}{\rho/2 + 1} .
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Now substituting $\rho = 0.078/0.18 = 0.4333$, $\alpha = 0.7671$.

First find $m=\cos \lambda \cos \phi$ for $(11 \overline{1})[011]$ slip. In cubic crystals, the normal to a plane has the same indices as the plane, so the normal to $(11 \overline{1})$ is $[11 \overline{1}]$. Also, in cubic crystals, the cosine of the angle between two directions is given by the dot product of unit vectors in those directions. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\cos \phi &= \frac{(4 \cdot 1 + 3 \cdot 1 + 2 \cdot \overline{1})}{\left[\sqrt{(4^2 + 3^2 + 2^2)} \sqrt{(1^2 + 1^2 + \overline{1}^2)}\right]} = \frac{5}{\sqrt{29} \sqrt{3}} \\
\cos \lambda &= \frac{(4 \cdot 0 + 3 \cdot 1 + 2 \cdot 1)}{\left[\sqrt{(4^2 + 3^2 + 2^2)} \sqrt{(0^2 + 1^2 + 1^2)}\right]} = \frac{5}{\sqrt{29} \sqrt{2}} \\
m &= \cos \lambda \cos \phi = \frac{25}{29 \sqrt{6}} = 0.352 \\
\tau &= m \sigma = 0.352 \times 5 \, \text{kPa} = 1.76 \, \text{kPa}
\end{align*}

$\tau_{nd} = \ell_n x \, \ell_d x \, \sigma_x + \ell_n z + \ell_d z \, \sigma_z$, where $d = [101]$, and $n = [11\overline{1}]$. Taking dot products,
\begin{align*}
\ell_n x &= [11\overline{1}] \cdot [100] = \frac{(1 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 0 + \overline{1} \cdot 0)}{\sqrt{(1^2 + 1^2 + \overline{1}^2)(1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2)}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \\
\ell_d x &= [101] \cdot [100] = \frac{(1 \cdot 1 + 0 \cdot 0 + 1 \cdot 0)}{\sqrt{(1^2 + 0^2 + 1^2)(1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2)}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
\ell_n z &= [11\overline{1}] \cdot [001] = \frac{(1 \cdot 0 + 1 \cdot 0 + \overline{1} \cdot 1)}{\sqrt{(1^2 + 1^2 + \overline{1}^2)(0^2 + 0^2 + 1^2)}} = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \\
\ell_d z &= [101] \cdot [001] = \frac{(1 \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot 0 + 1 \cdot 1)}{\sqrt{(1^2 + 0^2 + 1^2)(0^2 + 0^2 + 1^2)}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{align*}
Substituting, $\tau_{nd} = \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right) \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) 15 \, \text{kPa} + \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right) \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) 7.5 \, \text{kPa} = \frac{7.5}{\sqrt{6}} \, \text{kPa} = 3.06 \, \text{kPa}$.

Let the $[100]$, $[010]$, and $[001]$ directions be designated as 1, 2, and 3, respectively, and let the slip systems be designated as follows:
$[011](01\overline{1})$ \& $[01\overline{1}](011)$ as Aa, $[101](10\overline{1})$ \& $[10\overline{1}](101)$ as Bb, and $[110](1\overline{1}0)$ \& $[1\overline{1}0](110)$ as Cc.

The strains along the cubic axes can be written as
\begin{align*}
\varepsilon_1 &= \ell_1 A \ell_1 a \gamma_{Aa} + \ell_1 B \ell_1 b \gamma_{Bb} + \ell_1 C \ell_1 c \gamma_{Cc} = 0 + \frac{1}{2} \gamma_{Bb} + \frac{1}{2} \gamma_{Cc} \\
\varepsilon_2 &= \ell_2 A \ell_2 a \gamma_{Aa} + \ell_2 B \ell_2 b \gamma_{Bb} + \ell_2 C \ell_2 c \gamma_{Cc} = \frac{1}{2} \gamma_{Aa} + 0 + \frac{1}{2} \gamma_{Cc} \\
\gamma_{23} &= (\ell_2 A \ell_3 a + \ell_2 a \ell_3 A) \gamma_{Aa} + (\ell_2 B \ell_3 b + \ell_2 b \ell_3 B) \gamma_{Bb} + (\ell_2 C \ell_3 c + \ell_2 c \ell_3 C) \gamma_{Cc} \\
\gamma_{31} &= (\ell_3 A \ell_1 a + \ell_3 a \ell_1 A) \gamma_{Aa} + (\ell_3 B \ell_1 b + \ell_3 b \ell_1 B) \gamma_{Bb} + (\ell_3 C \ell_1 c + \ell_3 c \ell_1 C) \gamma_{Cc} \\
\gamma_{12} &= (\ell_1 A \ell_2 a + \ell_1 a \ell_2 A) \gamma_{Aa} + (\ell_1 B \ell_2 b + \ell_1 b \ell_2 B) \gamma_{Bb} + (\ell_1 C \ell_2 c + \ell_1 c \ell_2 C) \gamma_{Cc}
\end{align*}

Substituting $\ell_1 A = [100] \cdot [110] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$, $\ell_1 a = [100] \cdot [1\overline{1}0] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$, $\ell_1 B = [100] \cdot [101] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$,
\begin{align*}
\ell_1 b &= [100] \cdot [10\overline{1}] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \quad \ell_1 C = [100] \cdot [011] = 0, \quad \ell_1 c = [100] \cdot [01\overline{1}] = 0 \\
\ell_2 A &= [010] \cdot [110] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \quad \ell_2 a = [010] \cdot [1\overline{1}0] = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \quad \ell_2 B = [010] \cdot [101] = 0 \\
\ell_2 b &= [010] \cdot [10\overline{1}] = 0, \quad \ell_2 C = [010] \cdot [011] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \quad \ell_2 c = [010] \cdot [01\overline{1}] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
\ell_3 A &= [001] \cdot [110] = 0, \quad \ell_3 a = [001] \cdot [1\overline{1}0] = 0, \quad \ell_3 B = [001] \cdot [101] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
\ell_3 b &= [001] \cdot [10\overline{1}] = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \quad \ell_3 C = [001] \cdot [011] = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \\
\ell_3 c &= [001] \cdot [01\overline{1}] = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\end{align*}

Substituting $(\ell_2 A \ell_3 a + \ell_2 a \ell_3 A) = (\ell_2 B \ell_3 b + \ell_2 b \ell_3 B) = (\ell_2 C \ell_3 c + \ell_2 c \ell_3 C) = 0$, and so on, it can be concluded that $\gamma_{23} = \gamma_{31} = \gamma_{12} = 0$, so the shear strains $\gamma_{23}$, $\gamma_{31}$, and $\gamma_{12}$ cannot be satisfied. Therefore, there are only two independent strains, $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$, so only two slip systems are independent.

Solving equation for $r/b$,
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
\left(\frac{r}{b}\right)^{2} &= \frac{G}{8 \pi^2 U_{v}} = \frac{77 \times 10^{9} ~\text{Pa}}{8 \pi^2 \times 8.93 \times 10^{3} ~\text{kg} / \text{m}^{3} \times 4.73 \times 10^{6} ~\text{J} / \text{kg}} \\
&= 0.024, \quad \frac{r}{b}=0.16
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

\begin{aligned}
b_3 &= b_1 + b_2 = \frac{a}{2}[110] + a[0 \overline{1} 1] = \left[\frac{a}{2}+0, \frac{a}{2}-a, 0+a\right] = \frac{a}{2}[1 \overline{1} 2] \\
b_1^2 + b_2^2 &= \left(\frac{a}{2}\right)^2(1^2 + 1^2 + 0^2) + a^2[0^2 + (-1)^2 + 1^2] = a^2. \\
b_3^2 &= \left(\frac{a}{2}\right)^2[1^2 + (-1)^2 + 2^2] = 1.5 a^2.
\end{aligned}
Because $b_1^2 + b_2^2 < b_3^2$, the reaction would be energetically unfavorable.

An $x$-direction force balance requires that $\sigma_{\mathrm{xA}}=-\sigma_{\mathrm{xB}}$. If A and $B$ were not attached, A would contract more on cooling than B. They are bonded, however, on a surface parallel to $x$, so $e_{\mathrm{xA}}=e_{\mathrm{xB}}$. Therefore, $\frac{\sigma_{\mathrm{xA}}}{E_{\mathrm{A}}}+\alpha_{\mathrm{A}} \Delta T=\frac{\sigma_{\mathrm{xB}}}{E_{\mathrm{B}}}+\alpha_{\mathrm{B}} \Delta T$. Substituting $\sigma_{\mathrm{xB}}=-\sigma_{\mathrm{xA}}$, we get $\sigma_{\mathrm{xA}}= \frac{(\alpha_{\mathrm{B}}-\alpha_{\mathrm{A}}) \Delta T}{\frac{1}{E_{\mathrm{A}}}+\frac{1}{E_{\mathrm{B}}}}$.

Thus,
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
\sigma_{\mathrm{xA}} & =\frac{(\alpha_{\mathrm{A}}-\alpha_{\mathrm{B}}) \Delta T}{\frac{1}{E_{\mathrm{A}}}+\frac{1}{E_{\mathrm{B}}}} \\
& =\frac{(61.5-15) \times 10^{-6} /{ }^{\circ}\mathrm{C}}{\frac{1}{119}-\frac{1}{34.8}} \mathrm{GPa}=1.2 \mathrm{MPa} /{ }^{\circ}\mathrm{C}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

The number of atoms in 100 g of silver (Ag) can be calculated using the atomic mass of silver and the Avogadro constant. The calculation is as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Number of Ag atoms} & =\frac{(100 \mathrm{~g})\left(6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{atoms} / \mathrm{mol}\right)}{107.868 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
& =5.58 \times 10^{23}
\end{aligned}
$$

This calculation demonstrates how the atomic mass and the Avogadro constant are used to determine the number of atoms in a given mass of an element.

The octahedral sites include the twelve edges of the unit cell, with the coordinates

$$
\begin{array}{llll}
\frac{1}{2}, 0,0 & \frac{1}{2}, 1,0 & \frac{1}{2}, 0,1 & \frac{1}{2}, 1,1 \\
0, \frac{1}{2}, 0 & 1, \frac{1}{2}, 0 & 1, \frac{1}{2}, 1 & 0, \frac{1}{2}, 1 \\
0,0, \frac{1}{2} & 1,0, \frac{1}{2} & 1,1, \frac{1}{2} & 0,1, \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
$$

plus the center position, $1 / 2,1 / 2,1 / 2$. Each of the sites on the edge of the unit cell is shared between four unit cells, so only $1 / 4$ of each site belongs uniquely to each unit cell. Therefore, the number of sites belonging uniquely to each cell is

$$
\frac{12 \text { edges }}{\text { cell }} \cdot \frac{\frac{1}{4} \text { site }}{\text { edge }}+\frac{1 \text { body-center }}{\text { cell }} \cdot \frac{1 \text { site }}{\text { body-center }}=4 \text { octahedral sites/cell }
$$

(a) The lattice must belong to the cubic crystal system. Since different types of atoms are located at the corner, face-centered, and body-centered positions, the lattice must be simple cubic. The structure can be described as a simple cubic lattice with a basis of $\mathrm{Ca}(0,0,0), \mathrm{Ti}(1 / 2,1 / 2,1 / 2)$, and $\mathrm{O}(0,1 / 2,1 / 2),(1 / 2,0,1 / 2)$, and $(1 / 2,1 / 2,0)$.
(b) Using the unit cell concept,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{8 \text { corners }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 / 8 \mathrm{Ca} \text { atom }}{\text { corner }}+\frac{1 \text { body-center }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 \mathrm{Ti} \text { atom }}{\text { body-center }} \\
\quad+\frac{6 \text { face-centers }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 / 2 \mathrm{O} \text { atom }}{\text { face-center }}=\frac{5 \text { atoms }}{\text { unit cell }}
\end{gathered}
$$

The chemical formula for perovskite is $\mathrm{CaTiO}_{3}$.
(c) If calcium is located at the body-centered position rather than the corners of the unit cell, then titanium must be located at the corners of the unit cell, and the oxygen atoms must be located at the edge centers of the unit cell. Another lattice and basis description of perovskite is thus a simple cubic lattice with a basis of $\mathrm{Ca}(1 / 2,1 / 2,1 / 2), \mathrm{Ti}(0,0,0)$, and $\mathrm{O}(1 / 2,0,0),(0,1 / 2,0)$, and $(0,0,1 / 2)$.
(d) Using the unit cell concept,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1 \text { body-center }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 \mathrm{Ca} \text { atom }}{\text { body-center }}+\frac{8 \text { corners }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 / 8 \mathrm{Ti} \text { atom }}{\text { corner }} \\
& \quad+\frac{12 \text { edge centers }}{\text { unit cell }} * \frac{1 / 4 \mathrm{O} \text { atom }}{\text { edge-center }}=\frac{5 \text { atoms }}{\text { unit cell }}
\end{aligned}
$$

Again we find that the chemical formula is $\mathrm{CaTiO}_{3}$.

(a) The planar density is calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Planar density (110)} & =\frac{\text{atoms}}{\text{area}}=\frac{2}{(\sqrt{2})\left(2.866 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{2}} \\
& =1.72 \times 10^{15} \text{ atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{2} \\
\text{Planar density (112)} & =0.994 \times 10^{15} \text{ atoms } / \mathrm{cm}^{2}(\text{ from problem statement })
\end{aligned}
$$

(b) The interplanar spacings are calculated using the formula:

$$
\begin{aligned}
d_{110} & =\frac{2.866 \times 10^{-8}}{\sqrt{1^{2}+1^{2}+0}}=2.0266 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm} \\
d_{112} & =\frac{2.866 \times 10^{-8}}{\sqrt{1^{2}+1^{2}+2^{2}}}=1.17 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

The planar density is higher and the interplanar spacing is larger for the (110) plane than for the (112) plane; therefore, the (110) plane is the preferred slip plane.

Dislocations begin to move when the resolved shear stress $\tau_r$ equals the critical resolved shear stress, 148 psi. From Schmid's law:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tau_r & =\sigma \cos \lambda \cos \phi \text { or } \\
148 \mathrm{psi} & =(500 \mathrm{psi}) \cos \lambda \cos \phi
\end{aligned}
$$


Because we wish slip to occur at a $45^{\circ}$ angle to the axis of the rod, $\lambda=45^{\circ}$, and

$$
\begin{aligned}
\cos \phi & =\frac{148}{500 \cos 45^{\circ}}=0.4186 \\
\phi & =65.3^{\circ}
\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, we must produce a rod that is oriented such that $\lambda=45^{\circ}$ and $\phi=65.3^{\circ}$. Note that $\phi$ and $\lambda$ do not add to $90^{\circ}$.

We might do this by a solidification process. We could orient a seed crystal of solid aluminum at the bottom of a mold. Liquid aluminum could be introduced into the mold. The liquid solidifies at the seed crystal, and a single crystal rod of the proper orientation is produced.

a. First, let's calculate the initial and surface compositions in atomic percent:

$$
\begin{gathered}
c_{i}=\frac{1 \mathrm{P} \text { atom }}{10^{7} \text { atoms }} \times 100=0.00001 \mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{P} \\
c_{s}=\frac{400 \mathrm{P} \text { atoms }}{10^{7} \text { atoms }} \times 100=0.004 \mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{P} \\
\frac{\Delta c}{\Delta x}=\frac{0.00001-0.004 \mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{P}}{0.1 \mathrm{~cm}}=-0.0399 \frac{\mathrm{at} \% \mathrm{P}}{\mathrm{~cm}}
\end{gathered}
$$

b. To find the gradient in terms of $\frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^{3} \cdot \mathrm{~cm}}$, we must find the volume of the unit cell. The lattice parameter is $5.4307 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}$. Thus,

$$
V_{\text {cell }}=\left(5.4307 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}=1.6 \times 10^{-22} \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^{3}}{\mathrm{~cell}}
$$

The volume occupied by $10^{7} \mathrm{Si}$ atoms is

$$
V=\left[\frac{10^{7} \text { atoms }}{8 \frac{\text { atoms }}{\text { cell }}}\right]\left[1.6 \times 10^{-22}\left(\frac{\mathrm{~cm}^{3}}{\text { cell }}\right)\right]=2 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
$$

The compositions in atoms $/ \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ are

$$
\begin{aligned}
& c_{i}=\frac{1 \mathrm{P} \text { atom }}{2 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}}=0.005 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{P}\left(\frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right) \\
& c_{s}=\frac{400 \mathrm{P} \text { atoms }}{2 \times 10^{-16} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}}=2 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{P}\left(\frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the composition gradient is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\Delta c}{\Delta x} & =\frac{0.005 \times 10^{18}-2 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{P}\left(\frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)}{0.1 \mathrm{~cm}} \\
& =-1.995 \times 10^{19} \mathrm{P}\left(\frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^{3} \cdot \mathrm{~cm}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The composition of nickel at the $\mathrm{Ni} / \mathrm{MgO}$ interface is $100 \% \mathrm{Ni}$, or

$$
c_{\mathrm{Ni} / \mathrm{MgO}}=\frac{4 \mathrm{Ni} \frac{\text { atoms }}{\text { unit cell }}}{\left(3.6 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^3}=8.573 \times 10^{22 \frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^3}}
$$


The composition of nickel at the $\mathrm{Ta} / \mathrm{MgO}$ interface is $0 \% \mathrm{Ni}$. Thus, the concentration gradient is

$$
\frac{\Delta c}{\Delta x}=\frac{0-8.573 \times 10^{22} \frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^3}}{0.05 \mathrm{~cm}}=-1.715 \times 10^{24} \frac{\mathrm{atoms}}{\mathrm{~cm}^3 \cdot \mathrm{~cm}}
$$
The flux of nickel atoms through the MgO layer is

$$
\begin{aligned}
& J=-D \frac{\Delta c}{\Delta x}=-\left(9 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~cm}^2 / \mathrm{s}\right)\left(-1.715 \times 10^{\left.24 \frac{\mathrm{atoms}}{\mathrm{~cm}^3 \cdot \mathrm{~cm}}\right)}\right. \\
& J=1.543 \times 10^{13} \frac{\mathrm{Ni} \text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}
\end{aligned}
$$


The total number of nickel atoms crossing the $2 \mathrm{~cm} \times 2 \mathrm{~cm}$ interface per second is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Total } \mathrm{Ni} \text { atoms per second } & =(J)(\text { Area })=\left(1.543 \times 10^{13} \frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}\right)(2 \mathrm{~cm})(2 \mathrm{~cm}) \\
& =6.17 \times 10^{13} \mathrm{Ni} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

The total number of nitrogen atoms in the container is

$$
\left(0.5 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{cm}^3\right)(\pi / 4)(3 \mathrm{~cm})^2(10 \mathrm{~cm})=35.343 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{~N} \text { atoms }
$$


The maximum number of atoms to be lost is $1 \%$ of this total, or

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{N} \text { atom loss per } \mathrm{h} & =(0.01)\left(35.34 \times 10^{20}\right)=35.343 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{~N} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{h} \\
\mathrm{~N} \text { atom loss per } \mathrm{s} & =\left(35.343 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{~N} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{h}\right) /(3600 \mathrm{~s} / \mathrm{h}) \\
& =0.0098 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{~N} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$


The flux is then

$$
\begin{aligned}
J & =\frac{0.0098 \times 10^{18}(\mathrm{~N} \text { atoms } / \mathrm{s})}{\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)(3 \mathrm{~cm})^2} \\
& =0.00139 \times 10^{18} \mathrm{~N} \frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}
\end{aligned}
$$


Using Equation ($D=D_0 \exp \left(\frac{-Q}{R T}\right)$) and values from Table, the diffusion coefficient of nitrogen in BCC iron at $700^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=973 \mathrm{~K}$ is

$$
\begin{gathered}
D=D_0 \exp \left(\frac{-Q}{R T}\right) \\
D_{\mathrm{N}}=0.0047 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~s}} \exp \left[\frac{-18,300 \frac{\mathrm{cal}}{\mathrm{~mol}}}{1.987 \frac{\mathrm{cal}}{\mathrm{~mol} \cdot \mathrm{~K}}(973 \mathrm{~K})}\right] \\
=(0.0047)\left(7.748 \times 10^{-5}\right)=3.64 \times 10^{-7 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~s}}}
\end{gathered}
$$
From Equation ($J=-D \frac{d c}{d x}$):

$$
\begin{gathered}
J=-D\left(\frac{\Delta c}{\Delta x}\right)=0.00139 \times 10^{18} \frac{\mathrm{~N} \text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}} \\
\Delta x=-D \Delta c / J=\frac{\left[\left(-3.64 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~cm}^2 / \mathrm{s}\right)\left(1 \times 10^{18}-50 \times 10^{18} \frac{\mathrm{Natoms}}{\mathrm{~cm}^3}\right)\right]}{0.00139 \times 10^{18} \frac{\mathrm{Natoms}}{\mathrm{~cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}} \\
\Delta x=0.013 \mathrm{~cm}=\text { minimum thickness of the membrane }
\end{gathered}
$$


In a similar manner, the maximum thickness of the membrane that will permit $90 \%$ of the hydrogen to pass can be calculated as

$$
\mathrm{H} \text { atom loss per } \mathrm{h}=(0.90)\left(35.343 \times 10^{20}\right)=31.80 \times 10^{20}
$$


H atom loss per $\mathrm{s}=0.0088 \times 10^{20}$

$$
J=0.125 \times 10^{18} \frac{\mathrm{H} \text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}
$$


From Equation ($D=D_0 \exp \left(\frac{-Q}{R T}\right)$) and Table,

$$
D_{\mathrm{H}}=0.0012 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~s}} \exp \left[\frac{-3,600 \frac{\mathrm{cal}}{\mathrm{~mol}}}{1.987 \frac{\mathrm{cal}}{\mathrm{~K} \cdot \mathrm{~mol}}(973 \mathrm{~K})}\right]=1.86 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~cm}^2 / \mathrm{s}
$$


Since

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Delta x=-D \Delta c / J \\
& \Delta x\left.=\frac{\left(-1.86 \times 10^{-4} \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~s}}\right.}{\Delta}\right)\left(-49 \times 10^{18 \frac{\mathrm{H} \text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^3}}\right) \\
& 0.125 \times 10^{18 \frac{\mathrm{H} \text { atoms }}{\mathrm{cm}^2 \cdot \mathrm{~s}}} \\
&=0.073 \mathrm{~cm}=\text { maximum thickness }
\end{aligned}
$$


An iron membrane with a thickness between 0.013 and 0.073 cm will be satisfactory.

Based on the description of the sample, $w=0.5$ in., $h=0.375$ in., and $L=5$ in. From Equation (Flexural strength for three-point bend test $\sigma_{\text {bend }}=\frac{3 F L}{2 w h^2}$):

$$\begin{aligned}
45,000 \mathrm{psi} = \frac{3FL}{2wh^2} & = \frac{(3)(F)(5 \mathrm{in.})}{(2)(0.5 \mathrm{in.})(0.375 \mathrm{in.})^2} = 106.7 \mathrm{~F} \\
F & = \frac{45,000}{106.7} = 422 \mathrm{lb}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the deflection, from Equation (Flexural modulus $E_{\text {bend }}=\frac{L^3 F}{4 w h^3 \delta}$), is

$$\begin{aligned}
18 \times 10^6 \mathrm{psi} & = \frac{L^3F}{4wh^3\delta} = \frac{(5 \mathrm{in.})^3(422 \mathrm{lb})}{(4)(0.5 \mathrm{in.})(0.375 \mathrm{in.})^3\delta} \\
\delta & = 0.0278 \mathrm{in.}
\end{aligned}$$

In this calculation, we assumed a linear relationship between stress and strain and also that there is no viscoelastic behavior.

To design our manufacturing and testing capability, we must determine the maximum size of any flaws that might lead to failure within the 10 year period. The critical crack size using the fracture toughness and the maximum stress is

$$
\begin{gathered}
K_{I c}=f \sigma \sqrt{\pi a_{c}} \\
80 \mathrm{MPa} \sqrt{\mathrm{~m}}=(1.0)(500 \mathrm{MPa}) \sqrt{\pi a_{c}} \\
a_{c}=0.0081 \mathrm{~m}=8.1 \mathrm{~mm}
\end{gathered}
$$

The maximum stress is 500 MPa; however, the minimum stress is zero, not 60 MPa in compression, because cracks do not propagate in compression. Thus, $\Delta \sigma$ is

$$
\Delta \sigma=\sigma_{\max }-\sigma_{\min }=500-0=500 \mathrm{MPa}
$$

We need to determine the minimum number of cycles that the plate must withstand:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& N=(1 \text { cycle } / 5 \mathrm{~min})(60 \mathrm{~min} / h)(24 \mathrm{~h} / d)(365 \mathrm{~d} / \mathrm{y})(10 \mathrm{y}) \\
& N=1,051,200 \text { cycles }
\end{aligned}
$$

If we assume that $f=1.0$ for all crack lengths and note that $C=1.62 \times 10^{-12}$ and $n=3.2$ from Figure in Equation ($N=\frac{2\left[\left(a_c\right)^{(2-n) / 2}-\left(a_i\right)^{(2-n) / 2}\right]}{(2-n) C f^n \Delta \sigma^n \pi^{n / 2}}$), then

$$
\begin{gathered}
1,051,200=\frac{2\left[(0.008)^{(2-3.2) / 2}-\left(a_{i}\right)^{(2-3.2) / 2}\right]}{(2-3.2)\left(1.62 \times 10^{-12}\right)(1)^{3.2}(500)^{3.2} \pi^{3.2 / 2}} \\
1,051,200=\frac{2\left[18-a_{i}^{0.6}\right]}{(-1.2)\left(1.62 \times 10^{-12}\right)(1)\left(4.332 \times 10^{8}\right)(6.244)} \\
a_{i}^{-0.6}=18+2764=2782 \\
a_{i}=1.82 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}=0.00182 \mathrm{~mm} \text { for surface flaws } \\
2 a_{i}=0.00364 \mathrm{~mm} \text { for internal flaws }
\end{gathered}
$$

The manufacturing process must produce surface flaws smaller than 0.00182 mm in length. In addition, nondestructive tests must be available to ensure that cracks approaching this length are not present.

question:
Calculate the size of the critical radius and the number of atoms in the critical nucleus when solid copper forms by homogeneous nucleation. Comment on the size of the nucleus and assumptions we made while deriving the equation for the radius of the nucleus. Give your answer as a tuple: (critical_radius_cm, number_of_atoms).

For Cu, 
$$ 
\begin{aligned} 
\Delta T & =236^{\circ} \mathrm{C} \quad T_{m}=1085+273=1358 \mathrm{~K} \\ 
\Delta H_{f} & =1628 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\ 
\sigma_{s l} & =177 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{cm}^{2} 
\end{aligned} 
$$ .

The lattice parameter for FCC copper is $a_0=0.3615 \mathrm{~nm}$

solution:
From the given measurements, we can determine the constants $k_{\text{solidification}}$ and $c_{1}$ in the equation $d = k_{\text{solidification}} \sqrt{t} - c_{1}$:

$$
\begin{gathered}
0.5 \mathrm{in.} =k_{\text{solidification}} \sqrt{(5 \mathrm{~min})}-c_{1} \text { or } c_{1}=k \sqrt{5}-0.5 \\
1.5 \mathrm{in.} =k_{\text{solidification}} \sqrt{(20 \mathrm{~min})}-c_{1}=k \sqrt{20}-(k \sqrt{5}-0.5) \\
1.5=k_{\text{solidification}}(\sqrt{20}-\sqrt{5})+0.5 \\
k_{\text{solidification}}=\frac{1.5-0.5}{4.472-2.236}=0.447 \frac{\mathrm{in.}}{\sqrt{\min }} \\
c_{1}=(0.447) \sqrt{5}-0.5=0.5 \mathrm{in.}
\end{gathered}
$$

Solidification is complete when $d=2 \mathrm{in.}$ (half the diameter, since freezing is occurring from all surfaces):

$$
\begin{aligned}
2 & =0.447 \sqrt{t}-0.5 \\
\sqrt{t} & =\frac{2+0.5}{0.447}=5.59 \\
t & =31.25 \mathrm{~min}
\end{aligned}
$$

In actual practice, the total solidification time would be somewhat longer than 31.25 min due to the mold becoming hotter and less effective in removing heat from the casting as solidification continues.

This is a hypoeutectic composition. Therefore, the microconstituents expected are primary $\alpha$ and eutectic. Note that we still have only two phases ($\alpha$ and $\beta$). We can determine the amounts and compositions of the microconstituents if we look at how they form. The primary $\alpha$ microconstituent is all of the solid $\alpha$ that forms before the alloy cools to the eutectic temperature; the eutectic microconstituent is all of the liquid that goes through the eutectic reaction. At a temperature just above the eutectic - say, $184^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$-the amounts and compositions of the two phases are

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha: 19 \% \mathrm{Sn}, \% \alpha & =\frac{61.9-30}{61.9-19} \times 100=74 \%=\% \text { primary } \alpha \\
L: 61.9 \% \mathrm{Sn}, \% L & =\frac{30-19}{61.9-19} \times 100=26 \%=\% \text { eutectic at } 182^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, the primary alpha microconstituent is obtained by determining the amount of $\alpha$ present at the temperature just above the eutectic. The amount of eutectic microconstituent at a temperature just below the eutectic (e.g., $182^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$) is determined by calculating the amount of liquid just above the eutectic temperature (e.g., at $184^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$), since all of this liquid of eutectic composition is transformed into the eutectic microconstituent. Note that at the eutectic temperature ($183^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$), the eutectic reaction is in progress (formation of the proeutectic $\alpha$ is complete); hence, the amount of the eutectic microconstituent at $183^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ will change with time (starting at $0 \%$ and ending at $26 \%$ eutectic, in this case). Please be certain that you understand this example since many students tend to miss how the calculation is performed.

When the alloy cools below the eutectic to $182^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, all of the liquid at $184^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ transforms to eutectic and the composition of the eutectic microconstituent is $61.9 \%$ Sn. The solid $\alpha$ present at $184^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ remains unchanged after cooling to $182^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and is the primary microconstituent.

The molecular weights of hexamethylene diamine, adipic acid, and water are 116, 146, and $18 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}$, respectively. The number of moles of hexamethylene diamine is equal to the number of moles of adipic acid:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1000 \mathrm{~g}}{116 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} & =8.62 \text { moles }=\frac{x \mathrm{~g}}{146 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol}} \\
x & =1259 \mathrm{~g} \text { of adipic acid required }
\end{aligned}
$$

One water molecule is lost when hexamethylene diamine reacts with adipic acid. Each time a monomer is added to the chain, one molecule of water is lost. Thus, when a long chain forms, there are (on average) two water molecules released for each repeat unit of the chain (each repeat unit being formed from two monomers). Thus, the number of moles of water lost is $2(8.62$ moles $)=17.24$ moles or

$$
17.24 \text { moles } \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}(18 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{mol})=310 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}
$$

The total amount of nylon produced is

$$
1000 \mathrm{~g}+1259 \mathrm{~g}-310 \mathrm{~g}=1949 \mathrm{~g}
$$

Although the strain on the elastomer band may be constant, the stress will decrease over time due to stress relaxation. We can use Equation ($\sigma=\sigma_0 \exp (-t / \lambda)$) and our initial tests to determine the relaxation time for the polymer:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma & =\sigma_0 \exp \left(-\frac{t}{\lambda}\right) \\
980 & =1000 \exp \left(-\frac{6}{\lambda}\right) \\
-\frac{6}{\lambda} & =\ln \left(\frac{980}{1000}\right)=\ln (0.98)=-0.0202 \\
\lambda & =\frac{6}{0.0202}=297 \text { weeks }
\end{aligned}
$$


Now that we know the relaxation time, we can determine the stress that must be initially placed onto the band so that it will still be stressed to 1500 psi after 1 year ( 52 weeks).

$$
\begin{gathered}
1500=\sigma_0 \exp (-52 / 297)=\sigma_0 \exp (-0.1751)=0.8394 \sigma_0 \\
\sigma_0=\frac{1500}{0.8394}=1787 \mathrm{psi}
\end{gathered}
$$


The polyisoprene band must be made significantly undersized so it can slip over the materials it is holding together with a tension of 1787 psi. After one year, the stress will still be 1500 psi .

From Figure, a volume fraction of clay below 0.35 is required to maintain a tensile strength greater than 3000 psi, whereas a volume fraction of at least 0.2 is needed for the minimum modulus of elasticity. For lowest cost, we use the maximum allowable clay, or a volume fraction of 0.35. In $1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of composite parts, there are $350 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of clay and $650 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of polyethylene in the composite, or 

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\left(350 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)\left(2.4 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)}{454 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}}=1.85 \mathrm{lb} \text { clay } \\
& \frac{\left(650 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}\right)\left(0.95 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}\right)}{454 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{lb}}=1.36 \mathrm{lb} \text { polyethylene }
\end{aligned}
$$

The cost of materials is

$$
\begin{aligned}
(1.85 \mathrm{lb} \text { clay })(\$ 0.05 / \mathrm{lb}) & =\$ 0.0925 \\
(1.36 \mathrm{lb} \mathrm{PE})(\$ 0.50 / \mathrm{lb}) & =\$ 0.68 \\
\text { total } & =\$ 0.7725 \text { per } 1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Suppose that weight is critical. The composite's density is

$$
\rho_{c}=(0.35)(2.4)+(0.65)(0.95)=1.46 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
$$

We may wish to sacrifice some of the economic savings in order to obtain lighter weight. If we use only 0.2 volume fraction clay, then (using the same method as above) we find that we need 1.06 lb clay and 1.67 lb polyethylene. The cost of materials is now

$$
\begin{aligned}
(1.06 \mathrm{lb} \text { clay })(\$ 0.05 / \mathrm{lb}) & =\$ 0.053 \\
(1.67 \mathrm{lb} \mathrm{PE})(\$ 0.50 / \mathrm{lb}) & =\$ 0.835 \\
\text { total } & =\$ 0.89 \text { per } 1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

The density of the composite is

$$
\rho_{c}=(0.2)(2.4)+(0.8)(0.95)=1.24 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}
$$

The material costs about $15 \%$ more, but there is a weight savings of $15 \%$.

From the rule of mixtures:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\rho_{c} & =(0.6)(2.7)+(0.4)(2.36)=2.56 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
E_{c, \mathrm{~g}} & =(0.6)\left(10 \times 10^{6}\right)+(0.4)\left(55 \times 10^{6}\right)=28 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{psi} \\
T S_{c} & =(0.6)(5,000)+(0.4)(400,000)=163,000 \mathrm{psi}
\end{aligned}
$$

Note that the tensile strength calculation is only an approximation. Perpendicular to the fibers:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1}{E_{c, \perp}}=\frac{0.6}{10 \times 10^{6}}+\frac{0.4}{55 \times 10^{6}}=0.06727 \times 10^{-6} \\
& E_{c, \perp}=14.9 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{psi}
\end{aligned}
$$

One method by which we can calculate the concrete mix is to first determine the volume of each constituent based on one sack ( 94 lb ) of cement. We should remember that after the concrete is poured, there are no void spaces between the various constituents; therefore, we need to consider the true density-not the bulk density-of the constituents in our calculations.

For each sack of cement we use, the volume of materials required is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Cement } & =\frac{94 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{sack}}{190 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{ft}^3}=0.495 \mathrm{ft}^3 \\
\text { Sand } & =\frac{2.5 \times 94 \mathrm{lb} \text { cement }}{160 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{ft}^3}=1.469 \mathrm{ft}^3 \\
\text { Gravel } & =\frac{4 \times 94 \mathrm{lb} \text { cement }}{170 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{ft}^3}=2.212 \mathrm{ft}^3 \\
\text { Water } & =\frac{0.4 \times 94 \mathrm{lb} \text { cement }}{62.4 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{ft}^3}=0.603 \mathrm{ft}^3
\end{aligned}
$$


Total volume of concrete $=4.78 \mathrm{ft}^3 / \mathrm{sack}$ of cement
Therefore, in 5 cubic yards (or $135 \mathrm{ft}^3$ ), we need

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Cement } & =\frac{135 \mathrm{ft}^3}{4.78 \mathrm{ft}^3 / \mathrm{sack}}=28 \text { sacks } \\
\text { Sand } & =(28 \text { sacks })(94 \mathrm{lb} / \text { sack })(2.5 \text { sand } / \text { cement })=6580 \mathrm{lb} \\
\text { Gravel } & =(28 \text { sacks })(94 \mathrm{lb} / \text { sack })(4 \text { gravel } / \text { cement })=10,528 \mathrm{lb} \\
\text { Water } & =(28 \text { sacks })(94 \mathrm{lb} / \text { sack })(0.4 \text { water } / \text { cement })=1053 \mathrm{lb}
\end{aligned}
$$


The sand contains $4 \%$ water and the gravel contains $1 \%$ water. To obtain the weight of the wet sand and gravel, we must adjust for the water content of each:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Sand } & =(6580 \text { dry }) / 0.96=6854 \mathrm{lb} \text { and water }=274 \mathrm{lb} \\
\text { Gravel } & =(10,528 \text { dry }) / 0.99=10,634 \mathrm{lb} \text { and water }=106 \mathrm{lb}
\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, we actually only need to add:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Water } & =1053 \mathrm{lb}-274 \mathrm{lb}-106 \mathrm{lb}=673 \mathrm{lb} \\
& =\frac{(673 \mathrm{lb})\left(7.48 \mathrm{gal} / \mathrm{ft}^3\right)}{62.4 \mathrm{lb} / \mathrm{ft}^3}=81 \mathrm{gal}
\end{aligned}
$$


Accordingly, we recommend that 28 sacks of cement, 6854 lb of sand, and $10,634 \mathrm{lb}$ of gravel be combined with 81 gal of water.

(a) The valence of copper is one; therefore, the number of valence electrons equals the number of copper atoms in the material. The number of valence electrons per unit volume is calculated as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
n & =\frac{(4 \text { atoms } / \text { cell })(1 \text { electron } / \text { atom })}{\left(3.6151 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}\right)^{3}}=8.466 \times 10^{22} \text { electrons } / \mathrm{cm}^{3} \\
q & =1.6 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$

The mobility $\mu$ is then given by:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mu & =\frac{\sigma}{n q}=\frac{5.98 \times 10^{5}}{\left(8.466 \times 10^{22}\right)\left(1.6 \times 10^{-19}\right)} \\
& =44.1 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^{2}}{\Omega \cdot \mathrm{C}}=44.1 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^{2}}{\mathrm{~V} \cdot \mathrm{~s}}
\end{aligned}
$$

(b) The electric field $E$ in the wire is:

$$
E=\frac{V}{l}=\frac{10}{100}=0.1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}
