& \sigma=12.9 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{ohm}^{-1} \cdot \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

The change in resistivity of a pure metal as a function of temperature can be estimated according to

$$
\rho=\rho_{R T}\left(1+\alpha_{R} \Delta T\right)
$$

where $\rho$ is the resistivity at any temperature $T, \rho_{R T}$ is the resistivity at room temperature (i.e., $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ), $\Delta T=\left(T-T_{R T}\right)$ is the difference between the temperature of interest and room temperature, and $\alpha_{R}$ is the temperature resistivity coefficient.

From Table, $\rho=43 \Omega \cdot \mathrm{~cm}, \therefore \sigma=0.0233 \Omega^{-1} \cdot \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$
Also from Table,

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_g & =0.67 \mathrm{eV}, \mu_n=3900 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~V} \cdot \mathrm{~s}}, \mu_p=1900 \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~V} \cdot \mathrm{~s}} \\
2 \mathrm{k}_{\mathrm{B}} T & =(2)\left(8.63 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{K}\right)(273+25)=0.05143 \mathrm{eV} \text { at } T=25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{aligned}
$$

(a) From Equation($\sigma=n q \mu_n+p q \mu_p$),

$$
n=\frac{\sigma}{q\left(\mu_n+\mu_p\right)}=\frac{0.0233}{\left(1.6 \times 10^{-19}\right)(3900+1900)}=2.51 \times 10^{13} \frac{\text { electrons }}{\mathrm{cm}^3}
$$


There are $2.51 \times 10^{13}$ electrons $/ \mathrm{cm}^3$ and $2.51 \times 10^{13}$ holes $/ \mathrm{cm}^3$ conducting charge in germanium at room temperature.
(b) The lattice parameter of diamond cubic germanium is $5.6575 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}$.

The total number of electrons in the valence band of germanium at 0 K is

