(a) The capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor is given by

$$
C=\frac{\mathrm{k} \varepsilon_{0} A}{t}
$$

Thus, the capacitance per layer will be

$$
\begin{gathered}
C_{\text {layer }}=\frac{(3000)\left(8.85 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{m}\right)\left(10 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)\left(5 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m}\right)}{10 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~m}} \\
C_{\text {layer }}=13.28 \times 10^{-8}
\end{gathered}
$$

We have 100 layers connected in parallel. Capacitances add in this arrangement. All layers have the same geometric dimensions in this case.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& C_{\text {total }}=(\text { number of layers }) \cdot(\text { capacitance per layer }) \\
& C_{\text {total }}=(100)\left(13.28 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~F}\right)=13.28 \mu \mathrm{~F}
\end{aligned}
$$

Based on the unpaired electronic spins, we expect each iron atom to have four electrons that act as magnetic dipoles. The number of atoms per $\mathrm{m}^{3}$ in BCC iron is

$$
\text { Number of Fe atoms } / \mathrm{m}^{3}=\frac{2 \text { atoms } / \text { cell }}{\left(2.866 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~m}\right)^{3}}=8.496 \times 10^{28}
$$

The maximum volume magnetization $\left(M_{\text {sat }}\right)$ is the total magnetic moment per unit volume:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& M_{\text {sat }}=\left(8.496 \times 10^{28} \frac{\text { atoms }}{\mathrm{m}^{3}}\right)\left(9.274 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~A} \cdot \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)\left(4 \frac{\text { Bohr magnetons }}{\text { atom }}\right) \\
& M_{\text {sat }}=3.15 \times 10^{6} \frac{\mathrm{~A}}{\mathrm{~m}}
\end{aligned}
$$

To convert the value of saturation magnetization $M$ into saturation flux density $B$ in tesla, we need the value of $\mu_{0} M$. In ferromagnetic materials $\mu_{0} M \gg \mu_{0} H$ and therefore, $B \cong \mu_{0} M$.

Thus, the saturation induction or saturation flux density in tesla is given by $B_{\text {sat }}=\mu_{0} M_{\text {sat }}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& B_{\text {sat }}=\left(4 \pi \times 10^{-7} \frac{\mathrm{~Wb}}{\mathrm{~A} \cdot \mathrm{~m}}\right)\left(3.15 \times 10^{6} \frac{\mathrm{~A}}{\mathrm{~m}}\right) \\
& B_{\text {sat }}=3.96 \frac{\mathrm{~Wb}}{\mathrm{~m}^{2}}=3.96 \text { tesla }
\end{aligned}
$$

This is almost two times the experimentally observed value of 2.1 tesla. Reversing our calculations, we can show that the each iron atom contributes only about 2.1 Bohr magneton and not 4 . This is the difference between behavior of individual atoms and their behavior in a crystalline solid. It can be shown that in the case of iron, the difference is due to the $3 d$ electron orbital moment being quenched in the crystal.

As noted before, the attractive force from a permanent magnet is given by

$$
F=\frac{\mu_0 M^2 A}{2}
$$


We have been given the value of $\mu_0 M=1.61$ tesla. We can rewrite the equation that provides the force due to a permanent magnet as follows:

$$
\begin{gathered}
F=\frac{\mu_0 M^2 A}{2}=\frac{\left(\mu_0 M\right)^2 A}{2 \mu_0} \\
\therefore \frac{F}{A}=\frac{(1.61 \mathrm{~T})^2}{2\left(4 \pi \times 10^{-7} \frac{\mathrm{H}}{\mathrm{~m}}\right)}=1031.4 \frac{\mathrm{kN}}{\mathrm{~m}^2}
\end{gathered}
$$


Note that the force in this case will be 1031 kN since the area $(A)$ has been specified as $1 \mathrm{~m}^2$.

Assuming that no losses are caused by the reflection of x-rays from the aluminum, we simply need to choose the thickness of the aluminum required to transmit $95 \%$ of the incident intensity. The final intensity will therefore be $0.95 I_{0}$. Thus, from Equation ($I=I_0 \exp (-\alpha x)$),

$$
\begin{aligned}
\ln \left(\frac{0.95 I_{0}}{I_{0}}\right) & =-(108)(x) \\
\ln (0.95) & =-0.051=-108 x \\
x & =\frac{-0.051}{-108}=0.00047 \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

We would like to roll the aluminum to a thickness of 0.00047 cm or less. The filter could be thicker if a material were selected that has a lower linear absorption coefficient for zinc $K_{\alpha} \mathrm{x}$-rays.

The specific heat of tungsten is $0.032 \frac{\mathrm{cal}}{\mathrm{g} \cdot \mathrm{K}}$. Thus, the heat required can be calculated using the formula:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Heat required } & =(\text { specific heat })(\text { mass })(\Delta T) \\
& =(0.032 \mathrm{cal} / \mathrm{g} \cdot \mathrm{~K})(250 \mathrm{~g})(650-25) \\
& =5000 \mathrm{cal}
\end{aligned}
$$

If no losses occur, 5000 cal (or $20,920 \mathrm{~J}$ ) must be supplied to the tungsten. A variety of processes might be used to heat the metal. We could use a gas torch, we could place the tungsten in an induction coil to induce eddy currents, we could pass an electrical current through the metal, or we could place the metal into an oven heated by SiC resistors.

Because the enamel is bonded to the 1020 steel, it is essentially restrained. If only the enamel was heated (and the steel remained at a constant temperature), the maximum temperature change would be

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sigma_{\text {thermal }}=\alpha E \Delta T=\sigma_{\text {fracture }} \\
\left(10 \times 10^{\left.-6^{\circ} \mathrm{C}^{-1}\right)\left(15 \times 10^6 \mathrm{psi}\right) \Delta T=4000 \mathrm{psi}}\right. \\
\Delta T=26.7^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{gathered}
$$


The steel also expands, thereby permitting a larger temperature increase prior to fracture. Its coefficient of thermal expansion is $12 \times 10^{-6}{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}^{-1}$, and its modulus of elasticity is $30 \times 10^6 \mathrm{psi}$. Since the steel expands more than the enamel, a stress is still introduced into the enamel. The net coefficient of expansion is

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta \alpha=12 \times 10^{-6}-10 \times 10^{-6}=2 \times 10^{-6^{\circ}} \mathrm{C}^{-1} \\
\sigma=\left(2 \times 10^{-6}\right)\left(15 \times 10^6\right) \Delta T=4000 \\
\Delta T=133^{\circ} \mathrm{C}
\end{gathered}
$$


In order to permit greater temperature variations, we might select an enamel that has a higher coefficient of thermal expansion, an enamel that has a lower modulus of elasticity (so that greater strains can be permitted before the stress reaches the fracture stress), or an enamel that has a higher strength.

