Assuming that the sheet oxidizes from both sides:

$$
\begin{aligned}
y & =\sqrt{\mathrm{k} t}=\sqrt{\left(3.9 \times 10^{-12} \frac{\mathrm{~cm}^2}{\mathrm{~s}}\right)}(t)=\frac{0.1 \mathrm{~cm}}{2 \text { sides }}=0.05 \mathrm{~cm} \\
t & =\frac{(0.05 \mathrm{~cm})^2}{3.9 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{~cm}^2 / \mathrm{s}}=6.4 \times 10^8 \mathrm{~s}=20.3 \text { years }
\end{aligned}
$$


Temperature also affects the rate of oxidation. In many metals, the rate of oxidation is controlled by the rate of diffusion of oxygen or metal ions through the oxide. If oxygen diffusion is more rapid, oxidation occurs between the oxide and the metal; if the metal ion diffusion is more rapid, oxidation occurs at the oxide-atmosphere interface. Consequently, we expect oxidation rates to follow an Arrhenius relationship, increasing exponentially as the temperature increases.

